<FIRST>u w AM-SouthAfrica-Missiles 2ndLd-Writethru   10-26 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Missiles, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0849,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say South Africa Tested Missile Built With Israeli Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 3-4: ``Responding to,'' with material inserted
in earlier 1st Ld a0757 and dropped from a0849</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa has test-fired an
intermediate-range ballistic missile that couldcarry nuclear
warheads and was built with help from Israel, a U.S. official said
Thursday.
   Israel and South Africa are also cooperating in the development
of a long-range missile that could be used to launch reconnaissance
satellites into space, said the official, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   Responding to reports about the nuclear cooperation, the State
Department urged Israel to sign the international Nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty, which it has refused to do for fear of
opening its facilities to international inspection.
   ``We have repeatedly urged Israel and other non-signatories'' to
join in the pact, said a statement issued late Thursday. ``We
reiterate that call.''
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir denied Thursday that his
government had provided South Africa with the technology for a
nuclear-capable missile. South Africa's foreign minister, Pik
Botha, said, ``I bear no knowledge whatsoever of such cooperation.''
   Israel's Defense Ministry spokesman, Eitan Haber, said his
country is adhering to a 1987 decision that no new defense
contracts between Israel and South Africa be signed. But Israel
also has said existing contracts would be honored.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said, ``We don't
have any direct knowledge that we can comment on at this time ...
We are looking into it.''
   The State Department and the Pentagon refused to discuss the
matter. ``We do not comment on intelligence matters. The U.S.
policy of opposition to the proliferation of missiles and nuclear
weapons is well known,'' said State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler.
   ``Our ambassador in Israel has discussed similar reports in the
overall question of proliferation on a number of occasions with
Israel's Ministry of Defense,'' she said.
   The U.S. official said intelligence reports said South Africa
last summer tested a modified version of the Israeli-made Jericho
II medium-range missile at Armaston, on the Indian Ocean coast near
Capetown.
   The Washington Post, citing unidentified ``informed official,''
said in Friday editions the U.S. ambassador was ``stiffed'' and
told ``it was none of our business'' when he raised the missile
issue in January.
   NBC-TV, citing unidentified intelligence sources and a CIA
document, reported Wednesday that South Africa was providing
Israel, in return, with enriched uranium for its own nuclear
warheads. Neither country has admitted to having nuclear weapons.
   The South African missile, test-fired over the Indian Ocean,
flew 900 miles, its maximum range, said the official.
   Israel test-fired its own Jericho II missile about 500 miles
over the Mediterranean last year, he said.
   A long-range version of the Jericho, known as the Shavit _
Hebrew for comet _ was used to launch an Israeli
photo-reconnaissance satellite earlier this year from a site in the
Negev Desert, the official said. Press reports at the time
described the rocket as a multi-stage missile having a 2,000-mile
range.
   NBC identified South Africa's long-range test site as Overberg,
saying Israeli experts would be given a chance to monitor testing
at that site.
