<FIRST>r a PM-FlippenAppointment     10-26 0122</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flippen Appointment,0125</SECOND>
<HEAD>Named AP Buffalo Correspondent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alan Flippen, a newsman in the Providence,
R.I., bureau of The Associated Press, has been named AP
correspondent in charge at Buffalo.
   The appointment was announced Wednesday by Albany chief of
Bureau Lew Wheaton.
   Flippen, 25, joined the AP in Louisville in 1986. He also worked
in the Indianapolis bureau before transferring to Providence in
1987.
   Flippen is a native of Wilmington, Del., and a graduate of
Princeton University. He holds a master's degree in journalism from
Columbia University and began his journalism career at WNRK Radio
in Newark, Del.
   In Buffalo he succeeds Darren Dopp, who resigned to become a
deputy press secretary to New York Gov. Mario Cuomo.
</TEXT>
