<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Analysis     10-26 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Analysis,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon Accord Opens Door to Peace, But Move Remains Fragile</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The peace accord worked out by in Taif,
Saudi Arabia, is the most serious Arab attempt to end Lebanon's 14
years of sectarian civil war, but making it work is another matter.
   Lebanese legislators and Arab League mediators, who met in the
Saudi resort for three weeks, achieved what was unthinkable a few
weeks ago in a country that has had rival Christian and Moslem
governments since September 1988.
   The plan is the first to provide a framework for political
reforms designed to share power equally between the traditionally
dominant Christians and Moslems, now an estimated 55 percent of
Lebanon's 4 million people.
   It is a fragile structure, however, because it does not resolve
the political frustrations of militia leaders on both sides, who
were not represented at Taif. The accord also lacks a concrete plan
for withdrawal of Syria's 40,000 soldiers stationed in Lebanon,
which Christians demand.
   Vagueness about withdrawal clearly leaves Syria with a role in
Lebanon, where it is the main power broker. The agreement notes,
somewhat disingenuously given Syrian control of 70 percent of the
country, that Syria ``will not permit any act that threatens
Lebanon's security, independence or sovereignty.''
   Arab and foreign pressure may force militia leaders to accept
the accord, which Lebanon's war-weary people hope will end a war
that taken more than 150,000 lives and displaced one-fourth of the
population, but there are many pitfalls.
   Deeply embedded distrust on both sides and rivalries of Syria,
Israel, Iraq, Iran and Libya played out in Lebanon could wreck the
plan as they did peace efforts in 1983, 1984 and 1985.
   ``Reaching agreement in Taif is likely to be child's play in
comparison to putting that agreement into effect in Lebanon,''
analyst Charles Snow wrote in the respected Middle East Economic
Survey.
   The Taif accord reduces the dominant role of Maronite Catholics,
the main Christian sect, in the government and Parliament and gives
Moslems more power than they have had since independence from
France in 1943.
   It envisages a government of national reconcilitiation that will
restore central authority and election of a president acceptable to
all sides.
   Nabih Berri, leader of the Shiite Moslem militia Amal, says the
agreement does not give the 1.2 million Shiites, the largest sect
in Lebanon, a share of power commensurate with their numbers.
   Walid Jumblatt, the Druse Moslem chieftain, voiced grudging
acceptance to support his Syrian allies, but clearly is far from
happy with it. The Druse, a mystical offshoot of Islam long hostile
to the Christians, form only 6 percent of the population and fear
for their survival.
   For Maronites led the army commander, Gen. Michel Aoun, the
major flaw in the agreement is its failure to be specific about
Syrian withdrawal.
   Aoun considers Syria an occupying power. Ironically, the Syrians
moved into Lebanon in April 1976 to help save the Christians from
being overwhelmed by an alliance of leftists, Moslems and
Palestinians.
   Syria feared the leftists and Palestinians would control a
radical state on its vulnerable western flank and precipitate an
Israeli invasion, which came to pass in 1982.
   Later in 1976, the Arab League conferred some legality on the
Syrian action by giving it a peacekeeping mandate.
   In the kaledeiscope of changing alliances in Lebanon, the
Syrians soon found themselves fighting the Christians. Aoun says
Syria has violated the Arab League mandate by openly siding with
the Moslems.
   In March, he began a ``war of liberation'' against the Syrians
that involved some of the most ferocious artillery battles of the
war. More than 900 people were killed and nearly 3,000 wounded,
nearly all of them civilians.
   Outgunned and outnumbered, he gambled that outside powers would
compel Syria to withdraw, but Western powers were wary of the
Lebanese quagmire and stayed aloof. Aoun was left isolated, with
little choice but to accept an Arab League cease-fire on Sept. 22.
   George Saadeh, leader of the right-wing Phalange Party, and
other Maronite legislators defied Aoun's demand that they refuse
concessions at Taif until they had guarantees of Syrian withdrawal.
   ``Aoun sees himself as a national savior, a man with a
mission,'' a Lebanese analyst said privately. ``That makes him
dangerous. He's taking on everyone in sight, but he can't stand
alone against the whole Arab world and the international
community.''
   Samir Geagea, leader of the main Christian militia, and Maronite
Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir have endorsed the Taif agreement, causing
speculation about Aoun's continued control of the Christian
government and army.
   Syria, as in the past, has linked its departure to Israeli
withdrawal from the ``security zone'' it maintains just inside
south Lebanon. Israel cites the presence of guerrillas in the area
as a security threat and shows no signs of leaving.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ed Blanche is Middle East news editor of The
Associated Press, formerly based in Beirut and now in Nicosia.
</TEXT>
