<FIRST>r p PM-CelebrityCandidate     10-26 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Celebrity Candidate,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Beverly Hills Cop' Appearances Helping City Council Candidate</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN DESMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Cmdr. Gilbert Hill, who appeared as Eddie
Murphy's foul-mouthed, short-tempered boss in the ``Beverly Hills
Cop'' movies, pauses to sign autographs while he stumps for a City
Council seat.
   ``Absolutely it's helped, and I don't apologize for it,'' Hill
said of the name recognition. ``But behind the name, my community
record stands up to anybody's. I'm a longtime resident and a police
officer for 32 years.''
   He finished fourth in September's primary _ highest among
non-incumbents. Recent polls show him second among the 18
candidates for nine council seats. The top vote-getter in the Nov.
7 election will automatically be council president.
   Hill's appearances in ``Beverly Hills Cop'' stalled his police
career. In February 1986, he was moved from the Homicide Section,
which he had headed for five years, to run the department's
lesser-known Patrol Support Division. A week after the transfer, he
took a leave for ``Beverly Hills Cop II.''
   ``I'm going to retire from the police department when I win,''
Hill said Wednesday.
   Hill said he sensed jealously from people in Detroit after his
face appeared on the big screen.
   ``I never got caught up in the fame,'' he said. ``Anyone who
knows me knows I didn't change. The only change is that I spent
more time giving of myself.''
   Hill said Mayor Coleman Young and Police Chief William Hart
encouraged him to run for City Council but cautioned him against
campaigning during work hours.
   ``I only campaign after 4 p.m. and Saturdays and Sundays,'' said
Hill.
   He said he doesn't have a fiery temper and sharp tongue like his
character in both ``Beverly Hills Cop'' movies.
   ``You can't do that in real life,'' Hill said. ``These guys have
real guns. You have to be extremely careful.''
   Hill won't give up his acting career. He's awaiting an
announcement for a third ``Beverly Hills Cop'' movie.
   ``I pray for it everyday,'' he said.
</TEXT>
