<DOCNO> AP891026-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0258EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AtticaVictims     10-26 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Attica Victims,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Awards $1.3 Million to Victims of Attica Prison Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than $800,000 has been awarded to the
widows of two men slain in the bloody police assault on Attica
state prison, but their lawyer says vindication is the sweetest
product of the 18-year-old case.
   Judge Donald Corbett on Wednesday awarded $1.3 million in
damages to seven former Attica inmates or their survivors, saying
the men ``neither participated in the uprising nor resisted in the
retaking'' of the prison by state police.
   The police assault on the prison on Sept. 13, 1971, was
described by an investigating commission as the ``bloodiest
encounter between Americans since the Civil War.''
   Brenda West of Buffalo and Sara Gray of Rochester, whose
husbands were shot to death in the assault, were awarded $475,000
and $385,000, respectively.
   ``They have felt for many years that their husbands had to be
vindicated in some way,'' said their attorney, James Hagerty. ``The
money is very nice, of course, but they feel very good about the
vindication.''
   Hagerty said he would seek interest accruing over 18 years that
would bring the awards for both women to more than $1 million.
   Mrs. West declined to be interviewed on Wednesday, and Mrs. Gray
couldn't be reached for comment.
   More than 1,200 inmates took control of the maximum-security
prison near Buffalo for four days, holding guards and civilians
hostage. The police assault left 39 inmates and employees dead and
80 injured. Four people had died earlier during the prison takeover.
   Three of the seven inmates covered in the lawsuit were killed in
the 10 minutes of police gunfire on inmates. Two others have since
died of unrelated causes and two are still alive.
   Corbett said the state was liable for damages for injuries
``resulting from the intentional use of excessive force.''
   The state will appeal, said James Flateau, spokesman for the
state Criminal Justice director.
   The awards ranged from $35,000 to $475,000, depending on the
inmates' pain and suffering, their families' loss of money based on
their future employment prospects and disfigurement, Corbett said.
   In talks with state authorities during and after the uprising,
inmates objected to what they called degrading conditions at
Attica. They said they'd been locked in their cells 13 hours a day,
were allowed only one shower a week and never knew how their mail
would be censored or if it would be withheld entirely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-KennedyCenter     10-26 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kennedy Center,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davidson Quitting in 1991 as Kennedy Center Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing
Arts is looking for a successor to Chairman Ralph P. Davidson, who
plans to quit in early 1991 over unspecified differences with the
center's board of trustees.
   Davidson's announcement Wednesday followed recurring reports
that a majority of the 45-member Kennedy Center board was
dissatisfied with the former Time Inc. executive's management style
and personality clashes.
   At a meeting Wednesday, the board accepted Davidson's advance
notice that he will resign when his three-year contract expires in
February 1991. The trustees issued a statement praising his
``dedication to the center and his many management and programming
initiatives.''
   Trustee James Evans will lead a search committee to find a
successor to Davidson, 62, who has been the $125,000-a-year
chairman and chief executive of the national arts center since
February 1988. Davidson succeeded Broadway producer Roger L.
Stevens, the center's founding chairman.
   Another trustee, former Defense Secretary Melvin Laird, will
chair a transition committee. Davidson said he hoped a successor
could be named by mid-1990.
   ``I arrived at my decision after several discussions with the
board and the realization that we had different priorities and
different expectations of each other,'' Davidson said in a separate
statement.
   ``These differences happen in institutions of all kinds and, as
regrettable as they may be, I fully understand the need for a
change for the sake of the institution,'' said Davidson, who did
not elaborate.
   Reports of growing tensions between Davidson and the trustees
surfaced after the board's last meeting in July.
   The trustees were reported to have criticized Davidson privately
for his aloof management style, arbitrary treatment of the Kennedy
Center staff and failure to attend important social functions.
   Concerns also were raised privately about financing the National
Symphony Orchestra's planned tour of the Soviet Union next
February, and about a breakdown in negotiations for bringing
British producer Duncan Weldon's staging of Shakespeare's ``Richard
II'' and ``Richard III'' to the Kennedy Center.
   There were some complaints that Davidson had failed to meet
fund-raising expectations. But the board's statement Wednesday
praised Davidson's ``efforts to create a satisfactory endowment for
the center and its affiliate, the National Symphony Orchestra.''
   The Kennedy Center receives no federal support, except for
housekeeping services by the National Park Service and occasional
programming grants from the National Endowment for the Arts. Most
of the center's $57 million annual budget is financed by ticket
sales and private contributions.
   Davidson receives $125,000 annually as chief administrator of
the Kennedy Center, the white marble cultural center alongside the
Potomac River which opened in September 1971 as the only official
memorial to President Kennedy.
   Stevens, who supervised construction of the center, served as
its first chairman without salary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lite     10-26 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lite,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Treasurer Robert Bowman got
hooked on fast food as a youthful burger flipper, and he dreams of
the day when doctors will say ``salt is good for you'' and push
saturated fat to prevent heart attacks.
   Bowman quit his job at McDonald's in 1973, but he told about 750
McDonald's assistant managers at a convention Wednesday that Big
Mac sauce will always be in his veins.
   ``I am always proud to be an `alum' of McDonald's,'' Bowman said.
   During seminars at the convention, employees were quizzed on
such matters as ``In what order should a Big Mac, fries and a soda
be presented to a customer?'' and ``What is the proper temperature
setting for cleaning the biscuit oven?''
   Winners got a variety of prizes including McDonald's stock.
   ``I'm an unabashed Number 1 frequenter of McDonald's in this
state, bar none,'' Bowman said. ``I have this dream doctors will
come back in five years and say salt is good for you, saturated fat
is the best thing to prevent a heart attack, and if you eat red
meat three times a day you're going to live to be 120.''
   Bowman was 16 when he got his first job at a McDonald's in
Brookfield, Wis., in 1971. He stayed there two years.
   ``One out of every 15 Americans get their first job at a
McDonald's,'' Bowman said. ``For people to belittle the fast-food
industry is an insult. ... No economy can be based on lawyers and
doctors.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montana has had its share of jerks over the
years _ enough, anyway, to devote a 1{-hour seminar on the more
famous among them.
   Take Calamity Jane, for instance. Idol of frontier mythology,
right?
   Not necessarily, say seminar organizers, who have titled Jane's
segment ``Calamity Jane _ Sleaze of the Frontier.''
   The seminar scheduled Friday afternoon in Helena is part of
two-day conference sponsored by the Montana Historial Society. The
seminar title is ``Speaking Ill of the Dead: Jerks in Montana
History.''
   Others being discussed include W.A. Clark, one of the notorious
``copper kings'' who dominated and corrupted Montana politics near
the turn of the century.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Joe Frank Harris was looking for a
lighthearted one-liner at his news conference, hoping to sidestep a
question about who might succeed him.
   The question Wednesday was whether he agreed with claims that
Mayor Andrew Young, a fellow Democrat and possible candidate, could
not be elected because of anti-Atlanta sentiment in the state.
   Harris replied: ``Let me just say that anyone that qualifies,
that gets his name on the ballot, can be elected governor. ... I'm
proof of that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
