<FIRST>r a PM-Names     10-26 0844</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0874</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Today'' show weatherman Willard Scott says
he's staying, but he's sure friend and colleague Jane Pauley will
be leaving the NBC-TV show on which she's been co-host for 13 years.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Scott said he talked
with Pauley after Wednesday's broadcast. She didn't specifically
say she was leaving, but left the impression of ```I'm so glad and
the decision is made,''' Scott said.
   Pauley, who turns 39 on Tuesday, reportedly has been unhappy
with changes on the program, including the Sept. 5 move of Deborah
Norville from ``NBC News at Sunrise'' to ``Today.''
   Some speculation has it that Norville eventually will succeed
Pauley as co-host of ``Today'' with Bryant Gumbel.
   Despite heavy publicity about Pauley's reported unhappiness,
Scott said, ``I would have bet the family farm that she never was
going to leave. But from what I saw today, I don't think there's
any question'' that she will.
   Pauley, whose reported discontent also includes concern that two
new layers of management will oversee the show, did not reply to a
request for comment. She previously has declined to discuss when
and if she'll leave ``Today.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having Ruth Westheimer address an education
conference on sex is like inviting Timothy Leary to speak on drugs,
a state senator says.
   Republican state Sen. James Donovan said Wednesday he's
boycotting the annual conference of the state School Boards
Association because the noted sex therapist is speaking there.
   ``I think her whole message is one that's immoral,'' the Utica
legislator said. ``There's no promotion of high moral standards.
It's `whatever feels good, do it,' notwithstanding your parents'
instruction or generally how you feel about sex outside of
marriage.''
   Westheimer laughed when reached at her New York City office for
a reaction to Donovan's statements.
   ``If issues of sexuality enter politics, that would make me very
sad,'' Westheimer said. ``I'm not a politician and I'm not a
theologian. I don't judge other people's morals. What I am is an
educator.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kelsey Grammer, who plays a psychiatrist on
NBC's ``Cheers,'' will enter a drug abuse education program to
avoid a possible prison term for cocaine possession.
   He told a Municipal Court judge Wednesday he missed a court
appearance the previous day because of confusion over dates. Judge
Aviva Bobb had withheld issuing an order for his arrest until today.
   Grammer, 34, who plays Frasier Crane on the popular sitcom, was
accused of one felony count of cocaine possession. If he
successfully completes the court-sponsored program, Grammer could
have the case dismissed and his record would be cleared. He had no
previous record.
   Police say Grammer was stopped while driving April 14 for having
an expired license plate. Officers learned he did not have a
driver's license, only a learner's permit. A computer check showed
an outstanding speeding ticket, authorities said.
   En route to the police station, he allegedly dropped a small
packet containing about a quarter-gram of cocaine on the seat of
the police car, prosecutors said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indicted Saudi financier Adnan Khashoggi won a
brief reprieve from his court-ordered confinement to his Manhattan
penthouse, gaining a judge's permission to spend two weeks in
Southern California.
   Khashoggi's trip, scheduled to begin Friday, is an exception to
travel restrictions attached to his release on $10 million bail
while he awaits a March trial on charges he helped Imelda and
Ferdinand Marcos defraud the Philippine treasury.
   While in California, Khashoggi's movements will continue to be
monitored by an electronic ankle bracelet, as ordered by U.S.
District Judge John Keenan.
   His attorney, Robert Morvillo, said Wednesday that Khashoggi's
stay in Los Angeles could be characterized as ``part business, part
pleasure.''
   He said Khashoggi would meet with one of his other attorneys to
discuss the status of certain lawsuits in which he is involved.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy ``The Greek'' Synder, who used to share
his football forecasts with TV viewers, now wants to make sure he's
paid for his picks, a lawyer for the oddsmaker says.
   The Baltimore Bulletin Inc., known as the Mike Warren Sports and
Jimmy ``The Greek'' Sports Service, filed suit in U.S. District
Court against a Reno sports information service accused of selling
Snyder's and Warren's football picks without permission.
   Their attorney, Robert Schulman, said Consensus Sports Service
is somehow getting their football picks and is serving as a
middleman to make thousands of dollars by selling the predictions
to customers.
   ``They are pirating the picks from Jimmy `The Greek' and Warren,
but we're not sure how,'' Schulman said Wednesday in a telephone
interview from his Baltimore office.
   Dave Strout, manager of the Consensus office, said the company
had no immediate comment on the suit filed Tuesday. He said Gerrard
Byrnes, founder, owner and operator of the sports information
service, was out of town and couldn't be reached for comment.
   The lawsuit seeks $100,000 in damages plus other costs.
</TEXT>
