<FIRST>r w PM-Immigration     10-26 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Immigration,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes to Defer Deporting Exiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of illegal aliens who fled civil
strife in El Salvador, Nicaragua and China could be given haven in
the United States for three years under an immigration package
approved by the House.
   The measure designed to protect as many as 750,000 exiles from
deportation was approved 258-162 on Wednesday and goes to the
Senate.
   ``These are people who need our help and we are in a position to
help them,'' Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass., said in urging support.
   The bill would suspend for three years deportation of illegal
aliens who fled El Salvador, Nicaragua and China if they were in
the United States when the measure went into effect and if they
registered within nine months.
   It also would establish a system for extending temporary status
to citizens of additional countries beset by armed conflict and
natural disaster.
   Approval came despite warnings from opponents that it would
encourage job-hungry Central Americans to come north in the guise
of political exiles.
   ``It isn't right to say to American workers that we are going to
take your job away from you and give it to people who came here to
take your job away from you in the first place,'' said Rep. Bob
Walker, R-Pa.
   Moakley noted that the measure has support from the AFL-CIO and
a number of large labor unions.
   Proponents said 70,000 Salvadorans and 30,000 Nicaraguan
civilians have been killed by civil war over the last decade and
that 10,000 democracy demonstrators have been jailed in China.
   ``I think its in our interest to have Nicaraguans and
Salvadorans living in the open rather than maintaining an
underground existence,'' Rep. Hamilton Fish, R-N.Y., told the House.
   However, Rep. Helen Bentley, R-Md., cited estimates that the
price of operating the program could reach $260 million over two
years.
   ``I can tell you that my constituents will not abide by it,''
she said.
</TEXT>
