<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-FranceWine     10-26 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-France Wine,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says American Wine Sales Boom in France</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People in France, the classic home of fine
wines, are developing a taste for American vintages, the Department
of Agriculture says.
   This country shipped 72,400 gallons of wine to France last year,
five times as much as in 1985. One reason for the increase is the
fall in the price of the dollar, which makes American wines cheaper
in France than they used to be.
   There are other reasons, too, according to Holly S. Higgins, who
recently finished an assignment as U.S. agricultural attache in
Paris.
   ``Press articles and tastings featuring U.S. wines are
popular,'' she wrote in the October issue of the department's
monthly ``AgExporter.''
   ``The food and drink press has focused on quality, the high
level of technology used in producing U.S. wines and the fact that
the United States has an excellent selection of regional wine such
as California, Washington, New York, Virginia and Texas.''
   Despite the enthusiasm of French consumers, the French
government still worries about U.S. wineries using such traditional
French names as Chablis, Champagne and Burgundy, she said. The
French consider that these geographical names belong to them.
   The U.S. government has agreed not to export wines with such
labels to France or the other 11 countries in the European Economic
Community, but the ban does not extend to American shipments to
other markets, such as Latin America or the Far East.
   Steve Burns, international marketing manager for the Wine
Institute, said he saw no difficulty about the ban.
   ``We'd rather label our wines by the variety of grape:
chardonnay or cabernet or pinot noir,'' he said in an interview.
   ``It's easier for people in a hurry. They don't have to worry
about whether the Burgundy they're looking at is the right year to
go with the kind of meal they're having. There's enough mystery in
wine already. We're trying to make it more of an everyday affair.''
   He said sales in France from California, where most American
wine is produced, were up 185 percent last year.
   According to Ms. Higgins' figures, the French favor American
reds and what the French call rose or pink wines _ now sometimes
called ``blush'' wines in this country. There was a drop last year
in sales to France of American white wines, which many Americans
favor over reds.
   The total value of U.S. wine sales to France is still small:
$1.2 million last year. France bought $182 million worth from Italy
and $95 million worth from Portugal, much of it to mix with French
wines under French labels. But in 1985 the total value of U.S. wine
sales to France was only $155,000.
   ``Prospects for greater U.S. sales in the French market are
bright,'' Ms. Higgins wrote. ``U.S. exporters can expect the French
market to expand in the future as U.S. wines gain acceptance and
find their niche in the marketplace.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
