<FIRST>r w PM-US-Lebanon     10-26 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Lebanon,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Members of Congress Plan Lebanon Trip Despite Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of Congress want to visit Lebanon
to win support for a proposal to end the country's 14-year civil
war, but the State Department is worried about their safety.
   Reps. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, and Nick Rahall, D-W.Va., want to
meet with Gen. Michel Aoun, the leader of Lebanon's predominantly
Christian army who has rejected the peace plan, according to
sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   However, the State Department has banned most travel by
Americans to Lebanon because the situation ``is so dangerous that
no U.S. citizen can be considered safe from terrorist acts.''
   Eight Americans are being held hostage by pro-Iranian radicals.
   Rahall's office said it could ``neither confirm nor deny it, for
security reasons.'' A spokesman for Ms. Oakar, Jim Belles, said he
could not obtain information about her plans.
   Ms. Oakar, who like Rahall is of Lebanese descent, tried to
visit Lebanon in August, but sources said the State Department
advised her to cancel the trip.
   U.S. passports are invalid for travel to Lebanon unless special
permission is obtained. Violation of the ban can be punishable by
imprisonment or a fine.
   The U.S. embassy was evacuated last month after Aoun made veiled
threats to take American hostages to draw attention to his fight
for expulsion of 40,000 Syrian troops.
   ``We don't oppose their talking to him (Aoun), but we can't
offer any support or help if they get in trouble,'' said one
official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Meanwhile, the White House ruled out pressuring Aoun to accept
the plan.
   ``That's ... an internal matter for Lebanon and the various
factions there to deal with,'' said presidential spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater.
   The plan adopted by Christian and Moslem legislators in
closed-door meetings in Saudi Arabia would shift political control
from the Christian minority to the Moslem majority.
   Aoun called on Lebanese lawmakers to reject the plan when it
comes up for a vote next month.
</TEXT>
