<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0247EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich-Ethics     10-26 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich-Ethics,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Faces New Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee is being asked once
more to investigate allegations against Republican Whip Newt
Gingrich.
   Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., filed additional ethics charges
Wednesday alleging the Georgia congressman violated campaign
finance and financial disclosure statutes.
   Alexander said his new charges, with 670 pages of supporting
documents, should motivate the panel to open an official
preliminary investigation.
   An independent law firm hired by the committee to look into
earlier charges against Gingrich reported last week that it had
found no reason to proceed with such an inquiry, suggesting that
the panel might be ready to drop the ethics case.
   The committee is tentatively scheduled to meet Tuesday.
   But some on the committee, formally called the Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct, say they are bothered by that
recommendation and believe an easier standard is being applied to
Gingrich than was applied to House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   Wright resigned May 31 after a long ethics probe that began when
Gingrich filed a complaint.
   Rich Galen, a Gingrich spokesman, called the new charges part of
``a personal vendetta'' by Alexander.
   Among Alexander's new charges:
   _Gingrich funneled $12,000 worth of advertising and $20,000 in
contributions to the 1986 re-election campaign of Sen. Mack
Mattingly, R-Ga., but failed to report the gifts as required by
federal election law.
   _A commercial travel agency in Florida, Marathon Travel, used
letters from Gingrich on official congressional letterhead to
solicit business. Use of a lawmaker's official position to promote
commercial ventures is against House rules.
   _Gingrich sought to influence federal agencies to help a Georgia
businessman who was a member of a partnership formed in 1977 to
underwrite a Gingrich book-writing effort. The businessman, Chester
Roush Jr., reportedly received $12 million in federal subsidies
since Gingrich was elected in 1978.
   _Gingrich failed to report the purchase of a house with his
daughter, as required on annual financial disclosure forms. The
house was bought from a longtime political supporter of Gingrich,
Alexander said.
   _A political action committee Gingrich chairs, Conservatives for
Hope and Opportunity, raised more than $217,000 to support
conservative candidates but donated only $900 to campaigns. The
rest was spent on Gingrich's travel and expenses, the complaint
charged, making the solicitation for money a ``prohibited scheme''
under the law.
</TEXT>
