<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Slides     10-26 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Slides,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landslides Threaten Earthquake Devastated Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SCZ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOMPICO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debbie Newhall's address has not changed
but the location of her mountain home has. And the killer
earthquake to blame may have even more fury to unleash.
   Landslides that already have consumed 100 homes and damaged more
than 300 now threaten hundreds more in the Santa Cruz Mountains,
just a few miles from the epicenter of the Oct. 17 quake.
   ``I'm afraid this whole area is going to go,'' said Mrs.
Newhall, whose damaged home sits on the edge of a hill. The house
moved a couple of inches during the quake, cracking its foundation
posts, separating floors from walls and destroying the fireplace.
   ``I sit here at night and listen to rain pouring down. You hear
things falling from the trees. A big stick will come down and hit
the roof. You're wondering if that'll be the straw that pushes the
house down the hill,'' she said.
   The aftershocks _ more than 4,000 _ carry a different kind of
worry. ``We sleep with one kid under one arm and one under another,
so we can jump up and run out the door,'' she said.
   Geologists worry that heavy winter rains falling into huge gaps
in the Earth created by the quake could cause landslides.
   ``The big concern is if it's going to rain, how much and how
fast?'' said Gary Griggs, a University of California, Santa Cruz,
geologist.
   ``If we have a wet winter, there's a potential for a lot of
slides,'' Wilson Scaling, chief of the federal Soil Conservation
Service, said Wednesday after touring the area by helicopter.
   ``I feel very sorry for these folks. They're kind of sitting on
a powder keg. The potential is there for something else, but
hopefully that won't occur.''
   But earthquakes and the threat of landslides won't drive some
people away from the forests of redwood, oak and pine that rest
high above the scenic coastal section.
   ``If you want the beauty of California, you have to suffer
earthquakes,'' said Kieran Reid as he replaced damaged beams under
his house. ``People in the flatland, they got the shock, too.''
   Others have surrendered. ``I want to get to lower ground,'' said
renter Carol McCabe.
   Mrs. McCabe said she's still jittery from the quake. ``I can't
spend 15 minutes in the house. It's a wonderful place to be, but I
just can't go back.''
   Seventeen-year resident Beverly Bires, the victim of a house
fire a year ago, said she's packing up and leaving for Oregon.
   ``What part of me the fire didn't scare off the earthquake did.
You stay and stay and stay. After Tuesday, I said it's over.''
</TEXT>
