<FIRST>r w PM-ToxicDumps     10-26 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toxic Dumps,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>25 Sites Added to Superfund Cleanup List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is adding
25 sites to the Superfund cleanup list, bringing the number of
toxic waste dumps scheduled for cleanup to 1,219.
   The additional sites, announced Wednesday, are in 19 states and
include two federal facilities _ the New London Submarine Base in
New London, Conn., and Ellsworth Air Force Base in Rapid City, S.D.
   Sites on the national priority list under the Superfund cleanup
program are those toxic waste sites that potentially pose the
greatest risk to health and the environment.
   Here are the 23 additional non-government sites by state:
   Alaska: Arctic Surplus, Fairbanks.
   Arkansas: Magnolia City Landfill, Magnolia; Monroe Auto
Equipment (Paragould Pit), Paragould.
   California: Industrial Waste Processing, Fresno; United
Heckathorn Co., Richmond; Western Pacific Railroad Co., Oroville.
   Delaware: Koppers Co. Inc. (Newport plant), Newport.
   Florida: Anaconda Aluminum-Milgo Electron, Miami.
   Illinois: MIG (Dewane Landfill), Belvidere.
   Minnesota: Dakhue Sanitary Landfill, Cannon Falls.
   Missouri: Westlake Landfill, Bridgeton.
   Nebraska: 10th Street Site, Columbus; the former Nebraska
Ordnance Plant, Mead.
   New Jersey: Chemical Insecticide Corp., Edison Township.
   Nevada: Carson River Mercury Site, Lyon-Churchill County.
   New York: Sealand Restoration Inc., Lisbon.
   Oklahoma: Kerr-McGee Corp. (Cushing plant), Cushing.
   Oregon: Union Pacific Railroad Tie Treat, The Dalles.
   Pennsylvania: Dublin TCE Site, Dublin Borough; Ohio River Park,
Neville Island.
   South Carolina: Para-Chem Southern Inc., Simpsonville.
   South Dakota: Williams Pipe Line Disposal Pitt, Sioux Falls.
   Wisconsin: Better Brite Chrome &amp; Zinc Shops, DePere.
</TEXT>
