<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-High-DefinitionTV     10-26 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Definition TV,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Definition TV Backers Criticize Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's ``unwillingness to take a
strong lead'' in developing a U.S. high-definition television
industry is hurting America's ability to compete overseas, HDTV
proponents say.
   More than 100 business leaders, members of Congress and
technical experts wrote to Bush on Wednesday to say they were
``deeply disturbed that the United States is failing to match
Japanese and European efforts on HDTV,'' according to the
Congressional HDTV Caucus.
   The caucus said that among those signing the letter were John
Mitchell, chairman of Motorola Corp.; Robert Noyce, head of the
Sematech computer-chip consortium; Jerry Pearlman, chief executive
officer of Zenith Corp., which has proposed a U.S. HDTV
transmission system; and Mitchell Kertzman, chairman of the
American Electronics Association, which has urged the government to
commit $1.35 billion in matching funds over five years to spur HDTV
development.
   More than 25 members of Congress signed the letter, the caucus
said.
   HDTV proponents say the new technology, which promises motion
picture-sharp images and compact disc-quality sound, could be the
``technology driver'' that could revitalize the U.S. electronics
industry and have important applications in medicine, defense and
other industries.
   But a Congressional Budget Office report in August said HDTV
claims were ``very optimistic'' and that even under the rosiest of
scenarios, HDTV sales will be small relative to other electronic
equipment markets.
   The House has appropriated $50 million development money for
next year, and the Defense Advanced Projects Agency is providing
$30 million in seed money for defense-related HDTV equipment.
   But the Bush administration otherwise has shown little
inclination to push HDTV development.
   Rep. Mel Levine, D-Calif., co-chair of the caucus, said
Wednesday that ``the Bush administration's unwillingness to take a
strong lead on HDTV seriously handicaps this nation's ability to
compete internationally.''
   ``While the Japanese and Europeans outpace our technology
efforts daily, the administration sits on the sidelines waiting for
an economic miracle to revitalize our industrial base,'' he said.
``We need an HDTV initiative today, not promises of a broader
technology program tomorrow.''
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher told Congress earlier this
year that developing a policy on HDTV was among the
administration's highest priorities, although the government didn't
plan to play ``uncle sugar'' to American industry.
   But Commerce officials last month said that outlook had changed
and the administration now was looking at HDTV only as part of a
broad-based effort to boost U.S. technological competitiveness.
   Congressional sources said then that Mosbacher was slapped down
by the White House for making statements that smacked of the
``industrial policy'' that had been advocated by Bush's Democratic
opponent, Michael Dukakis, in the 1988 presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0322EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Police     10-26 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Police,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some United Of Despised Secret Police Disbanding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an effort to regain public acceptance,
the government is disbanding units of the widely despised secret
police, reducing eavesdropping and focusing police resources on
fighting crime, commanders say.
   Many of the opposition activists the secret police had long made
a practice of watching and harassing under one-party Communist rule
became lawmakers and Cabinet ministers this year.
   Six undercover departments are being disbanded, there will be
less bugging and units that inspected foreign mail and monitored
foreign radio broadcasts will be dissolved, police officials told a
news conference.
   ``The Interior Ministry is going to strive for public acceptance
and prestige,'' said Wojciech Garstka, spokesman for the Interior
Ministry, which is in charge of the police.
   Garstka was joined by the deputy chiefs of the regular and
secret police for the unusual news conference Wednesday.
   He characterized the changes being made in the country's police
as ``perhaps the deepest in postwar history.''
   Despite Solidarity's leading role in the new government, the
Interior Ministry is still run by the Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, a
long-time Communist and confidant of President Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   Jerzy Karpacz, deputy chief of the secret police, said the
officers ``not only fully accept these changes, but are aware that
the changes are irreversible. If any are found with a different
view, they will have to leave the force.''
   The secret police long symbolized Communist control by fear.
They are bitterly remembered as the executors of Stalinist purges,
as infiltrators of opposition groups and as thugs who roughed up
activists.
   Three rogue officers and their commander from the so-called
``fourth department,'' which spied on the church, were convicted of
the 1984 kidnapping and murder of Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, a
charismatic Solidarity priest.
   The fourth department and five other units, including those
responsible for surveillance of citizens' loyalty and protection of
the agricultural, manufacturing and arms industries have been
liquidated, Garstka announced.
   Despite the changes, three new secret police units will be
formed, he said. One will guard against political extremists and
terrorists who ``do not want to become legal'' under new freedoms,
another will safeguard the economy against espionage and
disruption, and a third will analyze security information and
develop new methods, especially for crime prevention, he said.
   Also, counter-intelligence efforts will be strengthened, he said.
   More emphasis will be put on protecting public safety and
property, Garstka said, and some secret police officers will be
transferred to help combat what he said was an alarming rise in
thefts and burglaries.
   There are now about 1,250 crimes per 100,000 people annually,
which Garstka said is relatively low by Western standards. But more
car break-ins and other crimes are being reported as the economic
situation worsens and the gap between rich and poor widens.
   There are many vacancies in the police because of low pay and
low prestige, said Zbigniew Nowicki, deputy commander of the
regular police force. He said that in some Warsaw precincts, 59
percent of the positions are vacant.
   The 12,500-strong ZOMO riot police, disbanded in a highly
symbolic move Sept. 29, will be replaced by ``prevention squads''
of 5,177 officers in 22 of the 49 provinces, Garstka said. They
will be supplemented by 13,000 men serving in the police as an
alternative to mandatory military duty.
   Karpacz denied there was a special police unit to monitor
foreign journalists. But he would not answer directly whether
Western reporters' offices and homes were bugged.
   Garstka said the Interior Ministry is prepared to provide all
materials requested by a special parliament commission
investigating accusations that security forces are responsible for
more than 90 deaths.
   However, he said an internal investigation did not find ``any
role of the security service in these deaths.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
