<DOCNO> AP891026-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0308EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Warning Bjt   10-26 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Warning, Bjt,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calif. Consumers Don't Notice Warnings, But Like Information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER KERR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They're everywhere in California:
ominous signs warning consumers of some dangerous chemical that
could spread the plagues of cancer or birth defects.
   ``WARNING: Detectable amounts of chemicals known to the state to
cause cancer, birth defects or other reproductive harm may be found
in and around this facility.''
   These ubiquitous warnings were required by Proposition 65, the
environmentalist-backed ballot initiative approved three years ago.
   Industry groups say because the signs are so widespread, they
become meaningless or can create ignorant ``chemophobia.''
   But environmentalists counter that people have the right to know
what is in the products they buy, around their neighborhoods and on
their job site.
   Consumers, randomly approached while shopping, generally say
that although they don't always pay attention to the signs, they're
glad the information is there.
   ``I think it's a good idea,'' said Charles Perry, shopping
recently in a downtown Fresno drugstore. ``A lot of people buy
things just because people tell them it's good without reading
what's in it. It's best you read for yourself and see what's in a
product.''
   Proposition 65 required the governor to issue a list of
chemicals that cause cancer or reproductive harm. One year after a
chemical goes on the list, businesses must give anyone exposed to
the chemical ``clear and reasonable warning.''
   The list now has 307 chemicals and compounds. The state is
required to add chemicals to the list as new information arises.
Gov. George Deukmejian created an advisory panel to review
chemicals and recommend them for the list at least annually.
   Because the initiative did not specify how companies should warn
people, the state Health and Welfare Agency issued regulations in
February 1988 that said warnings could consist of labels on
products, signs in stores or menus of restaurants. It also called
for ``a system of signs, public advertising identifying the system
and toll-free information services.''
   The regulations exempt food, drug, cosmetic and medical-device
products regulated under state and federal safety laws.
   Consequently, consumers have not found warning labels on the
thousands of individual products in grocery stores, hardward stores
and other businesses. Instead, most stores have a general warning
near the door covering their entire products.
   Grocery Manufacturers Association spokesman Jeffrey Nedelman
said the warnings have little if any effect on consumers. He said
warnings on alcohol have not stopped people from drinking.
   His organization released a report a year ago by the Hudson
Institute, a policy research firm in Indianapolis, that concluded
the Proposition 65 warnings ``will not provide consumers with
relevant or usable information about carcinogens and reproductive
toxins.''
   The report said if food products are labeled individually,
``consumers' confusion may well undermine confidence in the federal
regulatory process and create havoc in the marketplace.''
   Scientists for the Toxics Awareness Project of the California
Business Roundtable say Proposition 65 had contributed to emotional
talk about toxics that isn't always scientifically based.
   ``People are scared, frightened, mainly because they do not
understand what makes chemicals harmful,'' said Alice Ottoboni, a
retired toxicologist for the state and a member of the project.
``Most people think if a chemical is toxic in a small amount, it is
toxic in every amount.''
   ``Labeling without informed labeling, I don't think informs the
public,'' says Allen Verstuyft of Chevron Research Co. ``Just to
tell somebody a chemical is there without education is
meaningless.''
   Paul Van Dyke of Campaign California, one of the environmental
groups backing Proposition 65, said some people won't read
anything, no matter how it's presented. But others are information
seekers, he said.
   ``These are people who need information and have a right to
it,'' he said. ``We've never seen a proliferation of warnings as
being particularly dangerous. We would rather see that left to the
individual and not have regulators censor information.''
   Pedro Mayor of Los Angeles, shopping recently at a supermarket
in Glendale, said his buying habits have changed since Proposition
65. ``If I buy grapes or apples now I make sure they are clean,
that they don't have pesticides,'' he said.
   Mayor said he has also noticed benefits from Proposition 65 at
Hughes Aircraft, where he works. ``They have a lot of warnings.
They post them all over. We use a lot of chemical coatings in
aerospace,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0044 </DOCNO>
