<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Observance Set For Captives In Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress are calling on Americans
to wear yellow ribbons and pray for hostages in Lebanon on the eve
of hostage Terry Anderson's fifth birthday in captivity.
   ``They will not and should not be forgotten,'' Senate Republican
leader Bob Dole said. ``We're asking ... that we take action to
symbolize our dedication toward winning their release.''
   President Bush has signed a congressional resolution proclaiming
Friday, Anderson's 42nd birthday, as National Hostage Awareness Day.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was seized March 16, 1985. He is the longest-held hostage.
   Other American hostages are Thomas Sutherland, Frank H. Reed,
Joseph J. Cicippio, Edwin A. Tracy, Jesse J. Turner, Alann B. Steen
and Robert B. Polhill.
   Former hostages and relatives of those still held will
participate in a ``Mass of Hope'' Friday at Georgetown University
in Washington, said Carmella LaSpada, spokeswoman for the hostage
support group No Greater Love.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Congressman Hospitalized With Inflamed Pancreas</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Jack Brooks, the 66-year-old dean of the
Texas congressional delegation, is suffering from an inflammation
of the pancreas and is expected to remain hospitalized for several
days, according to his office.
   The Democrat was admitted to Bethesda Naval Hospital on Sunday
after suffering abdominal pains during a flight from Texas to
Washington.
   His office said Wednesday that Brooks' condition was described
as serious but stable, and that he was expected to remain in
intensive care for several days.
   Brooks, the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, was
elected to Congress in 1952. He took over the Judiciary Committee
in January, after serving as chairman of the House Government
Operations Committee since 1975.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>D'Amato Mentioned Cases to Giuliani Out of `Concern'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato says he was merely
passing on his ``concern'' for the prosecutor's office when he
approached U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani in 1984 and 1985 on
behalf of people representing two organized crime figures.
   ``I didn't intercede, I never interceded,'' D'Amato, R-N.Y.,
said in a telephone interview Wednesday. ``I just passed on a
concern. ... I never asked Giuliani to do anything as it related to
any matter. Never. And he says that.''
   D'Amato was responding to a report in the Village Voice that he
had called Giuliani in 1984 to support a sentence reduction for
jailed mobster Mario Gigante.
   Months later, the Voice said, D'Amato asked Giuliani to review
minor charges against Paul Castellano, an alleged Gambino crime
family boss who was later murdered.
   But D'Amato said he never mentioned a specific case in the
latter conversation, and that he was was only passing on the remark
of a lawyer who said he had information that might be
``embarrassing'' to Giuliani's office.
   Asked who the lawyer was, D'Amato said, ``I believe, I believe
it was Roy Cohn.''
   Cohn, who died in 1986, won notoriety in the 1950s as the grand
inquisitor of Sen. Joseph McCarthy's communist-hunting committee.
Later, in private practice, Cohn represented a number of organized
crime figures, including Castellano.
   Giuliani, who resigned as U.S. Attorney to run for mayor in New
York City, said Wednesday that Castellano's name never came up in
the conversation with D'Amato.
   ``Nobody was ever identified,'' he said. ``(D'Amato) talked
about murder counts ... being that a lawyer was concerned that the
U.S. attorney's office would lose the case because although the
person was guilty of the other things the murder counts would not
be substantiated.''
   Giuliani told the New York Daily News he had concluded D'Amato
was referring to the Castellano case. He also said he told D'Amato
``this was not the way to communicate information to me.''
</TEXT>
