<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0327EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-PLO     10-26 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-PLO,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel: Arafat Still Involved in Terror Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel, at odds with Washington over a PLO role
in peace talks, has issued a report claiming Yasser Arafat's
faction ordered 12 attacks on Israeli civilians since the PLO chief
disavowed terrorism in December.
   Groups affiliated with the Palestine Liberation Organization
carried out 18 infiltrations or rocket attacks across Israel's
borders in the same period, the report said.
   Yigal Carmon, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's anti-terror
adviser, prepared the report and provided a copy to The Associated
Press on Wednesday.
   In his report, Carmon said the attacks ``are a violation of the
commitment Arafat gave to the United States and shows he can't be
trusted and that you can't do business with him.''
   He urged the United States to ``suspend the dialogue temporarily
until Arafat keeps his commitments.''
   The report comes as Israel and the United States haggle over
peace moves, especially the possible involvement of the PLO in
talks.
   Israel defines the PLO as a terrorist organization and refuses
to deal with it. It has strongly objected to the U.S. dialogue with
the PLO, which began 10 months ago when Arafat renounced terrorism
and said he recognized Israel.
   The Israeli report noted that Thomas Pickering, then the U.S.
ambassador, gave Israel a pledge a day after the U.S.-PLO talks
began Dec. 15 in Tunis that ``no American administration can
sustain the dialogue if terrorism continues by the PLO or any of
its factions.''
   Washington told Israel it expected the PLO to condemn any act of
terror and to discipline the guerrillas responsible, Carmon's
report said, and added:
   ``Not only has the PLO failed to fulfill these requirements, but
Arafat's own Fatah organization in particular has itself engaged in
terrorist acts ... and it has, furthermore, encouraged and lauded
these attacks even in the midst of these talks.''
   Carmon's report said security agents uncovered a 10-member cell
in April based near Jenin in the West Bank whose members were
recruited by the Force 17 unit of Fatah, Arafat's guerrilla wing,
in Amman, Jordan in 1987-88 and ordered to carry out attacks in
Israel.
   It blamed the cell for firebombings of two cars in northern
Israel and a hand grenade attack on a commuter bus in February and
March 1989, none of which caused casualties.
   The report said a second group linked to Force 17, an elite unit
led by Mahmoud Al Natur _ an Arafat aide known as Abu Tayyib _ was
blamed for seven bombings in the Tel Aviv-Petah Tikva area from
March through June. Another explosion in the West Bank wounded a
bomber.
   Two other bombings were attributed to an operation called
Western Sector, which the report said was under Arafat's personal
command. One wounded a Jewish cemetery worker.
   Sources said one reason U.S. officials remain unconvinced by
Israeli claims of Fatah involvement is that they are based on
interrogations. The credibility of such information was diminished
after a 1987 investigation revealed the use of torture by the Shin
Bet security service.
   Carmon said PLO factions under Arafat's umbrella were
responsible for nine attacks across the border in the past 10
months, many aimed at settlements near Lebanon, in which no
civilian casualties were reported. He said the other raids were by
pro-Syrian groups opposed to Arafat.
   Between Dec. 15 and Oct. 1, the report said, 99 alleged Arab
collaborators were killed by strike committees directed by the
PLO's ``unified command'' in the occupied lands.
   Israeli security sources said Wednesday they had found a
two-page, handwritten letter from a Fatah official ordering a Gaza
Strip activist to carry out assassinations. It was dated Aug. 18
and signed ``Halim,'' a code name used by a Force 17 official in
Amman, they said.
   The activist, identified as Hamdi Sheik Khalil, was arrested
Sept. 19. His lawyer said no formal charges had been filed.
   According to the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
the letter ordered the killings to be done in the name of the
Revolutionary Eagles in order to disguise PLO involvement. The
group has claimed responsibility for killing Kamal Wahidi, a senior
Gaza City official suspected of collaborating with Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
