<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     10-26 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Share Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen
Thursday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
moderately.
   The dollar ended at 141.90 yen, up 0.35 yen from the previous
day's 141.55-yen finish. The currency started trading at 141.60
yen, and moved between 141.50 yen and 141.90 yen.
   The 250-issue Nikkei Stock Average bounced back and rose by
236.09 points, or 0.67 percent, to end at 35,678.49. It had lost
84.15 points Wednesday.
   The dollar moved little in Tokyo before the release of the U.S.
gross national product figures for the third quarter, due out later
Thursday, traders said.
   Traders expected the figure to be about 2.5 percent, the figure
registered in the second quarter, according to a Bank of Tokyo
trader, who spoke anonymously.
   If the figure stays about the same, the market environment would
not change much, another trader with a major commercial bank said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On the stock exchange, dealers attributed the Nikkei index's
rebound to the yen's stability on the foreign exchange market.
   ``Japanese investors regained their buying incentives after the
last two days of falls, and picked up issues whose prices had
fallen,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama, a senior dealer with Nikko
Securities.
   He said participation by some major financial institutions also
reassured other investors and helped the index recover.
</TEXT>
