<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-TVMovies     10-26 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-TV Movies,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake-Related TV Movies Raise Questions of Exploitation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television projects based on San Francisco's
killer earthquake are already in the works, but some producers say
a TV show about the devastation would be exploitive.
   ABC and CBS said Wednesday they are considering television shows
about the Oct. 17 catastrophe. The death toll Wednesday stood at
63, and damage estimates have reached $10 billion.
   ``We are in the earliest stages of development'' of an
earthquake-related production, ABC spokesman Bob Wright said.
Another ABC spokesman said the network had already commissioned the
project with a producer.
   Craig Hoffman, a CBS spokesman, said: ``People have been
contacting us to determine the network's interest in doing a
project but no decision has been made either way.''
   NBC spokeswoman Sue Binford said she was unaware of any San
Francisco earthquake-inspired movie in the works at her network.
   TV producer David Wolper has had some ``serious discussions''
about making a quake show, said Auriel Sanderson, an assistant to
Wolper. Wolper was out of town and could not be reached for
comment, she said.
   Irwin Allen, producer of several disaster-related movies, said
he is thinking about developing a quake project.
   ``We're considering it, but we just completed a script for CBS
on Hurricane Hugo,'' Allen said. ``The (earthquake) is on the desk,
and we're surely thinking of it, but the hurricane comes first.''
   Some producers said such a program would not be a good idea.
   ``We are not doing anything on it,'' said Lindy DeKoben, vice
president of creative affairs for the Lansburg Co., which
specializes in ``fact-based'' movies such as ``Quiet Victory: The
Charlie Wedemeyer Story'' and ``The Ryan White Story.''
   ``We don't find anything redeeming in the story and a movie
would only exploit the misfortunes of others,'' DeKoben said.
   Marcy Gross, co-owner of Gross Weston Productions, makers of ``I
Love You Perfect'' and ``The Billionaire Boys Club,'' doubted that
a television movie based on the earthquake could serve a purpose.
   ``It's too soon and too painful,'' Gross said. ``I wouldn't want
to intrude on anybody's tragedy. ... As much as we love to sell
shows and we like to do anything that's current, I think we'd be
intruding on people's pain.''
   Such a program likely would include the story Julio Berumen, the
6-year-old whose right leg was amputated above the knee when he was
rescued from the wreckage of Interstate 880 in Oakland. Rescuers
had to cut through his mother's body to reach him.
   Another likely subject would be Buck Helm, who survived for 90
hours in the I-880 rubble, or a firefighter such as Gerry Shannon,
who grabbed a woman pinned in her blazing Marina district apartment
as a gas leak threatened to set off an explosion.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
