<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-26 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen today,
while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index bounced back moderately.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues regained 236.09
points, or 0.67 percent, to 35,678.49. It had lost 84.15 points
Wednesday.
   The dollar closed at 141.90 yen, up 0.35 yen from Wednesday's
close of 141.55 yen. It started trading at 141.60 yen and rose
while moving between 141.50 yen and 141.90 yen.
   ``The currency market had little movement today,'' said a Bank
of Tokyo trader, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Traders bought the yen against the dollar during earlier
trading, which kept the dollar at around its opening rate, but the
dollar rose back later as investors sold West German marks and
bought the U.S. unit for technical adjustments, he said.
   The U.S. currency rose further shortly before the end of trading
as market players tried to increase their dollar holdings for their
position adjustments, the trader added.
   Despite ups and downs in the dollar-yen rate, the dollar has
become less attractive to investors due to the U.S. monetary policy
of keeping its interest rate moderately low, traders said.
   On the stock exchange, the index rose steadily as the yen's
stability reassured market players and encouraged their buying
incentives, stock dealers said.
   The Nikkei lost more than 140 points in the last two days.
   Core industry issues such as railways and construction were
among the recent winners, which have become leading issues of the
market.
   Trading was fairly active today, with first section volume
estimated at 850 million shares, down, however, from Wednesday's 1
billion.
   Meanwhile, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. shares fell
further to 1.35 million yen, yet another low.
</TEXT>
