<HEAD>Newsman Laments Comments About New York Drivers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anchor Tom Brokaw apologized _ sort of _ to New
Yorkers for a remark he made last week on the ``NBC Nightly News.''
   Brokaw had complimented San Francisco motorists on Oct. 18, the
day after the earthquake, for their courtesy to one another despite
the malfunction of traffic lights.
   But he said that would never happen in the city where he himself
lives and works.
   ``In New York City, not a chance,'' Brokaw said.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch let Brokaw know of his disapproval about
the remark, said the New York Post in today's editions.
   So in a ``personal note'' on Wednesday night's broadcast, Brokaw
reminded viewers about his remark, and added:
   ``Well, that angered a lot of my fellow New Yorkers, who
reminded me of how smoothly traffic moved in this city during the
big power blackouts. And they were right. I was wrong.
   ``Traffic does move a lot better here when the traffic lights
don't work,'' Brokaw said.
