<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today,
and currency dealers attributed it to Wednesday's remarks by U.S.
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   The dollar's rise began in New York late Wednesday following
Greenspan's statements indicating the Fed remains concerned about
inflation in the United States. The remarks reinforced market
perceptions that the Fed won't ease monetary policy in the near
future, dealers said.
   They said the market was, however, waiting for U.S. third
quarter gross national product preliminary figures to be released
last Thursday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.35 yen to a closing 141.90 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 141.71 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   --1.8448 West German marks, up from 1.8410
   --1.6155 Swiss francs, up from 1.6129
   --6.2638 French francs, up from 6.2520
   --2.0825 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0740
   --1,352.00 Italian lire, up from 1,350.00
   --$1.1750 Canadian, up from $1.1745
   In London, it cost $1.6067 to buy one pound, slightly cheaper
for buyers than $1.6090 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $367.50 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $368.25. At mid-morning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $368.45.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $368.40 compared with $368.70 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 11 cents to close at a bid
$368.74.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.11 a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Wednesday.
