<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Drill     10-26 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Drill,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Drill Canceled After Real Thing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the International Society for
Traumatic Stress Studies say a disaster drill planned here for
today has been canceled.
   Last week's earthquake prompted some 500 visiting psychiatrists
and experts to call off their long-planned ``experiential program
where people will be asked to act as victims.''
   Instead, a panel of psychiatric and disaster relief experts will
be host of an open discussion on the real-life emotional
aftershocks from the Oct. 17 quake.
   Yael Danieli, an Israeli psychologist and president of the
society, said Northern California is handling the quake in a
``typically American'' manner _ pushing ahead and not allowing it
to get in the the way of things like the World Series.
   ``It's wonderful how America keeps going, but there's a danger
in just forgetting about the quake,'' said Danieli, who has done
extensive research with Holocaust survivors. ``It's like people
gave themselves a week to deal with it, but never had a chance to
cry, to scream. Maybe they can blow off some steam at the World
Series.''
</TEXT>
