<DOCNO> AP891026-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0625EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerDenied     10-26 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Denied,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Denied Docking Because It Lacks Oil-Spill Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENAI, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker carrying more than 14 million
gallons of crude oil was anchored in Cook Inlet after it being
turned away from a refinery dock because it lacked a state-approved
oil spill contingency plan.
   The Unocal vessel, the SanSinena II, was bound for the
Tesoro-Alaska Petroleum Co. refinery when the state Department of
Environmental Conservation denied it permission to dock on Tuesday.
   Larry Dietrick, the department's environmental quality director,
said Unocal had been denied a variance that would allow the tanker
to load or unload in Cook Inlet.
   Cook Inlet and Prince William Sound have been the focus of state
Department of Environmental Conservation review since the March 24
grounding of the tanker Exxon Valdez. It caused the nation's
largest oil spill, with nearly 11 million gallons coating 1,000
miles of shoreline.
   Unocal had planned for the vessel to unload its cargo at the
refinery and then pick up Cook Inlet crude oil before returning to
California, said Joe Sautner, an environmental field officer for
the state.
   State law requires spill contingency plans for any vessel
carrying more than 420,000 gallons of oil, and the plans must be
for specific areas, Sautner said.
   Unocal submitted a plan for the tanker late Wednesday, but it
had not been reviewed, he said. State officials have up to 65 days
to review such plans. Although Unocal referred to plans submitted
in 1978 and 1984, those could not be found and would have expired
in three years, Sautner said.
   ``That plan will probably not get reviewed in time to solve this
situation in the immediate future,'' he said. ``The reason that we
can't do it really quickly is that we don't want to put ourselves
in a position of doing a quick review.''
   Unocal officials in Kenai and Anchorage could not be reached for
comment late Wednesday.
   Last week, department Commissioner Dennis Kelso announced that
all tanker owners, operators and charterers in Prince William Sound
would need to have state-approved spill response plans by Nov. 13.
   Following the Valdez grounding, the state announced that the
Cook Inlet tanker traffic would be re-examined. The department said
it would turn away tankers lacking appropriate spill contingency
plans.
</TEXT>
