<HEAD>Kohl Calls New East German Leader for `Constructive' Talk</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl today called
East Germany's new Communist leader, Egon Krenz, for a 20-minute
talk on the need to improve inter-German relations, officials
announced.
   ``The conversation took place in a businesslike and constructive
atmosphere,'' Hans Klein, federal information minister and Kohl's
chief spokesman, told reporters after the early morning call.
   Klein said the two German leaders ``underscored their interest
in a further development of inter-German relations and advancement
of practical cooperation.''
   It was agreed during the talk, the first-ever contact between
the two men leading the separate German states, that Kohl's chief
of staff, Rudolf Seiters, would travel to East Berlin soon to meet
with senior East German officials.
   Kohl on Tuesday said he had no objections to a summit meeting
with Krenz, as soon as both sides considered it advantageous.
   Krenz responded Wednesday by telling reporters in East Berlin
that he, too, was open to a summit, but that pressing domestic
problems had to be dealt with first.
   Krenz, 52, was named Communist Party chief on Oct. 18 to succeed
his ousted mentor, Erich Honecker.
   East Germany's state-run media have since embarked on a more
open course, and the Communist country's leaders now say they are
willing to discuss reform with groups including opposition
activists they have previously shunned.
</TEXT>
