<FIRST>r a PM-Schools-PartyLine     10-26 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Schools-Party Line,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYC School Phone Bill Lists Porn, Party Line Calls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers, administrators and staffers in two
school districts called dial-a-porn, called information and called
collect to the tune of thousands of dollars in telephone misuse,
investigators were told.
   ``It's absolutely disgusting, people spending their time making
porn calls and baseball trivia calls,'' declared James F. Gill,
chairman of a commission investigating political patronage hiring
and other abuses in New York City schools.
   Misuse or waste amounted to 13 cents of every dollar spent on
telephone service in the two largely poor districts in East Harlem
and the Bronx, the commission said.
   Their personnel made at least $18,000 worth of calls on school
phones to dial-a-porn, sports, horoscope and gab lines, Amyjane
Rettew, a counsel for the commission, testified Wednesday.
   Records showed hundreds of calls, at 50 cents to $35 each, to
telephone lines like ``Erotic Fantasies,'' ``Dirty Joke,'' and
``Smut,'' she said.
   Rettew said irregularities ``leaped off the pages'' when
investigators _ who weren't particularly looking for telephone
misuse _ saw the telephone bills of the local boards.
   About $35,000 went down the drain because school personnel
called information instead of using a telephone directory and
$30,000 more was lost in penalties for late payment of telephone
bills, she said.
   An additional $6,500 was billed as collect or third-party-charge
calls, categories frowned upon or forbidden in Board of Education
policies.
   In a statement issued later in the day, schools acting
Chancellor Bernard Mecklowitz said he has directed the board's
business office to arrange for electronic blocks to prevent school
telephones from dialing the exchanges and area codes of chat lines.
</TEXT>
