<HEAD>Indicted Financier Allowed Trip to California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adnan Khashoggi, the indicted Saudi financier
who was confined to his apartment on $10 million bail, has been
granted a visit to California that his lawyer calls ``part
business, part pleasure.''
   While in California, Khashoggi's movements will continue to be
monitored by an electronic ankle bracelet as ordered by U.S.
District Judge John Keenan.
   The trip is an exception to travel restrictions attached to his
release on bail while he awaits a March trial on charges he helped
the late leader of the Philippines, Ferdinand Marcos, and his wife,
Imelda, defraud their national treasury.
   Khashoggi's itinerary includes eight nights, starting Friday, at
the exclusive Century Plaza Hotel in Los Angeles and five nights at
the home of his brother, Essam Khashoggi, in Santa Barbara.
   His attorney, Robert Morvillo, said in an Oct. 12 letter to
Keenan that Khashoggi's hotel room will be equipped with a personal
phone line to accommodate the monitoring device.
   Keenan granted permission for the trip in September.
   Morvillo said in an interview Wednesday that Khashoggi's stay in
Los Angeles will be ``part business, part pleasure.''
   He said Khashoggi would meet with one of his other attorneys to
discuss the status of civil lawsuits in which he is involved.
   Khashoggi was a fugitive after the indictment was brought in
October 1988. He was apprehended in April by Swiss authorities and
jailed in Switzerland until his extradition to New York in July.
