<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0827EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MichiganAbortion     10-26 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Michigan Abortion,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan Senate Approves Abortion Consent Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion activists were bolstered
after the Michigan Senate approved a bill that would require
parental consent before girls 17 or younger could obtain abortions.
   The bill goes to the House for consideration, possibly next
week, after senators passed it Wednesday on a vote of 29-8.
   Backers of the bill feel they have the votes in the House,
although it's uncertain whether the House would vote to override an
expected veto by Democratic Gov. James Blanchard.
   ``We expect a very favorable vote in the House,'' said Barbara
Listing, president of the anti-abortion group Michigan Right to
Life. ``With such wide public support for a parental rights
measure, we fully expect our representatives to reflect the will of
the citizens of Michigan.''
   Howard Simon, executive director of the American Civil Liberties
Union in Michigan, criticized the measure.
   ``I hope the public isn't suckered into thinking that this is a
family rights bill,'' he said. ``The issue is forcing unwanted
pregnancies to term.''
   About 30 states have parental consent laws on abortion, and most
are tied up in court and not enforced. Both sides of the abortion
issue are watching progress of the Michigan legislation because it
is among the first anti-abortion bills acted upon since the U.S.
Supreme Court on July 3 gave states more power to restrict
abortions.
   Among several amendments the Senate rejected was one that would
have waived parental consent if a girl was the victim of rape or
incest.
   Democratic Sen. John Cherry said it was ``unbelievable'' that a
victim of incest or rape might be required to ask her attacker for
permission to abort his child. ``This bill is deficient,'' he said.
``It's shocking.''
   The legislation would require a girl age 17 or less to get one
parent's written consent to obtain an abortion. If consent were
refused or the girl couldn't discuss the matter with a parent, she
would be able to seek a juvenile court order allowing the abortion.
   The court would be required to grant a waiver of parental
consent if it determined the girl was mature enough to make the
decision or found ``the abortion would be in the best interests of
the minor.''
   Parental consent wouldn't be required in an emergency, where the
continued pregnancy would endanger the girl.
</TEXT>
