<SECOND>PM-Arson Death,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth Worker Dies in Fire at Group Home, Former Resident Charged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A youth counselor died when he ran back into a
burning group home, apparently trying to rescue a boy he thought
was trapped, and police charged a former resident with murder and
arson in the fire.
   Peter Steiniger, 19, who left the home earlier this month when
he was charged with assaulting a different counselor, was arrested
after the fire Wednesday, police said.
   He was charged with murder, attempted murder and arson, said a
police spokesman, Officer Fred Weiner.
   The fire was started with a flammable liquid on the ground floor
of the Brooklyn group home, police said. Steiniger was seen at the
fire, said police and fire officials, and officials of the city's
Human Resources Administration, which ran the foster home for
abused and neglected youth.
   Witnesses told police they saw a young man break a window of the
home, pour a liquid inside and light a match. A two-gallon gasoline
can and a knife were found at the scene.
   Three counselors and six children living at the home escaped,
but 27-year-old counselor Terrance McGee ran back inside,
apparently under the mistaken impression that one boy was trapped.
   The front door slammed and locked in McGee, the Daily News said
in today's editions.
   ``We heard him screaming,'' said a 19-year-old resident, Bruce
Edwards, who helped others try to force open the door, but failed,
the News said.
   McGee was pronounced dead at Kings County Hospital of smoke
inhalation and burns.
   Steiniger had been arrested Oct. 12 for assaulting another youth
counselor at the home, said police Deputy Chief Joseph DeMartino.
   ``We believe he was angry at being evicted,'' DeMartino told
reporters.
