<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan     10-26 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhutto Government No-Confidence Motion to Open Nov. 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly speaker
announced today that Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto will face a
no-confidence motion next week at the request of conservatives
opposed to Ms. Bhutto's left-leaning party.
   Flag-waving government supporters waited outside the assembly
for the announcement. They were watched by dozens of helmeted riot
police.
   There was no unrest, but Speaker Meraj Khalid warned noisy
lawmakers. ``You should avoid a scene which could, God forbid,
present a bad example before the nation,'' he said.
   The Islamic Democratic Alliance, a group of nine mainly
conservative and Islamic fundamentalist parties, called Monday for
the no-confidence motion against the government of Ms. Bhutto's
left-leaning Pakistan People's Party.
   About 105 of 237 assembly members have announced they will vote
against Ms. Bhutto's 10-month-old Cabinet.
   The governing party has 116 seats in the legislature following
the defection of one member on Wednesday. But with the help of
independent lawmakers, it appeared likely to get the necessary 119
votes to stave off a challenge.
   Khalid said debate on the motion will begin Nov. 1.
   Ms. Bhutto predicted the opposition won't be able to muster more
than 90 votes.
   ``The opposition will be totally exposed when the vote takes
place as its members continue to desert its ranks,'' she told
reporters at the assembly building.
   Ms. Bhutto's party won by far the largest bloc of seats in the
National Assembly in November's elections, the first free elections
in more than a decade.
   But her rivals gained control of Punjab province, where 60
percent of Pakistan's 109 million people live.
   Since Ms. Bhutto became prime minister on Dec. 2, 1988, both
sides have vowed to unseat each other.
   Ms. Bhutto's government has been plagued by ethnic violence,
particularly in the country's largest city, Karachi.
   The southern port is in Ms. Bhutto's home province of Sindh,
where hundreds of people have died and thousands more have been
hurt in ethnic turmoil over the past three years.
</TEXT>
