<DOCNO> AP891026-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0916EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-Children     10-26 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Children,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Children with AIDS Infections Have Better Prospects than Adults</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AZT Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who catch the AIDS virus while young have a
far better chance than adults of remaining healthy with the
infection for many years, a study published today shows.
   The research, conducted on people who caught the human
immunodeficiency virus through blood products, is the largest of
several recent studies to show that the older people are, the
faster their infection progresses to AIDS.
   ``The popular notion is that AIDS is inevitable if one is
infected with HIV, and in fact there is no study that shows that,''
said Dr. James J. Goedert. ``The opportunity to provide long-term
health for an HIV-infected child is relatively good, especially
with AZT and other treatments coming along.''
   The drug AZT is often recommended for people infected with HIV
as a way of forestalling the start of AIDS symptoms.
   Goedert's research, conducted at the National Cancer Institute,
was published in the New England Journal of Medicine. It was based
on 319 people who got the AIDS virus through treatment for
hemophilia.
   Because of an inherited defect, hemophiliacs require regular
treatment with a protein called factor VIII that makes their blood
form clots. The factor is made from blood obtained from thousands
of donors. During the early 1980s, the treatment was often
unknowingly contaminated with HIV.
   Manufacturers began heating factor VIII to kill the virus in
1984. But by then, an estimated 60 percent of hemophiliacs in the
United States were already infected.
   As the epidemic progressed, doctors noticed that infected
hemophiliacs seemed to do better than male homosexuals and drug
abusers, the other main risk groups. However, the latest research
suggests this is simply because the hemophiliacs are frequently
younger.
   The study found that 13 percent of those who caught the AIDS
virus before age 18 had gone on to develop AIDS after eight years
of infection. By comparison, AIDS had occured in 27 percent of
those infected between ages 18 and 34 and in 44 percent of people
who got the virus after age 34.
   Goedert said young people might resist the virus longer because
they have more of the blood cells that are primary target of the
virus. Another explanation is that they have never been exposed to
the otherwise harmless microbes that can cause fatal illnesses in
people whose immune defenses are destroyed by HIV.
   ``Possibly there is some unmeasured co-factor associated with
aging,'' he said. ``The cells themselves may respond better in a
young person and control the virus better for a longer period of
time. If that could be demonstrated to be true, that might have
some implications for vaccine research, because a vaccine could be
targeted to enhance that factor.''
   An editorial in the journal by Dr. Harold R. Roberts of the
University of North Carolina said those who treat hemophiliacs can
take little comfort in the latest findings. While the work may
eventually lead to improved therapy, ``it is unlikely that this
will happen within the anticipated life span of currently infected
patients.''
   A separate study in the journal, conducted by German
researchers, found no AIDS infections among 155 hemophiliacs who
were treated with purified factor VIII during the early 1980s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
