<FIRST>u i PM-Gorbachev 1stLd-Writethru   10-26 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0506,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Studies Business Prospects, Praised For Lauding Finnish
Neutrality</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to UPDATE with details from meeting with business
leaders, new joint project announced; Fixes typos thruout. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev met today with the
leading businessmen of this prosperous country to hear ideas for
capitalist projects for the troubled Soviet economy, and he
couldn't believe his ears.
   Gorbachev reviewed Finnish developments in a range of industries
from forestry to clothing for seamen on icebreakers, and he was
clearly astounded when he had a conversation on a mobile telephone.
   ``Is this a joke or is this for real?'' he asked the chairman of
the Nokia electronics company, Simo Vuorilehto, when handed the
receiver. He had a short phone conversation in Russian, but it was
not known with whom.
   The meeting at the Confederation of Finnish Industries came on
the second day of a three-day state visit focusing on how to get
Western know-how and business acumen to bolster Gorbachev's
economic reform.
   Many of the companies represented already have joint projects
with Soviet firms, but Gorbachev told the industrialists there
should be many more. ``We should have dozens and dozens,'' he said.
   One new venture could be forthcoming. The Finnish company OY
Warsila Ab announced today that the Soviet Union and a group of
Finnish and Norwegian companies will launch a feasibility study on
exploiting a natural gas field under the Barents Sea and will set
up a joint venture if it is deemed profitable.
   Gorbachev showed particular interest in the environmental
controls in such industries as mining and metal technology, asking
the cost of such controls.
   Finnish officials have complained that Soviet factories are
responsible for much of their country's air pollution, and the
sides prepared an agreement aimed at curbing transboundary
pollution.
   The chairman of the business confederation, Casimir Ehrenrooth,
told Gorbachev the Finns agreed to a Soviet request to train
industry leaders in Western business management and practices.
   More than 30 other agreements are to be signed for joint
businesses, development projects and political issues.
   Earlier, Gorbachev had a breakfast meeting with Prime Minister
Harri Holkeri to explore state-to-state projects.
   The meetings came as Finnish newspapers lauded Gorbachev's
unequivocal recognition of Finnish neutrality, which in previous
Soviet statements had been couched in qualifications.
   In a dinner speech Wednesday, the Soviet president said, ``I
want to greet a neutral Finland.''
   The issue of neutrality strikes a sensitive chord in Finland,
which often has been derided as being under Moscow's thumb and
adopting subservient policies in exchange for being allowed to
remain independent following military defeats at the hands of the
Soviets.
   ``Gorbachev's dinner speech was marked by new thinking from
beginning to end,'' said an editorial in Helsingi Sanomat.
   On Wednesday, thousands of Finns chanted ``Gorba, Gorba'' and
waited in damp weather as Gorbachev visited a room where Lenin,
founder of the Soviet state, once hid from Czarist forces before
the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution. The room is in the house of the
police commissioner of the time in downtown Helsinki.
   The 58-year-old Kremlin chief shook hands and chatted with the
surging crowd. Some held up placards with slogans like,``Welcome
Gorbachev, Welcome New Thinking.''
   But Gorbachev also was dogged by a few protesters, who demanded
negotiations for the return of parts of the eastern Karelia region.
Finland ceded the region after fighting two bitter wars with the
Soviets in 1939 and 1944.
   ``Give us back Karelia,'' some demonstrators shouted from the
back of the crowd. Gorbachev showed no sign he heard.
</TEXT>
