<HEAD>Reagans Thank Japanese for California Quake Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan and his wife, Nancy,
thanked the Japanese people today for helping Californians to
recover from last week's devastating earthquake.
   Reagan met briefly with a group of 13 Japanese college students
who volunteered to help Californians clean up and rebuild their
homes in the San Francisco Bay area.
   ``I have just met with one of the most inspiring groups of young
people I have ever encountered,'' Reagan said. ``Their trip to San
Francisco is a most eloquent statement about the special friendship
between the people of Japan and the people of the United States.''
   Both the Reagans and their Japanese hosts, the Fujisankei
Communications Group, have emphasized the positive aspects of ties
between the two nations during the visit, while minimizing thorny
economic differences.
   Mrs. Reagan, meanwhile, was interviewed about her post-White
House life and anti-drug abuse program on the Fuji Television
network, owned by Fujisankei, which reportedly is paying the
Reagans $2 million for the visit.
   ``We're very grateful to the Japanese people for what they've
done, for the assistance they've given'' to the earthquake victims,
Mrs. Reagan said.
   Japanese companies and individuals reportedly have pledged more
than $7 million in earthquake aid, and several groups of Japanese
volunteers have left for California to help in the recovery efforts.
   After meeting with Reagan today, one short-cropped volunteer
smiled and said, ``He pointed at my head and commented that we had
similar haircuts.''
   Reagan's hair has been short since he underwent surgery Sept. 8
to drain fluid from his brain, an injury caused by a horseback
riding accident in July.
   ``Everyone tells him that he looks much younger _ that he looks
about 16 years old,'' Mrs. Reagan said of her husband's hair style.
``But I'm having a little bit of a hard time getting used to it.''
