<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0951EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DoctorSlaying     10-26 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctor Slaying,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murder Defendant Has Courtroom Outburst</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defendant in the rape and murder of a
pregnant doctor in her hospital office swore at a prosecutor who
was questioning a witness about his sanity, then turned another
outburst on the judge.
   ``I'm leaving, man! I'm leaving, (expletive)! You in trouble!''
Steven Smith screamed as prosecutor James Kindler cross-examined a
defense psychiatrist who testified the suspect was too deranged to
be prosecuted.
   Several jurors stared in surprise at Smith, who was standing at
the defense table. The defendant then said softly, ``There's
nothing I can do about it, man.''
   The turmoil Wednesday was sparked when Kindler asked Dr. Daniel
Schwartz if Smith could be faking insanity to receive lenient
treatment.
   State Supreme Court Justice James Leff, the trial judge, then
cleared the jury from the room and told Smith he would tolerate no
further outbursts, which prompted another explosion from the
defendant.
   ``You want me to stop it? I can't control it! Listen to me, man,
I'm not normal, man, at all, at all,'' said Smith. ``That's what
got me into trouble here now. ... I'm here to get help, brother.''
   Smith was then cuffed and led from the courtroom. Leff brought
the jury back and cross-examination of Schwartz continued.
   Smith, 23, is on trial for the rape and killing Jan. 9 of Dr.
Kathryn Hinnant, 33, at Bellevue Hospital. She was five months
pregnant.
   Schwartz, chief of forensic psychiatry at Brooklyn's Kings
County Hospital, said Smith appears to have a psychosis related to
schizophrenia.
   Schwartz said Smith has complained of hearing voices,
hallucinating and being unable to control his actions since he was
14. Smith, he said, apparently tried to commit suicide three times.
   He has been in and out of mental hospitals for the past decade.
   Contributing to Smith's insanity, Schwartz testified, is his
belief that his mother tried to abort him and wanted him dead.
   Smith's mother, Marian, who is in court every day, denied her
son's comments to psychiatrists. ``As far as not getting love and
care from me _ that's a lie,'' she said outside the courtroom. ``As
far as wanting him dead _ that's a lie.''
   Smith has pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity to the murder
charge. If convicted, he could be sentenced to 25 years to life.
   The jury is expected to begin deliberations Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
