<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     10-26 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Killed, One After His Car Strikes Policeman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli security forces shot and killed an
18-year-old Palestinian today after he ran his car into a policeman
at a West Bank roadblock, the army said. Troops killed a second
Palestinian in the Gaza Strip.
   The man fatally shot by soldiers in Gaza's Jabaliya refugee camp
was wearing a mask and ignored orders to halt and warning shots in
the air, the army said. He was identified as Adel Abu Salem, 19.
   Arab reporters said the soldiers surprised masked youths
painting anti-Israeli slogans by arriving in a civilian Mercedes
car and out of uniform. The army announcement made no mention of
the soldiers being in civilian dress.
   At least four people also were wounded in Jabaliya when police
fired plastic bullets and rubber-coated steel balls to quell a
stone-throwing protest that erupted after the masked man's
shooting, Arab hospital officials said.
   In separate clashes with soldiers, a 12-year-old Palestinian boy
was shot in the thigh in the Gaza Strip village of Beit Hanoun and
a 26-year-old man was wounded in the West Bank's Faraa refugee
camp, hospital officials said.
   In the West Bank, security forces chased a car driven by a
Palestinian through the streets of Bethlehem after the driver
intentionally ran into a policeman at a roadblock, an army
announcement said.
   Security forces shot and killed the driver when he failed to
halt, the announcment said. It said the policeman was hospitalized
with minor injuries.
   The Palestinian, identified as Naeem Karim Daamseh, 18, died at
a hospital in nearby Beit Jala. Hospital officials said he was shot
in the neck.
   The deaths raised to 605 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israeli soldiers and civilians in the 22-month uprising against
Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Forty Israelis also have been slain in the violence, and 135
Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs as alleged
collaborators with Israeli authorities
   Also in the Gaza Strip, the army destroyed two houses whose
residents were accused of attacking suspected collaborators, the
army said. Nineteen people lived in the homes in the villages of
Abassan and Beni Suhaillah, Arab reporters said.
   Army figures show soldiers have torn down more than 220
Palestinian houses during the uprising. Human rights groups say the
figure is higher.
