<FIRST>r i PM-PLOPasta     10-26 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PLO Pasta,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Pasta Entangles Manufacturer in Legal Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Israeli merchants have asked police
to probe whether an Arab noodle maker is wrapping its pasta in the
Palestinian flag.
   A spokesman for the Israeli Manufacturers' Association said
today that the group has filed a police complaint against the firm
for using the four colors of the outlawed Palestinian flag on its
spaghetti packages.
   ``We asked police to investigate why they are allowed to
distribute the flag in this way. It should be considered against
the law,'' said Danny Leish, a spokesman for the Israeli industrial
group.
   The police complaint is the latest battle in a war of symbols
that is part the Palestinian uprising against Israeli control of
the occupied territories. The complaint also reflects the anger of
Jewish industrialists with an economic slump partly caused by the
22-month rebellion.
   The Palestinian flag, which Israel considers a ``PLO flag,'' is
outlawed by Israel, as is the PLO, which the Jewish state considers
a terrorist organization.
   The spaghetti in question is produced by the Al Ghazel Macaroni
Co. in the West Bank city of Bethlehem. It is marketed in a package
decorated with green, black, red and white stripes.
   The company's owner, Wadi Abu Eta, could not be reached for
comment because phone lines were cut to the Bethlehem area.
   Ruth Shlesinger, a spokeswoman for national police in Jerusalem,
declined to comment on the complaint, which was filed two weeks ago.
   Leish denied the complaint was aimed at harming an Arab
competitor, but acknowledged Israeli food manufacturers were among
the hardest hit in the recession touched off by the rebellion in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. Unemployment currently
exceeds 9.5 percent in Israel.
   Food manufacturers have lost about $100 million during the
22-month-old uprising and had to cut about 1,000 jobs, Leish said.
He blamed much of the damage on an uprising boycott of Israeli
products by the occupied territories' 1.7 million Arabs.
   Leish complained that the problem is compounded by Arab
competitors marketing their products within Israel, adding the
Manufacturers' Association already has asked the army to insist
Palestinian products be clearly identified as such.
   The spaghetti dispute is the latest of a string of Israeli steps
against symbols of Palestinian nationhood. Forcing Arab youths to
pull down Palestinian flags is a regular occurrence in the disputed
lands.
   Sometimes names also are considered symbols. The Hadashot daily
reported that an Israeli hospital refused this week to register a
Bedouin Arab baby girl given the popular uprising name ``Tahrir,''
Arabic for ``liberation.''
   Speaking of symbols, Israeli reports noted the Al Ghazal
spaghetti package also bears a Kosher stamp, showing it meets with
Jewish dietary laws.
</TEXT>
