<FIRST>r a PM-ACENominations     10-26 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ACE Nominations,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Box Office Leads in ACE Awards Nominations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home Box Office has received nearly a third
of the 338 nominations for excellence in programming sponsored by
the National Academy of Cable Programming.
   HBO received 103 nominations for shows including ``Not
Necessarily the News,'' ``Vietnam War Story,'' ``Tales From the
Crypt'' and ``Murderers Among Us: The Simon Wiesenthal Story.''
   A total of 338 nominations in 82 categories were announced
Wednesday. Thirty cable companies got nominations.
   Showtime got 29 nominations, the Disney Channel 23, Arts &amp;
Entertainment 21, Cable News Network and ESPN 18 each, and Turner
Network Television 17.
   The 11th annual ACE awards ceremony will be broadcast live on
cable from Los Angeles on Jan. 14. Craft awards will be presented
Jan. 12.
   ``It's Garry Shandling's Show'' on Showtime was nominated as
best comedy series and its star, Garry Shandling, was nominated as
best actor in a comedy series. It also received two directing and
three writing nominations.
   ``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd,'' picked up by Lifetime
cable network after its cancellation last year by NBC, also was
nominated as best comedy series and acting nominations went to
Blair Brown, who stars in the title role, and to George Gaynes. The
show received two directing nominations.
   HBO's ``Not Necessarily the News'' received the third nomination
as best comedy series and Lucy Webb and Annabelle Gurwitch were
nominated as best actress in a comedy series. It was also cited for
writing and editing.
   HBO's ``Murderers Among Us'' was nominated as best movie or
miniseries, as were Disney's ``Looking for Miracles,'' TNT's
``Nightbreaker,'' HBO's ``Tailspin: Behind the Korean Airliner
Tragedy'' and HBO's ``Traveling Man.''
   Ben Kingsley was nominated as best actor for his role as Simon
Wiesenthal in ``Murderers Among Us,'' which also drew citations for
Renee Soutendijk as best actress in a movie or miniseries, and Jack
Shepherd for best supporting actor. Other nominations were for
directing, writing, art direction, editing and makeup.
   Nominations for best dramatic series went to USA Network's ``The
Hitchhiker,'' USA Network's ``The Ray Bradbury Theater'' and A&amp;E
Network's ``Shortstories.''
   HBO's ``Tales From the Crypt'' won three actor nominations, two
actress, two writing, one directing, two for original music score,
and one for makeup. It swept the category of director of
photography or lighting for a comedy or dramatic series with three
nominations.
   Cable has also been eligible to participate in the Emmy awards
for the past two years.
</TEXT>
