<FIRST>u i PM-Cheney     10-26 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheney,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Warns of Increasing Hi-Tech Exports to East Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JESSICA BALDWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILDENHALL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said
today that despite changes in the East bloc, the West must remain
``very cautious'' about selling it high-technology equipment.
   Answering questions during a visit to a U.S. air base in eastern
England, Cheney said it was necessary to maintain the COCOM regime
_ the organization of industrial democracies that regulates trade
in items to Soviet bloc nations. COCOM stands for Coordinating
Committee for Multilateral Export Controls.
   Cheney arrived here Wednesday from a NATO meeting in Portugal
and had talks with British Defense Secretary Tom King. His next
stop was West Germany.
   The export committee's 17 member states _ the United States, 14
of its NATO allies, Australia and Japan _ are meeting at a secret
venue in Paris.
   Cheney welcomed the changes in the Soviet Union and Eastern
Europe but said the West needs to remain ``very cautious about the
kinds of technology we allow to be transferred to the eastern
bloc.''
   He said the Soviet Union still has ``a huge arsenal of
intercontinental ballistic weapons and other strategic systems''
targeted against the United States and other NATO members.
   ``They are the only nation in the world capable of destroying
us. I think it is in our interests, under those circumstances, to
continue the COCOM regime,'' Cheney said.
   The United States' COCOM allies are pressing for an easing of
trade restrictions, leaving Washington all but isolated, according
to a U.S. source who spoke on condition of anonymity before the
meeting began Wednesday.
   European members accuse the United States of failing to adapt to
the changes in the East bloc and of using COCOM to protect U.S.
manufacturers from foreign competition.
   At the NATO meeting in Portugal, Cheney expressed concern about
a Kremlin push to upgrade its strategic, or long-range, nuclear
weapons.
   ``The Soviet Union still possesses enormous military
capability,'' he said. ``The Soviets continue with an aggressive
modernization program of their own strategic (nuclear) systems.''
   He said their ``strategic capability is more robust today than
it was when Mr. Gorbachev came to power.''
   In their final statement, Cheney and the other NATO officials
called on the Soviet Union to make unilateral cuts in its
short-range nuclear missile systems to current NATO levels.
   According to Western estimates, the Soviet Union has 1,450
short-range nuclear missile launchers in Europe. NATO has 88 Lance
launchers, most based in West Germany.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has promised to pull out
500 short-range nuclear weapons from Europe this year.
</TEXT>
