<FIRST>r i PM-Spain-Nuclear     10-26 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain-Nuclear,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear Plant Fire Sparks Worries, Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDELLOS, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a nuclear power plant here has
renewed nearby residents' worries about evacuation plans and has
energized opponents facing the ruling Socialist Party in a general
election on Sunday.
   The Oct. 19 fire damaged one of the two turbine generators
powering the plant's cooling systtem, but never affected its
graphite core, said Fausto Sanchez Cascado, spokesman at the
17-year-old Vandellos I nuclear plant.
   ``Everything happened in the exterior (electrical) part of the
plant. It never affected the reactor,'' Sanchez Cascado said in a
telephone interview today.
   There was no radiation released and the fire caused no injuries,
Sanchez Cascado said. The fire did reduce the plant's cooling
capacity by half, but it still had double that needed to cool the
nuclear core.
   Authorities have shut down the Spanish-built plant indefinitely
and Spain's Nuclear Safety Commission is investigating the
accident. Industry Minister Claudio Aranzadi said it was too early
to decide whether to close the plant permanently.
   The accident sparked major media coverage, some of it erroneous,
and calls for a nuclear power moratorium by campaigning opposition
leaders a week before general elections.
   ``All of the political parties are trying to take advantage,''
Industry and Energy Minister Undersecretary Victor Perez Pita said.
   Recent newspapers polls indicate voters are expected to give the
Socialists their third-straight parliamentary majority.
   ``The incident could have been serious,'' said Carlos Barcelo,
mayor of Vandellos, a small town about six miles from the plant.
``But it has been capitalized on by politicians and the public has
not received good information.''
   Spain's leading daily El Pais, which published five front-page
articles on the fire in six days, erroneously reported Wednesday
that the Vienna-based International Atomic Energy Agency had
described the accident as the worst since the April 1986 Chernobyl
disaster in the Soviet Union.
   In today's edition, El Pais said the judgment it attributed to
the agency had come from the agency's press clipping service in
which El Pais and other Spanish dailies had been mentioned.
   ``El Pais cited itself attributing its own views to the (atomic
energy agency),'' according to an agency statement issued today by
spokesman Hans Friedrich Meyer.
   Meanwhile, Barcelo and three other area mayors threatened to
pull out of the government's nuclear emergency evacuation plan,
after claiming that civil defense officials failed to notify them
about the fire for 30 minutes.
   The fire highlighted inadequate civil defense measures, Barcelo
said. The town's city administration has decided to take the
National Civil Defense Agency to court if it fails to better equip
local officials for an emergency.
   Vandellos I is Spain's third-oldest nuclear power plant. It was
built using French technology, went into service in 1972 and is to
remain operating until 2003.
   A consortium formed by the French utility Electricite de France
and several Spanish electric companies own the plant, a cold-gas
reactor that uses natural uranium as opposed to the enriched
uranium used by pressurized water reactors.
   These types of plants are set to be phased out of operation in
France in the next five years.
</TEXT>
