<FIRST>r a PM-ChicagoFilmFest     10-26 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Film Fest,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Film Wins Top Honors at Chicago Film Festival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Zerograd,'' a satire about life after glasnost
in the Soviet Union by Soviet director Karen Chakhnazarov, has won
the Gold Hugo, the top award in the Chicago International Film
Festival.
   ``Birth,'' a study of a father's search for his missing son
directed by India's Shaji Karun, and ``Death of a Teamaster,'' a
drama set in 17th century Japan directed by Kei Kumai, both earned
Silver Hugos.
   The awards were voted by a nine-member jury of film
professionals and announced Wednesday.
   Hong Kong director Alex Law's ``Painted Faces'' won a Silver
Hugo for best first feature.
   Silver Hugos for acting were awarded to Grazyna Szapolowska for
her role in Krzysztof Kieslowski's Polish feature, ``A Short Film
About Love,'' and to Jorg Gudzuhn for his performance in the East
German ``Fallada _ The Last Chapter.''
   Gold Plaques for acting were awarded to Caterina Sylos Labini
for the Italian comedy ``The Icicle Thief,'' and to Richard
Anconina for the French film ``Itinerary of a Spoiled Child.''
   The jury awarded special citations to Ivan Nichev's ``Ivan and
Alexandra'' from Bulgaria, Hungarian director Ferenc Teglasy's
``Never, Nowhere, to No One,'' and Idrissa Ouedraogo's ``Yaaba''
from Burkina Faso in West Africa.
   The festival continues through Nov. 2.
