<FIRST>r a PM-FreighterAground 1stLd-Writethru a0520 10-26 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Freighter Aground, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0520,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freighter Carrying Diesel Fuel Shipment Aground on Coral Reef</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to update with no success at pulling ship free,
alcohol test, no designated shipping lanes. Adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A freighter carrying thousands of gallons of diesel
fuel ran aground on a coral reef in the Key Largo National Marine
Sanctuary and ripped its hull, but no leaks were reported, the
Coast Guard said today.
   The 155-foot freighter Alec Owen Maitland, hauling no cargo but
carrying 8,000 to 10,000 gallons of diesel fuel for its own
engines, ran aground Wednesday afternoon about five miles off Key
Largo, Coast Guard Petty Officer Keith Richter said.
   The hull was gashed and the ship took on water in its forward
ballast tank.
   ``The forward tank has about 5 feet of water in it, but she's
not spilling any oil,'' Richter said.
   Two commercial tugs weren't strong enough to move the ship at
high tide this morning and a stronger tug was sent from Miami,
sanctuary Officer Harry Jackson said. Conditions were ideal with
1-foot seas, light wind and a sunny sky.
   There are no designated shipping lanes along the reef around the
Florida Keys, Jackson said. The Coast Guard said the freighter
draws 12 to 14 feet, and charts for the area show depths as shallow
at 2 to 4 feet.
   The ship, owned by Maitland Bros. Co. of Littlestown, Pa., ran
aground while traveling from Miami to Mobile, Ala., the Coast Guard
said.
   The ship's mate on duty when the ship ran aground was given a
breath test for alcohol, but the results were not yet available,
said Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Paul Von Protz. No one was injured among
the crew of five.
</TEXT>
