<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BoyLost     10-26 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boy Lost,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expanded Search Fails to Find Missing Boy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHEMULT, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The desperate search for a 9-year-old boy
missing since Sunday with his pony in the rugged canyons of central
Oregon resumed at daybreak today but already poor weather worsened.
   Heavy snow was falling and the temperature was 20 degrees, said
Klamath County search and rescue spokeswoman Betty Lucht. Despite
the weather, around 300 searchers planned to continue looking for
Nathan Madsden on horseback and on foot, she said.
   Nathan was dressed in a slicker and chaps, and his mother, Sarah
Madsen, said earlier that she was confident he could take care of
himself.
   Nathan disappeared Sunday while herding cattle with his family
during an annual roundup. Relatives said the boy and his
10-year-old sorrel, Tony, surely stayed together.
   This week's snow, sleet and rain have erased any tracks the boy
and his horse may have left. Overnight temperatures have been
freezing four nights in a row.
   ``If he can stay with the horse and huddle with it, he's got a
chance. If he's a tough little cowboy, he may still be alive,''
said Klamath County Sheriff Carl Burkhart.
   Two helicopters and a C-130 transport plane were sent Wednesday
by the Air Force Reserve 304th Aerospace Rescue &amp; Recovery Squadron
based in Portland. They joined a Civil Air Patrol plane that began
searching Wednesday after being grounded all week because of
inclement weather.
   Sheriff's spokeswoman Becky Collins said today's poor weather
would keep the helicopters grounded.
   The search party grew to about 350 Wednesday from 70 on Monday
and volunteers continued to call from as far away as Richland,
Wash., Collins said.
   Searchers on foot and horseback covered 60 square miles
Wednesday, expanding beyond the 13-square-mile canyon searched
previously.
   Several searchers walked through an area called the ``bogs,''
filled with treacherous mud pits. One man sank to his waist Tuesday.
   ``Only a nearby log saved the guy from going all the way in over
his head,'' said Russ Herbison of the Lane County Sheriff's Posse.
``For obvious reasons, we want to be sure there are no signs of
Nathan having been in there.
   ``No one's giving up hope, and no one's going home,'' Herbison
said. ``We're going to find him.''
</TEXT>
