<HEAD>Police Commissioner, 51 Officers Fired in Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's police commissioner and 51 senior
police officers were fired Thursday, according to Radio Omdurman
and informed sources.
   Police officers recently submitted a memorandum to the military
government, protesting interference of the army in police affairs
and demanding improvement in working conditions, the sources said.
   It was not immediately known if the firings were in response to
the memo.
   State-owned radio Omdurman reported that police commissioner,
Gen. Osman al-Shafei, had been promoted to major general and
relieved of his duties. The report gave no reason.
   Informed sources said 51 senior police officers also had been
fired. The government has not confirmed or denied this.
   The military government of Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan el-Bashir came
to power June 30 after overthrowing the civilian regime of Prime
Minister Sadek el-Mahdi. A mainly civilian cabinet has been formed
but the decision-making is controlled by el-Bashir and his 15-man
military council.
   A curfew and a state of emergency remain in effect.
