<SECOND>PM-Pregnancy Sentence,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Delay Sentence So Woman Can Have Abortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW PORT RICHEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has refused to postpone a
woman's 60-day jail sentence to allow her to get an abortion before
she is locked up.
   ``Do you want a continuance so you can murder your baby, is that
it?'' Pasco County Judge Dan C. Rasmussen asked Pamela Forney
before sending her to jail.
   Both defense and prosecution lawyers agreed Forney, who says she
begins her third month of pregnancy today, could postpone her
sentence by 10 days before serving her term for violaing probation
on a 1987 charge of driving under the influence.
   Ms. Forney, 26, asked for the additional time because she was
afraid it might be too late for a safe abortion when she got out of
jail.
   Ms. Forney pleaded with the judge, saying she is financially
unable to care for a baby. Rasmussen, however, suggested Monday
that she carry it full term and then give it up for adoption.
   ``I thought it was my choice,'' Ms. Forney said in a jail
interview Tuesday. ``He's telling me I don't have a choice. It's
not right that he can choose for me.''
   Ms. Forney, a part-time bartender who is not married, said she
doubts she'll have a job when she gets out of jail.
   Lee Cannon, attorney for the Pasco County Sheriff's Office, said
officials will have to have Ms. Forney medically evaluated and will
discuss their options at that time.
   ``We may go before the judge to seek an order to get the
procedure for her. We don't know yet,'' he said.
</TEXT>
