<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru   10-26 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0498,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Miners Return to Work, New Stoppages Threatened</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to update with miners back at work, others considering
strike. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal miners in the northern Vorkuta region
returned to work today after a 24-hour strike demanding promised
benefits and political reforms, a spokesman said. Miners in the
Ukraine met to consider a walkout.
   Miners in Vorkuta, 950 miles northeast of Moscow, walked off the
job at midnight Wednesday in violation of a new law banning strikes
in such vital areas as energy, defense and transportation.
   ``Due to pressure from the local media and management's taking
the case to court, the regional strike committee made a decision to
end the strike at midnight'' today, Sergei Masolovich, a member of
the regional strike committee, said by telephone. He said hearings
on the strike had begun in regional court.
   The area's largest coalfield remained on strike, but the other
strikes were called off, Masolovich said. He said a total of 18,000
miners in nine of the region's 13 mines took part.
   In the Ukraine, miner representatives were meeting to consider
resumption of the massive strike that last summer paralyzed the
Donetsk coal basin, the country's largest coal producing region.
   Top Soviet officials have openly voiced concern that the miners'
actions, by cutting the nation's coal supplies, could force a
rationing of heat and light as the brutal winter begins.
   The miners were demanding delivery of benefits promised by the
government during a massive strike last summer, said Anatoly
Litvinenko, another strike committee member.
   First Deputy Premier Lev Voronin warned earlier this month that
power stations and public utilities have 4.5 million fewer tons of
coal on hand now than at this time last year due to the strikes.
   Miners in virtually every major Soviet coal field walked off the
job during the summer, demanding better consumer goods and working
conditions and more financial independence.
   Litvinenko said the miners now also are demanding political
changes, including elimination of Article 6 of the constitution,
which makes the Communist Party the ``leading and guiding force of
Soviet society,'' and barring the party's general secretary from
holding the job of president.
   Litvinenko said the miners want their demands to be debated by
the Supreme Soviet legislature and be put on the agenda of the next
Congress of People's Deputies, scheduled to be held before the end
of the year.
   He said the political demands were not aimed specifically at
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev but at constititional changes for
the future.
   The miners are calling for their demands to be debated by the
Supreme Soviet legislature and put on the agenda of the next
Congress of People's Deputies, scheduled to be held before the end
of the year.
   Alexei Bokharev, chairman of the Donetsk strike committee in the
Ukraine, said in a telephone interview the government was playing
bureaucratic games. They said that only three paragraphs in the
46-paragraph agreement reached over the summer had been fulfilled.
   ``The miners want exact dates when all (promises) will be
fulfilled,'' Bokharev said.
   He said miners will decide Friday on a course of action.
``Either the strike will be resumed or a conciliation commission
will be appointed,'' Bokharev said.
   On Monday, about 20,000 miners in the western Siberian mining
town of Mezhdurechensk staged a two-hour warning strike, declaring
that the government had failed to come through on some of the
promised benefits from the summer strikes.
   Local officials in Mezhdurechensk said the miners had shown
disrespect for the new law, but they took no other action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
