<SECOND>PM-Israel-SAfrica, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0549,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Deny Israel Helping Pretoria With Nuclear Missile</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with U.S. saying South Africa
and Israel have cooperated on missiles; picks up 5th pvs: Israel's Defense
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN SCHECHET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir today denied
reports that Israel provided technology for a nuclear-capable
missile that reportedly was test-fired in South Africa in July.
   Shamir told Israel Radio there was ``no truth'' to the NBC
television news report, which said Israel has been engaged in a
partnership with South Africa to develop nuclear missile capability.
   ``We totally deny this story,'' said Shamir's media adviser, Avi
Pazner. ``There is no nuclear link or cooperation between Israel
and South Africa.''
   South Africa's foreign minister, Pik Botha, said: ``I bear no
knowledge whatsoever of such cooperation.''
   In Washington, however, a U.S. official said today that South
Africa has test-fired an intermediate-range ballistic missile that
could carry nuclear warheads and was built with help from Israel.
   Israel and South Africa are also cooperating in development of a
long-range missile that can be used to launch reconnaissance
satellites into space, said the official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The U.S. official said intelligence reports showed South Africa
had tested a modified version of the Israeli-made Jericho II
medium-range missile at Armaston, on the Indian Ocean coast near
Capetown last summer.
   Israel's Defense Ministry spokesman, Eitan Haber, said his
country is adhering to a March 18, 1987, Cabinet decision that no
new defense contracts between Israel and South Africa be signed.
   NBC cited unidentified intelligence sources and a CIA document
in its report.
   It said Israel provides missile technology to South Africa in
return for a continuous supply of enriched uranium for its own
nuclear warheads and the use of the Overberg long-range test site
in South Africa.
   The network said the Overberg site and a missile assembly
building there were built for both countries and that Israeli
engineers have worked there for several years.
   The first test resulting from the joint project took place July
5 when a missile flew 900 miles southeast from the test site, NBC
quoted the CIA paper as saying.
   The document identified the South African state arms maker
Armscor as the builder of the missile and said Israeli technology
was provided through Urdan Industries Ltd., based outside Tel Aviv,
NBC reported.
   Reached by telephone, a secretary at Urdan said the company's
director general, Yaacov Ben Bassat, was out of the country and
could not be reached for comment.
   The British newspaper The Guardian published a report in June
that South Africa was preparing to test a medium-range nuclear
missile developed in cooperation with Israel.
   Trade and Industry Minister Ariel Sharon defended the principle
of Israeli cooperation with South Africa, recalling South Africa's
help when Israel was facing Arab-inspired boycotts.
   ``But on this matter, we have a government decision and we are
acting in accordance,'' he said.
</TEXT>
