<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     10-26 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokesman Says Martial Law to be Lifted Soon in Beijing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martial law, entering its sixth month in Beijing,
will be lifted soon, the People's Daily newspaper reported Thursday.
   ``I cannot offer a timetable,'' government spokesman Yuan Mu
told the newspaper. ``(Martial law) is for a limited time and it
seems that it will be lifted before very long.''
   He said the government already had reduced the scope of martial
law ``and will continue to do so'' as the capital becomes more
stable.
   Yuan spoke Wednesday with journalists from the Nihon Keizai
Shimbun, Japan's leading economic newspaper.
   He noted that many foreigners have urged martial law be lifted
in order to increase confidence in the government.
   ``We understand their feelings and will consider their
suggestion,'' he said, but added that China would not yield to
sanctions or other pressures. Although Western countries have never
listed conditions, diplomats say privately that they are unlikely
to resume normal relations with China until martial law is lifted.
   Premier Li Peng declared martial law in most of Beijing on May
20, when tens of thousands of college students occupied Tiananmen
Square in the city center and demanded democratic reform. However,
it was enforced only after June 3-4, when the army shot its way
into the city, killing hundreds and perhaps thousands of people.
   Under martial law, the army banned marches, strikes, class
boycotts, giving speeches, distributing pamphlets, spreading rumors
and ``other destructive actions.''
   It also banned foreign reporters from conducting interviews or
making tapes or shooting videotape on the streets or at government
offices, schools and factories. Enforcement of the ban has relaxed
since midsummer, but all interviews still must be approved by
martial law headquarters.
   Martial law has helped keep tourists away even though soldiers
are visible at only a few key places. They still guard Tiananmen
Square, and still occupy the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences,
many of whose researchers were active in the protests.
   An undetermined number remain camped in several courtyards of
the former imperial palace, now a musuem. Soldiers also are posted
prominently in the university district.
   Squads of nearly 100 soldiers, four abreast, periodically jog
down Beijing's main street, their automatic weapons slung over
their shoulders.
   Gunfire still rings out at night, but there is never official
explanation. Residents claim at least some of the shots have been
civilian attacks on soldiers.
   Yuan also welcomed a recent statement by the French foreign
minister that France does not allow people on its territory to
conduct political activities against countries that France
recognizes.
   ``We hope France is as good as its word,'' Yuan said. However,
France has made similar statements in the past without strictly
enforcing the policy.
   China repeatedly has condemned France for giving haven to many
dissidents who fled China after the June crackdown.
   Yuan refused to comment on movement in Hungary and Poland away
from communism, but said socialist reform aims to improve and
develop the sociaist system, and ``cannot deviate from the track of
socialism.''
   On Monday, Li told the vice president of Yugoslavia's federal
Executive Council, Zivko Pregl, that China was greatly concerned
about events in some East European countries. But he said each
country must decide how to follow the socialist path.
   In internal debates, some Chinese theorists have begun referring
to Hungary and Poland as revisionist, meaning backsliders in the
socialist cause. But the word has not been used publicly.
</TEXT>
