<FIRST>u a PM-PlantExplosions 1stLd-Writethru a0486 10-26 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plant Explosions, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three More Bodies Found; Cause of Huge Blast Undetermined</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd graf, `Investigators in...' to UPDATE
with hydrocarbon leak detected and slowing search efforts. Picks up 4th
graf, `Even experts...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crews clearing tons of wreckage left by a
huge plastics plant explosion found three bodies, bringing the
number of confirmed dead to five, and continued to search today for
17 people believed killed.
   Elsewhere, two industrial plant explosions in Wyoming and
Connecticut killed one man and injured 12.
   Investigators in Texas have not determined the cause of the
series of explosions Monday at the Phillips Petroleum Co. plant,
which produced 4.5 million pounds of plastic a day.
   At midday today, safety crews discovered a reactor leaking
hydrocarbon gas. Several reporters and television crews were asked
to move a few hundred yards back from the cleanup area.
   ``We asked the press to move back as non-members of the search
team,'' Phillips spokesman Scott Carlberg said. ``We are taking an
extremely conservative safety measure. But we see no danger of
explosion.''
   Even experts were surprised at the extent of the destruction,
apparently touched off somehow in leaking ethylene and isobutane
gas.
   ``It's total devastation,'' said Assistant U.S. Labor Secretary
John Scannell, who heads the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration.
   ``In 30 years of experience in the chemical industry, I've never
seen such massive equipment twisted and strung about,'' said
Scannell, who toured the plant on the Houston Ship Channel on
Wednesday.
   Fifteen OSHA investigators joined Phillips workers cleaning up
the plant and searching for the cause of the explosion.
   The clean-up continued around the clock, with big floodlights
illuminating the scene at night as workers used hydraulic shears,
cranes and other heavy equipment to cut through a tangle of metal
beams and pipes.
   Of the three bodies found Wednesday, two were near a storage
area for polyethylene pellets manufactured at the plant, said
company spokesman Bill Wicker. The third was in a maintenance area.
Two others were found Monday and Tuesday.
   An official of the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers union said
plant employees had complained that staff shortages, long hours and
an abundance of workers from outside contractors could have caused
lapses in safety procedures.
   The official, Bob Wages, vice president of the OCAW's oil
section, didn't have specific safety complaints about the plant.
   ``It's symptomatic of what's going on in this industry,'' Wages
said of the complaints. ``I think companies are concerned about
safety, but I think they have competing interests: profit and
production.''
   A natural gas explosion in August killed a worker at the plant.
Union officials said the accident was an example of poorly trained
contract labor possibly endangering Phillips workers.
   Plant manager Robert Benz discounted any possible connection
between the use of contract workers and the two explosions. He said
contract workers get safety seminars twice a month.
   Scannell said the recovery of victims could take weeks. Part of
the problem is that when one piece of wreckage is moved, it sets
off a chain reaction of falling debris, he said.
   Outside Evanston, Wyo., a natural gas blast at an Amoco
Production Co. gas processing plant blew out a wall and threw
workers out of the building. One man was killed and 11 injured,
including five in serious condition today with burns, authorities
said.
   Investigators were trying to determine what caused natural gas
to leak from a compressor building, said Amoco spokesman Dick
Brewster.
   In New Haven, Conn., an explosion at a chemical and insulation
plant left one man with serious burns. The fire that followed the
blast at the Acme Division of the Allied Products Corp. was quickly
put out with dry chemicals stored inside the plant, said Fire Chief
John Riordan, who said the cause was under investigation.
</TEXT>
