<FIRST>u w PM-US-CentralAmerica 3rdLd-Writethru a0604 10-26 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Central America, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0604,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Headed to Western Hemisphere Meeting, Renews Embargo Against
Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material with Bush coments on Ortega, editing throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he is ``not uptight''
about attending a multinational meeting with Daniel Ortega but
would be ``very firm'' if he encounters the Marxist president of
Nicaragua.
   The administration is renewing a trade embargo against Nicaragua
and complaining to the Soviets that Ortega is exporting revolution.
   ``I have no agenda with Mr. Ortega'' but ``we're not going down
there to have some battle with Mr. Ortega,'' Bush said in an
interview with Latin American journalists Wednesday, the transcript
of which was released today. ``I'm not uptight about his being
there.''
   Bush said ``what we don't want to do is inject a lot of regional
tensions into their meeting. But I'm going to be polite, charming _
if I did have an encounter (with Ortega), it would be very firm
because I don't see why that one Sandinista regime is swimming
against the tide'' of democracy.
   ``And everybody knows we have a tense relationship, so I don't
want to act like we're waltzing around there in great harmony,
because we're not,'' Bush said.
   Plans were abandoned for a group communique from the summit
participants on general themes of democracy and the environment,
which had been proposed by the host government for the meeting
Friday and Saturday of hemispheric leaders.
   ``The U.S. objected to signing any statement with Daniel
Ortega,'' said one senior administration official, adding that
other countries also had raised concerns about the document's
contents.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged today
that ``that attitude was generally conveyed'' to the Costa Ricans
regarding Ortega. But he said, ``The Ortega aspect of this is being
totally overblown, at least in terms of our planning.''
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III on Wednesday criticized
Nicaragua in the face of claims by conservatives that Bush will be
giving a stamp of legitimacy to the leftist Sandinista regime by
attending the meeting with Ortega in Costa Rica.
   Baker, who also will attend the meeting in Costa Rica,
castigated the preparations for Nicaragua's Feb. 25 elections as
unfair to the Sandinistas' opposition, saying the opponents did not
have adequate access to the country's media.
   But Elliot Richardson, United Nations Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar's representative for monitoring the campaign, told
reporters Wednesday the Supreme Electoral Council ``has been
performing in a conscientious, fair and impartial manner.''
   ``It is certainly my impression, and I think that I speak for
all of us representing the United Nations in Nicaragua, that the
goal of a free, fair and honest election is being taken seriously
by all those concerned, in the government, in the parties, and
among the people,'' Richardson said.
   Baker also said Nicaragua is still shipping Soviet-bloc arms to
Marxist rebels in neighboring El Salvador, and called that a
``major problem'' despite repeated Soviet and Nicaraguan denials.
   The administration contacted the Soviets on Wednesday, Baker
said, to complain about the activity in light of Soviet assurances
that Moscow would urge a stop to such shipments.''
   Also Wednesday, Bush extended for another six months a U.S.
trade embargo against Nicaragua that was imposed by President
Reagan in mid-1985.
   He did it because Nicaragua poses ``an unusual and extraordinary
threat to national security and foreign policy of the United
States,'' Bush said in a statement to Congress.
   Bush must report to Congress twice a year on the status of the
embargo and on U.S.-Nicaraguan relations.
   Bush will be one of 18 heads of state attending the two-day
celebration of 100 years of democracy in Costa Rica. Participants
will all be seated around a common table for lunch, dinner and a
lengthy working session Friday.
   Administration officials say the president will not go out of
his way to be discourteous to Ortega but will not hold private
talks with him.
   ``I doubt he would refuse to speak if spoken to, but he's not
going to meet with him and he's not going to be extending any
particular courtesies in that direction,'' Baker told reporters at
the White House.
   Nicaragua has unsuccessfully sought talks with the United
States. The administration is trying to bolster opposition efforts
to win next year's elections.
   Bush and Ortega exchanged greetings and shook hands in 1986 at
the Guatemalan inauguration of President Vinicio Cerezo, when Bush
headed the U.S. delegation. They did not converse.
   Bush also will meet in Costa Rica with Ortega's election
opponent, Violeta Chamorro, at a breakfast for political leaders.
</TEXT>
