<FIRST>u w PM-Senate-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0587 10-26 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0587,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Says Aid Will Be Delayed By Decision to Inject Capital Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new to include White House reaction. Picks up 7th
graf pvs, Dole contended.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aid to Poland and Hungary will be delayed and
perhaps killed by a Republican attempt to inject capital gains tax
reductions into the aid debate, Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell said today.
   ``Obviously the capital gains issue has nothing to do with aid
to Eastern Europe,'' the Maine Democrat told the Senate.
``Obviously the only effect can be to delay and perhaps kill aid to
Poland and Hungary.''
   He called the GOP's decision to inject capital gains into the
aid debate one of a series of ``unwise and almost baffling'' steps
that President Bush and the Republicans have taken.
   But Republican leader Bob Dole accused Democrats of injecting
partisan politics into the debate over the size of the aid package
and said Republicans had no choice but to seek action on capital
gains on every possible bill.
   ``Options on this side for at least a look at capital gains are
shrinking daily,'' the Kansas Republican said. ``It finally
occurred to us that if we didn't act on this bill we would be shut
out entirely.''
   Sen. Robert Packwood, R-Ore., introduced the capital gains tax
reduction bill as an amendment to the aid package during debate
Wednesday night.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater offered a
less-than-enthusiastic endorsement of Packwood's strategy, saying
the administration was ``generally supportive'' of his proposal.
``We're willing to go along with it.''
   Fitzwater said the decision to link capital gains with aid to
Poland and Hungary was made on Capitol Hill, and that the
administration did not have much advance warning about it.
Stressing that the administration wants a vote on a capital gains
tax cut, Fitzwater said, ``We're certainly willing to see what
happens.''
   Dole contended that while Republicans will ``stand our ground''
on the capital gains issue, the delay will not affect aid to Poland
and Hungary over the long run.
   But it will have the beneficial effect of further focusing
attention on the wisdom of adopting a costly Democratic plan to
provide nearly $1 billion in aid to Poland and Hungary over three
years, the GOP leader said.
   Dole asserted that the less costly Republican approach has more
safeguards against funneling the money to ``failed socialist
enterprises.''
   ``We are not reducing our sympathy to Poland or to the
Solidarity movement,'' Dole said. ``We are not denying anything to
Poland,''
   But Mitchell said leaders of Poland's non-communist government
``have stressed the importance of prompt action as much as the
nature and level of the assistance itself.''
   Noting that winter is coming on, that food shortages persist and
that inflation is skyrocketing, Mitchel said: ``This is one of
those cases where assistance provided too late will be of no
assistance at all.''
   ``The administration has made clear that it believes the capital
gains reduction is more important than aid to Poland and Hungary,''
Mitchell said.
   ``Surely the brave leaders of Solidarity who have struggled so
hard to restore democracy to Poland know that this assistance is
needed in a timely fashion,'' he said.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont and other Democrats said the
president has offered Eastern Europe encouragement but no real or
solid commitment as it begins to move away from communism and
toward democracy and free enterprise.
   ``Why is this administration so willing to commit billions for
war but only small change for peace?'' Leahy asked.
   Republicans contended no solution will be found to Poland's
serious economic problems by ``throwing money'' at them, and that
the GOP's less costly approach is the more responsible, practical
and prudent course.
   Dole accused Democrats of an ill-advised and risky attempt to
flood Eastern Europe with U.S. taxpayer dollars.
   ``We have to be very careful and pragmatic about what we propose
to do,'' Dole said. ``There should not be a contest about how much
money we can drag out of the U.S. Treasury.''
   But even some Republicans endorsed the costlier Democratic aid
measure as an essential step.
   ``Events are changing quickly, and we must change our policies
with equal speed,'' said Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H. ``We must
grasp this opportunity before it slips away. I say let's go for it
and go for it aggressively.''
   The Republican version of the three-year authorization would
provide a total $585 million, more than $100 million over the $451
million assistance proposed by Bush.
   The Democrats, however, seek approval for $989 million in aid
over the three-year period, nearly $150 million more than the $840
million approved by the House last week.
   Their measure includes $125 million in food aid, $200 million in
currency stabilization loans, $200 million in trade credit
insurance guarantees, $40 million in environmental aid and $320
million for Poland and $80 million for Hungary to promote
development of private enterprise.
</TEXT>
