<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1419EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-France-Moslems     10-26 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Moslems,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Few Happy With Education Minister's Decision on Moslem Scarf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The education minister fired another shot in the
Scarf War by deciding Moslem girls can wear Islamic head coverings
to school, and a newspaper said Thursday he was trying to
``reconcile the irreconcilable.''
   At issue is the law barring religion from French public schools,
and to some extent the situation of immigrants.
   Education Minister Lionel Jospin appeared bent on satisfying
everyone in his comments to Parliament on Wednesday and in a
magazine interview published Thursday, but in the end seems to have
satisfied hardly anyone.
   Roman Catholic, Moslem and Jewish leaders in France generally
see no harm in the wearing of religious symbols to class, but in
political circles the secularity of schools is nearly a religion in
itself.
   The controversy began this month when three girls in a town
north of Paris decided to wear ``hijab'' scarves covering hair,
ears and neck to their junior high classes. The principal said they
could not, that doing so amounted to proselytizing in school, which
is illegal.
   Jospin told Parliament that school authorities should try to
persuade the students and their families to ``respect the
secularity of the school,'' but if that failed, ``the school must
accept and welcome them.''
   He also stressed, however, ``the firm and absolute refusal that
must be applied to all proselytism.''
   Teachers' unions were particularly unhappy and some members of
Jospin's own Socialist Party were clearly discomfited.
   In an interview with Le Nouvel Observateur, published Thursday,
the minister said: ``There is no threat to the French Republic by
fundamentalist Islam. If this republic doesn't know how to respond
in a humanitarian way to a handful of young girls wearing scarves,
I would be worried.''
   Liberation, a leftist daily, described Jospin as ``a minister of
education, alone in the tempest, abandoned even by part of his own
(party), who is trying to reconcile the irreconcilable.''
   It said the conservative opposition was tempted to take up the
issue, ``but doesn't quite know how to grab it.''
   Le Quotidien de Paris, a conservative paper, said Jospin's
decision ``is both against tradition and against the law.''
   Church and state were officially separated in this largely
Catholic country in 1905. Public schools are required to be
completely neutral about religion.
   ``This business is going to have many consequences because we
have begun a process of confrontation with Islam of which we are
seeing only the first symptoms,'' said Jean-Marie Le Pen, leader of
the extreme-right National Front party, which opposes immigration.
   ``I say that the right to wear a religious symbol must be total
on the condition that it is discreet,'' he said, ``but the chador
is more than that; it is a provocative proclamation, and that we
cannot accept.''
   In the debate, many people use the terms veil, chador and scarf
interchangeably. The item in question is a simple scarf covering
only the hair, while the chador is an ankle-length cloak.
   Yannick Simpron, head of the National Education Federation, the
largest teachers' unions and a pillar of Socialist Party support,
said he was waiting for written instructions from the Education
Ministry.
   ``Lionel Jospin proposes to negotiate in cases of wearing the
Islamic veil, but, says the minister, if at the end of the
discussions the families do not agree to give up this religious
symbol, the child must be accepted,'' Simpron declared. ``Where is
the margin for negotiation when the outcome is known?``
   Some see the wearing of scarves as an attempt to slow the
emancipation of Moslem women, not just a religious custom.
   In Parliament, Jospin said: ``For these young Moslem girls,
school is their only chance to emancipate themselves. They have no
other alternative.''
   Among those welcoming his decisino was radical lawyer Jacques
Verges, who represents several Moslem families.
   ``We won,'' he said in an interview. ``Secularity means the
neutrality of teachers, not the neutrality of students. The law
calls for the prohibition of all proselytism. It does not talk
about living a faith.''
</TEXT>
