<FIRST>r i AM-Reagan     10-26 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Thanks Japanese for Aid to California Quake Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan met Thursday with 13 university
students who have volunteered to help Californians clean up after
the earthquake, and said they were among the ``most inspiring''
young people he had ever met.
   The former president had no official appearances scheduled for
Thursday. His wife, Nancy, was interviewed on a television network
owned by the Fujisankei Communications Group, which engaged the
Reagans for the nine-day visit and is reported to be paying them $2
million.
   Fujisankei, Japan's largest media conglomerate, has not
confirmed the fee, but company officials have said the visit is
costing about $7 million.
   The Reagans and their Japanese hosts have used the opportunity
to praise the close ties between the two nations, and have avoided
mentioning thorny trade problems.
   Of his encounter with the Chuo University students, Reagan said:
   ``I have just met with one of the most inspiring groups of young
people I have ever encountered. Their trip to San Francisco is a
most eloquent statement about the special friendship between the
people of Japan and the people of the United States.''
   In her TV interview, Mrs. Reagan said: ``We're very grateful to
the Japanese people for what they've done, for the assistance
they've given'' since the earthquake struck last week.
   Japanese companies and individuals are reported to have pledged
$7 million in aid. Several groups of Japanese, like the Chuo
students, have volunteered to help repair the damage.
   After the meeting with Reagan, a student with short hair smiled
and said: ``He pointed at my head and commented that we had similar
haircuts.''
   Reagan's head was shaved when he underwent surgery Sept. 8 to
drain fluid from his brain because of an injury suffered while
riding horseback in July.
   ``Everyone tells him that he looks much younger, that he looks
about 16 years old,'' Mrs. Reagan said of her husband's hair style.
``But I'm having a little bit of a hard time getting used to it.''
   Reagan used two days of the visit to meet with current and
former Japanese government officials, but devotes most of his time
to appearances arranged by Fujisankei.
</TEXT>
