<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Relief     10-26 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Relief,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Building Supplies Arrive, Officials Concerned More Needed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three railroad boxcars of plywood from
the Pacific Northwest arrived Thursday in what officials called the
largest single donation of building materials since Hurricane Hugo
struck.
   But as shipments of relief supplies begin to taper off five
weeks after the storm, Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. said he is
concerned about meeting the needs of a rebuilding effort that could
take as long as two years.
   ``The city is coming back but the great problem is housing,''
Riley said. ``We're going to be rebuilding homes in the aftermath
of Hugo for a couple of years. We need money and building supplies
in tremendous quantities.''
   The storm destroyed 3,437 homes and caused major damage to
13,757 in the Charleston area, said Howard Chapman, who is
coordinating the city's relief effort.
   Local homebuilders could build only about 8,000 new homes in the
Charleston area in a year, Chapman said.
   ``That gives you an idea of the magnitude of how long it's going
to take,'' he said.
   ``It's going to take a long, long, time,'' Riley agreed.
   The donated plywood will be used to repair homes both in
Charleston and outlying areas hard-hit by Hugo, which smashed into
the state with 135 mph winds on Sept. 21.
   The materials will be used in part by Charleston's Heartline
program and Charleston County's Raise the Roof Program in which
volunteers help make repairs to damaged homes for those who can't
afford such repairs.
   ``The classic example would be the poor family which has no
insurance _ they don't have insurance because they don't have a lot
of things. In some instances, insurance was hard to get because
they were in a rural area that didn't have a fire department,'' the
mayor said.
   Some people may be eligible for money from the Federal Emergency
Management Agency and in those cases ``what we're trying to do is
fill the gaps,'' Riley said.
   The boxcars of plywood were shipped by a group known as the
Oregon Lands Coalition, which represents 10 organizations in both
Washington and Oregon, said Rita Kaley of Hood River, Ore.
   ``We really want it to go to the people in need, but of course
everyone is in need right now,'' she said.
   Part of the shipment was donated by Stevenson Co-Ply Inc. of
Stevenson, Wash., and one of the boards was autographed by workers
at the plant.
   Above the signatures was a message which read: ``Our thoughts go
with you in your crisis.''
</TEXT>
