<FIRST>u a PM-FarmBodies     10-26 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Bodies,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourth Body Found in Search of Farm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSH LEMIEUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fourth body has been found after 2{
weeks of digging and searching near the farm of an elderly couple
charged with conspiracy to steal cattle.
   The body of an unidentified man was found Wednesday evening in a
shallow grave in a barn about three miles northeast of Ludlow, in
northwestern Missouri. Three unidentified men were found 10 days
earlier buried at a farm several miles away.
   The digging started Oct. 9 after Ray Copeland, 75, and his wife,
Faye Copeland, 68, were arrested in the alleged cattle swindle.
   No charges have been filed in the four deaths. Authorities have
not named the Copelands as murder suspects but have said they are
searching for a number of transients who may have stayed with the
Copelands.
   Joe Ray Adams, 62, owner of the 860-acre farm where the body was
found Wednesday, said Copeland had worked for the previous owner as
the farm manager. Adams said the body, clad in boots and a heavy
coat, was wrapped in plastic and buried in a shallow grave under
bales of hay in a metal barn. He said the body was found under
small square bales of hay that had been stacked in the barn while
Copeland still worked at the farm and some large round bales that
Adams had added since he purchased the farm.
   An examination Wednesday night in Chillicothe did not determine
a cause of death, and the remains were being sent to Columbia for
further study, said Greg Coon, spokesman for the North Central
Missouri Major Case Squad.
   The decomposed bodies of three men were found Oct. 16 in shallow
graves in a barn on a farm near Ludlow where Copeland had done odd
jobs. Authorities said the men, between the ages of 20 and 32, had
been shot in the head.
   Earlier digging and searches by bloodhounds and officers
uncovered no bodies on the Copelands' 40-acre farm about 12 miles
north of where the three bodies were found, or about 90 miles
northeast of Kansas City.
   The Copelands were jailed on $25,000 bond each on charges that
they bought cattle with a check that bounced, then failed to make
good on the check.
</TEXT>
