<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1603EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WasteTrain     10-26 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waste Train,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Pooh Pooh Choo Choo' Headed Back To Baltimore, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPOLEONVILLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local officials raised a stink about
it, so a waste disposal company decided against accepting a train
loaded with smelly sewage sludge from Baltimore and sent it back.
   ``They took the `pooh pooh choo-choo' where it belongs. They
took it out of this parish,'' said Jim Simmons, president of the
Police Jury, the governing body of Assumption Parish.
   GSX Land Treatment Inc. had subcontracted with an engineering
firm to take the nonhazardous sewer sludge from a failed Baltimore
composting firm that bought the 12,000 tons of sludge from the city
of Baltimore. That city is under a state order to dispose of
200,000 tons of sludge by the end of November.
   GSX had intended to dispose of the sludge at its ``land farm''
in nearby White Castle, La. _ essentially a landfill where
non-hazardous waste is plowed into the ground. Some cities process
sewer sludge and sell it as fertilizer or soil conditioner.
   But residents of Assumption Parish complained vehemently about
the stench of the train, which also had passed through
Donaldsonville in Ascension Parish.
   The company moved its unloading operation to a less populated
site near Labadieville after Donaldsonville city attorney Sidney
Marchand filed a motion in court to stop the operation.
   After District Attorney Donald Carmouche threatened to do the
same thing on behalf of the Assumption Parish Police Jury, GSX
agreed to keep its unloading operation out of the area.
   Although GSX did accept 27 cars full of the sludge, it sent 63
others cars back and agreed it wouldn't take an additional 110 cars
not yet shipped to Louisiana.
   Carmouche said the waste train pulled out of the area Wednesday
and was headed back to Maryland, although there was no confirmation
of its destination from Baltimore officials or GSX.
   ``For the first time, Baltimore waste is going where it belongs
_ Baltimore,'' Carmouche told the Police Jury.
   Disposing of sewer waste isn't illegal in Louisiana, but
officials said they objected to taking out-of-state waste _
especially out-of-state waste that smelled so bad.
   GSX facility manager Dan Martin said the company was spending
more than anticipated trying to keep the sludge from smelling.
   Joseph Harrison, manager and vice president of Supreme Sugar in
Assumption Parish, said he's glad the controversy is over and that
the smells from the waste train aren't mixing with the strong odors
from his company's refinery.
   ``Pooh pooh and sugar don't go together,'' he told the Police
Jury.
   Earlier this month, five smelly railroad cars full of rotting
household trash were sent back to Philadelphia after Indiana
officials won a court order blocking a plan to dump the garbage in
their state. That garbage was headed for a landfill near Brazil,
Ind., but the state said the four companies involved in carting the
trash lacked a permit allowing it to be transferred from railroad
cars to dump trucks.
   That wasn't Philadelphia's first problem with long-distance
disposal. A freighter sailed the seas for two years searching for a
place to dump 14,000 tons of ash from city incinerators. The load
was rejected by 11 countries before the ship turned up empty in
Singapore late in 1988, after changing names and owners.
   Before that, a barge loaded with trash from New York's Long
Island was rejected by states down the Atlantic and Gulf coasts and
Central American nations before it was sent back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
