<DOCNO> AP891026-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1606EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CDC-Cancer     10-26 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC-Cancer,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cases Of Colorectal Cancer Up, But Fewer Are Fatal</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release at 6 p.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deaths from colon and rectal cancer, diseases
that kill about 55,000 Americans a year, are highest along an
unexplained line from Maine to Iowa, U.S. cancer specialists said
Thursday.
   The national Centers for Disease Control reported that the
highest mortality rates from colorectal cancer occurred in the
Northeast and the eastern north-central states _ from Maine, with a
death rate of 25.8 per 100,000 people in 1986; south to Maryland,
with 27.2; across to Iowa, with 24.8; and in virtually every state
in between.
   The District of Columbia had the nation's highest mortality rate
at 32.1.
   Nationwide, the mortality rate from colorectal cancer has been
declining and is now 23.1 per 100,000; 55,811 Americans died of the
disease in 1986, the CDC said.
   In the Northeast, only Connecticut at 24.5, Delaware at 23.8,
and Vermont at 22.4 had colorectal cancer death rates below 25 per
100,000. Other high rates were New Hampshire, 26.1; Massachusetts,
26.3; New York, 27.3; New Jersey, 27.1; Rhode Island, 28.7;
Pennsylvania, 26.6; Ohio, 26.4; Indiana, 25.9; and Illinois, 25.6.
   No other state exceeded a rate of 24.
   Wyoming had the lowest rate at 16.2, the Atlanta-based CDC
reported.
   The pattern _ more cancer deaths in the Northeast, fewer in the
West _ resembles one researchers have already seen in heart
disease, but they don't know why, said Dr. Robert A. Hahn, a CDC
cancer researcher.
   ``We don't know enough about the risk factors or their
distribution to say why that region is one with the highest
rates,'' Hahn said. ``We doubt it's just a matter of physical
environment, but we just don't know.''
   While few risk factors for colorectal cancer ``have been firmly
established,'' evidence points to high-fat diets as risky and
suggests that fruits and vegetables may help protect against the
disease, the CDC said.
   Obesity and a high-calorie lifestyle also may increase the risk,
while exercise may lower it, the CDC added.
   Approximately 145,000 colorectal cancer cases are diagnosed in
the United States each year, Hahn estimated.
   Colorectal cancer accounted for 12 percent of all cancer deaths
in the United States in 1986. Incidence of the disease has risen in
recent years, from a rate of 49.3 cases per 100,000 Americans in
1979 to 50.5 in 1986, Hahn said.
   But the mortality rate has dropped, from 24.8 deaths per 100,000
in 1979 to 23.1 in 1986.
   ``Detection of disease at an earlier stage might account for
some of the increase in survival,'' the CDC said. ``Stool blood
screening ..., (a) non-invasive and relatively inexpensive
technique, appears to detect a higher proportion of colorectal
cancers at earlier stages.''
   The CDC also noted that ``colorectal cancer is primarily a
cancer of the older population.'' The median age of diagnosis from
1982-86 was 71 years for cancer of the colon and 69 for rectal
cancer.
   Only three in 100,000 30-to-34-year-olds developed colorectal
cancer, compared to 532 in 100,000 in the 85-and-older category.
   The case rate in 1986 was 61 per 100,000 for men, compared with
43 per 100,000 for women.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1518EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-Poland     10-26 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Poland,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Says Capital Gains Move Will Delay Aid to Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republicans' new move to cut the capital
gains tax could delay or even kill Congress' unrelated effort to
provide aid to Poland and Hungary, Senate Democratic Leader George
Mitchell said Thursday.
   Republicans, meanwhile, said they were determined to force the
capital gains issue to an up-or-down vote to redeem one of
President Bush's principal campaign promises.
   The White House showed little enthusiasm for the GOP move,
merely expressing a willingness ``to go along.''
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, accusing Democrats
of ``pure politics'' and ``crying wolf,'' said the GOP might also
use the capital-gains issue as a bargaining chip in negotiations to
reduce the cost of the $989 million Democratic aid package for
Eastern Europe. The Republicans want a $585 million total.
   Sen. Robert Packwood, R-Ore, introduced the tax-cut proposal _
fiercely opposed by the Senate's Democratic leadership _ as an
amendment to the aid bill. The move late Wednesday halted all
action on the measure.
   Packwood said on Thursday that a majority of senators, including
several Democrats, favor a cut. But he acknowledged he does not
have the 60 votes needed to shut off a filibuster.
   Mitchell, D-Maine, told the Senate, ``Obviously the capital
gains issue has nothing to do with aid to Eastern Europe. Obviously
the only effect can be to delay and perhaps kill aid to Poland and
Hungary.''
   Mitchell, who later said the delay in passage of the
authorization bill could stall action for a week, called the GOP's
move ``unwise and almost baffling.''
   The leaders of Poland's non-communist government ``have stressed
the importance of prompt action as much as the nature and level of
the assistance itself,'' the majority leader said.
   Noting that winter is approaching, and that inflation is
skyrocketing, Mitchell said: ``This is one of those cases where
assistance provided too late will be of no assistance at all.''
   ``The administration has made clear that it believes the capital
gains reduction is more important than aid to Poland and Hungary,''
Mitchell said.
   But Dole, noting that food aid already is on the way to Poland,
said delaying the bill will have no negative impact, especially
since it is an authorization and does not actually appropriate any
money for the two countries.
   ``All of this wringing of hands is pure politics,'' Dole said.
``It's the old Democratic game of crying wolf.''
   Although Dole insisted he would force the matter to a
conclusion, the White House appeared only mildly enthusiastic.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration was ``generally supportive'' of the Packwood-Dole
strategy and was ``willing to go along with it.''
   Fitzwater said the decision to link capital gains with aid to
Poland and Hungary was made on Capitol Hill, and that the
administration did not have much advance warning. Stressing that
the administration does want a vote on a capital gains tax cut,
Fitzwater said, ``We're certainly willing to see what happens.''
</TEXT>
