<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1656EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People     10-26 0952</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0990</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Second item for release at 6 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home improvement guru Bob Vila, who advised
millions of viewers on the nuts and bolts of nuts and bolts on
``This Old House,'' will return to television in a nationally
syndicated show.
   The weekly half-hour program, tentatively titled ``Home Again
with Bob Vila,'' is scheduled to air next spring and will focus on
affordable do-it-yourself remodeling jobs.
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. announced Wednesday it will co-sponsor
and syndicate the show. Vila has also been signed as exclusive
spokesman for Sears home improvement products.
   Vila was host of the Emmy Award-winning ``This Old House'' on
the Public Broadcasting System from 1979 until last spring, when
his contract was not renewed.
   Daphne Noyes, publicist for ``This Old House,'' said Vila had
been doing commercials for a competitor of a major local
underwriter of the show.
   ``He had agreed to give up some of his commercial activities, if
we could indemnify him for the loss of income,'' she said. But the
producing station, WGBH-TV in Boston, chose not to do so, and
decided not to renew his contract.
   Vila's agent Rob Feiner said the bitterness Vila felt after
being forced to leave PBS has disappeared.
   ``He's looking to the future now,'' Feiner said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Series television and a regular schedule fit
Jamie Lee Curtis' new lifestyle perfectly.
   Curtis, who stars in ``Anything But Love'' on ABC and whose
movies include ``Trading Places'' and ``A Fish Called Wanda,''
adopted a baby girl three years ago with her husband, actor and
writer Christopher Guest.
   ``I was hoping to do a series,'' Curtis said in the Oct. 29
issue of Parade magazine. ``I wanted stability. I'm a wife and
mother now, and I want to dedicate as much time to my family as to
my work.''
   Curtis, unable to have children of her own, says, ``A woman who
can't have a child is handicapped. You're unable to do something
that you want. But that doesn't mean you have to give up.''
   She has already told her daughter Annie she is adopted.
   ``I've told her that another woman had her but was unable to
take care of her,'' she says. ``I'm taking care of her, and I'm her
mom. I think the more you tell a child she's adopted, the more
she'll feel comfortable with it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rosalynn Carter says her husband is leading a
full life working on projects to fight famine and promote human
rights around the world.
   ``I don't think he could be more challenged,'' she said
Wednesday of former President Jimmy Carter in a speech sponsored by
the Atlanta Historical Society. ``It's really a satisfying life for
him.''
   Mrs. Carter said she and the former president have worked
together on a number of projects sponsored by the Carter
Presidential Center and have been helped by the Bush administration.
   ``We don't have to go through any red tape. President Bush has
leaned over backwards to help us, and that's been very helpful,''
she said.
   Carter's latest project has been mediating peace talks between
the Ethiopian government and a rebel group, the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Stevie Nicks says she's glad to be back in
her native Phoenix after her ``skateboard'' ride on the San
Francisco earthquake.
   Nicks said she was underground in an amphitheater in Concord,
Calif., about 20 miles northeast of San Francisco, preparing for a
show when the quake hit Oct 17.
   ``The ground actually started to move back and forth under my
feet like a skateboard. A few minutes later, our tour manager came
in and yelled, `Everybody out!,''' Nicks recalled. ``He grabbed me
and we and about 30 people went running up two flights of stairs.''
   Nicks said the concert, part of her first solo tour in three
years, was cancelled for fear of aftershocks.
   ``It got me pretty shook up. It makes you stop and take stock of
your life,'' said the 41-year-old Nicks.
   ``That's why I couldn't wait to get back to Phoenix. I need to
be home, to be in my beautiful desert.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Also moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of New York Giants linebacker
Lawrence Taylor has filed for divorce after eight years of
marriage, her attorney said Thursday.
   ``She is seeking a divorce on the basis of cruelty which began
in 1983 and has been continuing recently,'' Michael K. Diamond said.
   In the divorce complaint, Deborah Belinda Taylor said Taylor
once appeared at a family function with another woman, and was
drunk and made a scene at the hospital when she was in labor with
their third child.
   The complaint said Taylor's much publicized cocaine problem,
which Taylor had claimed he kicked by playing golf, was no longer a
factor.
   ``Drugs were once a problem but that is a thing of the past,''
said Diamond.
   Steve Rosner, Taylor's business manager, said, ``It's a personal
matter, and as far as Lawrence and I are concerned, it will stay a
personal matter.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Gerald R. Ford was
awarded an honorary associate's degree Thursday from Grand Rapids
Junior College at a national conference of community and junior
colleges.
   College President Richard Calkins said he was ``embarrassed to
see that there were no honorary degrees from a community college''
on the former president's resume, which includes a long list of
honorary doctoral degrees.
   Ford, a former congressman from Grand Rapids, also was to
receive an honorary degree from St. Petersburg Junior College of
Florida, which is sponsoring the conference.
</TEXT>
