<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Church     10-26 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Church,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Religious Programming Begins on Polish TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic Church entered the
world of Polish prime-time television Thursday with the first
broadcast of a regular weekly religious show, believed to be the
first such program in Eastern Europe.
   The church, which claims more than 90 percent of Poles as
believers, has long sought access to television.
   But while coverage of such major religious events as papal
visits to Poland and Polish-born Pope John Paul II's Christmas Mass
had been permitted in recent years, the former Communist rulers
long balked at allowing regular religious programming.
   Finally, in connection with a new law establishing the legal
basis for the church's activities in Poland, an agreement allowing
the church television and radio programs was concluded in June with
the previous communist government.
   The Rev. Andrzej Koprowski, the host of the new show, said
before the broadcast that it answers the needs of the
overwhelmingly Catholic society which had listed a demand for
broadcast Masses in the labor upheaval that gave rise to Solidarity
in August 1980.
   Koprowski said the church wants ``to present the forms of its
presence in the world of culture, in social problems and on a world
scale.''
   On the show itself Koprowski, dressed in his black cassock,
welcomed Cardinal Jozef Glemp, the highest Roman Catholic authority
in Poland, who in turn blessed the program. The segment had been
recorded earlier in the day.
   ``I welcome television with great joy and hope, a television
which will broadcast programs of faith, programs of the church and
of believers,'' said Glemp, who wore a large silver cross around
his neck.
   ``I attach great hopes to this service. ... Today, technology,
especially in the mass media, helps us a lot and we would like to
be able to pass on a richness of spirit.''
   The program is being produced by a newly formed Religious
Programs Desk within the Episcopate, the administrative arm of
Poland's bishops.
   State TV said the programs are produced on church premises and
its only responsiblity is to broadcast the shows it receives from
the Episcopate.
   The 20-minute church programs are to be appear each Thursday at
6:25 p.m. on Polish Channel 1. In addition, Channel 2 will
broadcast a 20-minute ``evening prayer'' on Tuesdays at 6:30 p.m.
   Two months ago, the church began broadcasting weekly radio
programs.
   This has been a year of major achievements for the church with
the signing in May of a bill by parliament guaranteeing the right
of the church to operate legally.
   In addition to Glemp's blessing, the new show carried an
interview with Jerzy Turowicz, editor of the influential Catholic
weekly Tygodnik Powszechny, who battled with communist authorities
for years to keep publishing the paper he founded after World War
II.
   ``Television is a very powerful means of influencing people and
public opinion. It is a very valuable thing that the church in
Poland obtained the possibility to use this means. And it's very
important to take full advantage of this big chance,'' he said.
   Turowicz said he believed the program should not focus on church
liturgy and holiday celebrations, but that it should educate
society.
   It should be about ``problems that the church is living with,
which the church must face, about difficult problems which must be
solved and should give Catholics something to think about,''
Turowicz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
