<FIRST>r i AM-NgExtradition     10-26 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ng Extradition,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Orders Extradition of Reputed California Serial
Killer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The justice minister on Thursday ordered Charles
Ng extradited to the United States to face murder charges in a
string of sex-torture slayings.
   Ng still could appeal the ruling and continue his four-year
fight against extradition to California, where he is accused of
murdering 12 people.
   In a letter to defense lawyer Don MacLeod, Lewis rejected
defense arguments that he should refuse extradition unless
California agrees to refrain from imposing the death penalty on Ng.
   MacLeod had argued that the death penalty is cruel and inhumane
and that there is evidence it is applied in a racially biased
manner. He also raised questions about the jury selection process
and the independence of California judges.
   But Lewis concluded that the U.S. Constitution and criminal law
protect the rights of the accused.
   ``Canada accepts and has confidence in the body of criminal law
and the manner in which it is administered in the United States,''
said the minister.
   The fact that the death penalty has been abolished in Canada
does not make extradition impossible under the Canadian charter, he
said.
   If criminals knew that by fleeing to Canada they could escape a
death sentence elsewhere, ``Canada would become a safe haven for
such criminals. In my view, such a prospect is simply
unacceptable,'' he said.
   Ng, a native of Hong Kong who was educated in Britain and served
in the U.S. Marines, is charged with murder, kidnapping and
burglary in the deaths of 12 men, women and children.
   Eleven deaths involved sex slayings at a cabin 120 miles east of
San Francisco. The 12th involved the slaying of a San Francisco
disc jockey.
   Ng, 28, is serving a 4{-year sentence for shooting a security
guard in the hand in a bungled shoplifting attempt in Calgary in
1985. He has been fighting to avoid extradition upon completion of
his sentence.
   The Supreme Court of Canada, in a ruling delivered in August,
upheld lower court rulings in favor of extradition.
   Under the Canada-U.S. extradition treaty, the final decision
rests with the federal justice minister, who has the option of
refusing to extradite any prisoner unless American authorities
agree not to impose the death penalty.
   Now that Lewis has ruled in the case, his decision could in turn
be challenged in the courts in a second round of appeals.
   Ng came to Canada after his alleged accomplice in the
sex-and-torture slayings, Leonard Lake, was arrested for
shoplifting in San Francisco and subsequently committed suicide.
   Lake later was linked to the grisly killings and disappearances
of several people, and the investigation led to the charges against
Ng.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
