<DOCNO> AP891026-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Ruble     10-26 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ruble,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruble Devaluation Silence Leaves Experts Confused</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's failure to communicate clearly
the limits on a drastic devaluation of the ruble left confused
experts, businessmen and travelers scrambling for clarification
Thursday.
   Wednesday's announcement that the ruble would fall from $1.59 to
16 cents, but only for certain transactions, was of enormous
importance in international trade. But where most governments are
careful to speak quickly and precisely on such issues to avoid
upsetting markets, the Soviet bureaucracy dribbled out confusing,
conflicting tidbits of information.
   The original Tass announcement on Wednesday raised more
questions than it answered. It was only an Izvestia newspaper
article hours later that said the lower rate would apply to
foreigners and those Soviets going abroad, but not to commercial
transactions. Still, there were gaping holes left, and on Thursday,
officials offered contradictory clarifications.
   ``It doesn't seem to show a lot of coordination,'' one Western
diplomat said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Here we all
are, stumbling around trying to figure out what it means.''
   Several Westerners said they were told by highly placed Soviet
officials that foreign businessmen and diplomats living in Moscow
would enjoy the new, more favorable exchange rate.
   But Vladislav Lashinsky of the State Bank's protocol department
said the lower rate would apply only to foreign tourists, not to
foreign residents.
   Foreign businessmen were left to speculate whether they could
finance operations at the lower rate by bringing in tourists from
the home office once a month carrying cash. One diplomat wondered
if he would be able to buy a round-trip ticket from Moscow to New
York on Aeroflot for $150.
   Lashinsky also said the lower rate will affect only the
conversion of cash and traveler's checks, not purchases made by
credit card.
   Neither the government tourist agency Intourist nor the network
of state hard-currency stores were able to say how the new exchange
rate would affect their sales, which are priced in rubles but paid
in dollars or other hard currency.
   The change will help sop up some of the estimated 400 billion
rubles of unspendable savings that is contributing to the country's
severe shortages.
   Izvestia said the devaluation was designed to restrict a serious
drain on the national treasury's foreign currency reserves by
Soviet tourists flooding out to sample the once-forbidden fruits of
the West. Though each has been allowed to convert a mere 200 rubles
to foreign currency on leaving the country, they have been paid at
the official, lop-sided rate _ terrible for foreigners but great
for Soviets.
   ``When, thanks to new thinking and a new policy in the area of
human rights, thousands and hundreds of thousands of our citizens
have received the possibility of free exit, even the sale of a
limited sum of hard currency at a symbolic price in rubles presents
a serious financial problem,'' Izvestia said.
   The devaluation could be disastrous for Soviet tourists, who
instead of setting off overseas with $318 in their pockets will
have only $31.95 _ unless the government raises the 200-ruble limit
on how much they can exchange. The change is scheduled to take
effect Nov. 1.
   Even if the limit is altered, Soviets would have to pay 1,252
rubles _ or more than five months' average salary _ instead of 200
rubles to receive that same $318 in spending money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
