<FIRST>r a AM-WyoAmocoExplosion     10-26 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wyo Amoco Explosion,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four State Investigators Sent to Gas Explosion Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four state agents, including an arson
expert, began an investigation Thursday of an explosion at an Amoco
gas processing plant that killed one man and injured 11.
   ``The prime thing is to find out what happened and to see also
if there were any violations of OSHA rules,'' said Steve Foster,
assistant administrator for the state Occupational Health and
Safety Commission. That agency sent three investigators and the
fourth came from the State Fire Marshal's office.
   A malfunctioning valve in a compressor building at Amoco's
Anschutz Ranch East Gas Processing Plant may have caused the leak
that led to Wednesday's explosion, but ``we're not absolutely
certain,'' Amoco spokesman Dick Brewster said Thursday.
   He said static electricity could have ignited the gas, but
emphasized that was just a possibility.
   ``Had it not been for some unusual event, the gas might have
simply escaped and been vented outside of the building,'' Brewster
said. ``This is one of those tragic things where there shouldn't
have been ignition and there was.''
   David Phipps, plant operations center foreman, said workers had
little warning before the blast. They heard the hiss of gas
escaping just a few seconds before it ignited, he said.
   ``When it was realized there was gas escaping, they shut down
the compressor immediately and they were on their way out of the
building,'' Brewster said. ``Some were outside and some were just
inside.''
   He said there were 15 workers in the gas compressor building,
about one-quarter mile from the plant's main building in
southwestern Wyoming.
   The dead man was struck by one wall of the steel building that
was blown out by the blast.
   ``It appears as if he had just gotten out the door'' when the
explosion occurred, Brewster said.
   Brewster said a short fire followed the explosion.
   ``Once the explosion occurred the fire was over'' because the
supply of gas to the building was cut off as soon as the leak was
detected, he said.
   Brewster said the plant had a good safety record. Before
Wednesday's explosion, no workers had lost time on the job because
of an injury in seven years.
</TEXT>
