<FIRST>r w AM-US-Libya     10-26 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Libya,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>US: Gadhafi Still Supports Terrorism Despite Denials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Thursday that Libyan
leader Moammar Gadhafi was not telling the truth when he asserted
that he has halted support for international terrorist activities.
   Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Libya is still supplying
funds, weapons, safe havens and training facilities to such groups
as the Japanese Red Army, the Provisional Irish Republican Army,
the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command
and other terrorist groups.
   In addition, she said the ``notorious Abu Nidal organization,''
a Palestinian group otherwise known as the Fatah Revolutionary
Council, is still headquartered in Tripoli.
   Gadhafi acknowledged to an interviewer during a visit to Egypt
that Libya once supported terrorist groups, but he said he halted
the aid once ``we discovered that these groups were causing more
harm than benefit to the Arab cause.''
   He said that hijacking planes and killing civilians are acts of
murder that have nothing to do with combat. Libya, he added,
``should not be called to account for any of these acts because we
have withdrawn our support of such groups,'' he said.
   But Ms. Tutwiler said Libya is ``still trying to acquire
chemical weapons capability and is engaged in destabilizing efforts
around the world.
   ``We want to see irrevocable actions, not pronouncements or
short term adjustments that can be reversed.''
   The U.S. government, she said, ``is interested in actions, not
words.''
   In the interview, Gadhafi said he would welcome a dialogue with
the United States on the possibility of establishing friendlier
relations.
   ``We do not believe that conflict with the United States is
necessary,'' he said.
</TEXT>
