<SECOND>AM-US-Turkey,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Regrets Turkey's Restrictions on Military Activities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department expressed regret Thursday
over Turkey's decision to suspend certain U.S. military activities
in that country.
   The Turkish action followed approval by the Senate Judiciary
Committee of a resolution honoring Armenians alleged to have been
killed by Turks between 1915 and 1923.
   ``We regret Turkey's action and urge its suspension,'' State
Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said.
   The Turkish measures included a halt to U.S. port visits,
suspension of meetings on military cooperation, restrictions on
modernization projects at U.S. military facilities in Turkey and a
halt to U.S. use of training facilities at a military site at Kona.
