<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2151EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-WarsawPact     10-26 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warsaw Pact,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Foreign Ministers Meet in Warsaw</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seven Warsaw Pact foreign ministers
assessed the revolutionary changes taking place in the East bloc
Thursday at the military alliance's first meeting since Solidarity
took over the leadership in Poland.
   Non-communist Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski of Poland
welcomed the Warsaw Pact's foreign affairs committee as well as the
ministers for foreign trade from each country also invited to
attend the two days of talks.
   Skubiszewski stressed that despite the government change, Poland
wants to ``maintain friendly, mutually advantageous ties'' with its
Warsaw Pact partners, and ``strict respect of mutual interests on
the principle of equal rights.''
   Although not officially on the agenda, changes sweeping the
region were expected to be the main topic in informal moments of
the meeting.
   Since the foreign ministers last met a year ago, the once-banned
Solidarity movement has taken the reins of government in Poland,
Hungary's communist party has dissolved itself and become a
democratic leftist party and the aging hardline leader of East
Germany, Erich Honecker, has been replaced by a younger man
promising reform and dialogue with the opposition.
   Meanwhile, the Soviet Union continues to press ahead with change
in its fourth year under the leadership of Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
Only Czechoslovakia, Bulgaria and particularly Romania have
resisted the trend toward reform.
   Illustrating the gulf of attitudes the pervade the alliance,
Romania as recently as August tried to rally its Warsaw Pact allies
to intervene to halt the formation of a Solidarity-led government
as a threat to socialism, according to documents leaked in Poland.
The proposal found no support.
   ``It is not customary for the committee of foreign ministers to
discuss internal affairs of any country,'' said Foreign Ministry
spokesman Stefan Staniszewski of Poland. ``Nevertheless, I think
the ministers taking part in the meeting will find an opportunity
to share news and opinions concerning their countries.''
   He also said that ``certain problems concerning the future and
evolution of the pact will be discussed.''
   Skubiszewski told his fellow foreign ministers that he hoped the
session would contribute ``to the construction of a lasting
foundation of one, indivisible Europe.''
   Developments in East Germany, shaken by protests and the exodus
this year of 100,000 of its citizens, have renewed discussion on
German reunification and even brought into question the future of
two rival military alliances that have formed the basic
geopolitical structure of Europe since the late 1940s.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said in Moscow on
Monday that the Soviet Union would be interested in negotiating the
dissolution of both NATO and the Warsaw Pact by the year 2000.
   ``For the time being though, the two alliances do exist and one
should aim for their gradually being transformed into
political-military organizations through developing civilian trends
of their activity with a simultaneous reduction of all military
elements,'' Shevardnadze told PAP in Warsaw.
   In addition to the broader issues, Warsaw Pact foreign trade
ministers were also invited to the meeting to discuss ground rules
for reforming economic cooperation within the pact.
   ``Reformist tendencies in Eastern Europe, which are gaining new
territory apart from the traditional centers of ferment in Warsaw
and Budapest, cause questions about the future of the Warsaw
Pact,'' said a commentary Thursday in the daily Zycie Warszawy.
   The article, titled ``Ties, Chains or Alliance,'' said greater
flexibility should be allowed among the pact countries, while
respecting the strategic interests of the dominant partner, the
Soviet Union.
   ``All the reforms which no one could have imagined a few years
ago will be accepted in Moscow, unless they lead to the questioning
of membership in the Warsaw Pact,'' the commentary said.
   ``Efforts aimed at renovating the Warsaw Pact are gaining new
force, which will speed up the final results,'' the article said.
   The Warsaw Pact, the East bloc military alliance founded in
Warsaw in 1955 after the formation of NATO by the United States and
Western Europe, consists of the Soviet Union, Poland, East Germany,
Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
