<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-ForeignAid     10-26 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Foreign Aid,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Millions Pour In From Overseas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $1 million donation on Thursday by a
British corporation that makes hot tubs was the latest in more than
$8 million worth of foreign aid that has poured into Northern
California since last week's quake.
   Governments and foreign corporations that have ties to the
region have sent money. Costa Rican president Oscar Arias sent
2,500 pounds of coffee Thursday.
   The largest contributors have been the Japanese, who have
pledged more than $7 million in earthquake aid, prompting
expressions of thanks Thursday from former President Ronald Reagan
during his tour of Japan.
   All of the aid is designed to assist residents stunned by the
Oct. 17 quake that caused an estimated $7.1 billion worth of damage
to the region.
   Hanson Industries of Great Britain sent a $1 million check to
the Red Cross disaster relief fund to be used to help victims of
the San Francisco quake and Hurricane Hugo, the Red Cross announced.
   The company owns Jacuzzi Whirlpool Bath and Spa, Inc., of nearby
Walnut Grove, Calif., as well as Faberware cookware, Kaiser Cement
and other businesses, Sir James Murray, advisor to chairman Sir
Gordon White, said in a telephone interview from New York.
   Murray, a former British consul general in San Francisco, said
the company has 60,000 employees in the U.S., and White wanted to
help the nation recover from Hurricane Hugo and the earthquake.
   ``Whether it's famine in Biafra or the earthquake in Armenia,
Americans always are in the lead,'' Murray said. ``When they have a
natural disaster of the proportion of the West Coast quake or
Hurricane Hugo it's only right their friends should help.''
   Other major foreign donations to the fund include $570,000 from
Sony, $500,000 from Sanywa Bank, $200,000 from Toshiba, and
$200,000 from American Honda.
   The money will go towards the $20 million goal the Red Cross has
announced for earthquake victims and the $42 million they want to
raise for victims of Hurricane Hugo, said Barb Lohman of the Red
Cross.
   The Costa Rican coffee was slated for relief workers and shelter
residents in hard-hit Los Gatos, Santa Cruz, Watsonville and
Hollister, said Callie Gregory, a spokeswoman for San Jose, Calif.
   ``From San Jose, Costa Rica, to our sister city San Jose,
California,'' say the sacks of coffee.
   The government of Taiwan has donated $250,000 to the state of
California and another $250,000 to the city of San Francisco. A
Taiwanese province that is a sister state to California added
$100,000, according to the Taiwan consulate in San Francisco.
   The city of San Francisco has received about $1 million in small
donations, most from other countries, said Eileen Maloney, press
secretary to Mayor Art Agnos. That includes money from companies
and from Japanese schoolchildren, she said.
   In addition, 12 Japanese students who traveled to San Jose to
help victims brought $25,000 with them, said Bev Cubbage of the
Salvation Army.
   Foreign banks have also chipped in. The Bank of California-The
Mitsubishi Bank, Ltd. of Tokyo donated $300,000 and the Banque
National de Paris contributed $100,000 to a special relief campaign
set up by a local television station.
   Peggy McGinley of the Red Cross said other Japanese
contributions include: Bank of the West, $100,000; Industrial Bank
of Japan, $100,000; Duty Free Shoppers Group, $50,000; Hitachi,
$100,000; Union Bank, $100,000; Bank of Tokyo, $100,000;
Kanematsu-Gosho (USA) $20,000; C.Itoh and Co., $50,000; Nissho Iwai
American Corp. $50,000; Kyowa Bank, $50,000; Kikoman Soy Sauce,
$100,000; and Sumitomo Corp., $100,000.
</TEXT>
