<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1714EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Scandal     10-26 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Scandal,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN High Commissioner for Refugees Resigns Amid Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. high commissioner for refugees
resigned Thursday amid allegations of financial impropriety,
mismanagement and favoritism to Western donor nations.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar accepted Jean-Pierre
Hocke's resignation effective Wednesday, said U.N. spokesman
Francois Giuliani.
   On Tuesday, Denmark called for an investigation of Hocke's use
of Danish refugee funds for first-class air travel.
   Hocke's letter to Perez de Cuellar, read out by Giuliani, said:
   ``At a time when you have decided, based on a first evaluation
which has just been presented to you, to prolong and intensify an
investigation which you initiated, I do not wish my presence at the
head of HCR to complicate in any way the ongoing investigation.''
   Perez de Cuellar has received a report by U.N. auditors on
Hocke's use of funds, but its conclusions have not been disclosed.
   Hocke became high commissioner for refugees in 1986 as the
favored candidate of the U.S. State Department.
   The commissioner is officially responsible for at least 12
million refugees worldwide, although there are many more than that.
A separate U.N. agency helps Palestinian refugees.
   Officials of private relief agencies had expressed concern that
Hocke was bending to the restrictive national polices of major
donor nations rather than speaking out as the protector of refugees
worldwide.
   Western nations are adopting more restrictive refugee policies,
accepting only those who can prove they are politically persecuted
and excluding economic refugees.
   ``We do think that Hocke was ... protective of the more
restrictive actions taken by some developed governments, including
the United States,'' said Roger Winter, director of the U.S.
Committee of Refugees, an umbrella group for refugee agencies.
   Hocke's latest problems began in September, when Swiss
Television reported that internal documents showed he had drawn
$300,000 since 1987 from a special ``educational fund'' set up by
Sweden and Denmark to fly first class instead of business class.
   Hocke admitted he had flown first class, a right reserved only
for Perez de Cuellar under stringent U.N. austerity measures, but
denied any impropriety. He said he had flown first class on some
long intercontinental flights when he had a busy work schedule.
   Hocke's agency is struggling with a budget shortfall of $40
million.
   Part of the criticism that he did not challenge the refugee
policies of major donor nations came in January 1988 when he
ordered the burning of all 138,000 copies of the agency's monthly
magazine, ``Refugees,'' because it contained an article critical of
West Germany's policy.
   Hocke said the article was dated and that West Germany's
policies were improving. The act greatly embarrassed Bonn, however.
   A year ago, an internal report by the U.N. Panel on
Discrimination and other Grievances criticized Hocke's management
practices.
   The report condemned the ``personalization and centralization of
authority around the high commissioner'' as being part of the cause
of ``the rapidly growing management crisis'' at the refugee agency.
   Hocke's staff was so demoralized that they began leaking
documents to undermine him, U.N. officials have said. Among the
documents were the air travel expense reports.
   Gerald Hinteregger, an Austrian who heads the Geneva-based U.N.
Economic Commission for Europe, will serve as interim commissioner
until Perez de Cuellar selects a replacement, Giuliani said.
   The refugee agency spends about $500 million in aid money
annually. It has a staff of 2,300 people, including 800 in Geneva,
and the rest as field specialists.
   The United States, Japan, and West Germany are the leading
contributors, in that order.
   Hocke was a former director of operations of the International
Committee of the Red Cross.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-DetroitMayor    10-26 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Mayor, </SECOND>
<HEAD>Coleman Young Looks Like a Winner for Fifth Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Call it a walkaway, a shoo-in, a breeze or a
coronation, but a mayor by any other name than Coleman A. Young
doesn't look likely this election year despite the incumbent's 71
years, four terms in office and a well-known paternity suit.
   Two of his rivals in the primary have fallen in behind him, the
Rev. Jesse Jackson has come into the fold after a long-standing
coolness, and Young has refused to debate his opponent saying there
is nothing to talk about since the man has no record to discuss.
   The man who wants to stop Young from winning an unprecedented
fifth term on Nov. 7 is accountant Tom Barrow, 40, who has never
held office and who lost to Young in 1985 by 39 percent to 61
percent.
   Barrow entered this year's general election campaign with the
momentum of his non-partisan primary victory on Sept. 12 over
13-term Congressman John Conyers and City Council President Erma
Henderson.
   Conyers and another mayoral also-ran, paint store owner Charles
Costa, endorsed Young at the same news conference last week at
which Jackson announced his support. Henderson has held out, even
though she appeared at the press conference and despite Young's
suggestion two weeks ago that the city council name a park in her
honor.
   Results of a poll conducted for WJBK-TV and the Wayne State
University Center for Urban Studies released Wednesday showed Young
with 46 percent to Barrow's 29 percent with 17 percent undecided
and 8 percent refusing to answer. The poll of 310 registered voters
had a margin of error of plus or minus 5.5 percent.
   A poll conducted earlier this month for the Detroit Free Press
showed Young with 51 percent to 35 percent for Barrow with 14
percent undecided.
   Jackson's endorsement seemed like the final blow. Young had
incurred Jackson's wrath by supporting Michael Dukakis in the 1988
Democratic presidential primary, and by frequently criticizing
Jackson's credentials to run for president. Jackson supported
Conyers in the primary.
   ``People who might have decided to support Barrow just aren't
going to take a chance on him now,'' Wilbur Rich, a political
science professor at Wayne State University and the author of a
Young biography, said Thursday.
   Even the paternity lawsuit earlier this year was settled
amicably. Young set up a trust fund for his 7-year-old son, Joel
Loving, and will provide for the boy through his 25th birthday.
   Young has campaigned steadily, appearing at groundbreakings,
anniversaries and ribbon-cuttings, as well as at dozens of the
city's black churches.
   He started the campaign with a fund of nearly $5 million. Actor
James Earl Jones did the voice-overs for some of his early
television ads. Barrow's total fund is said to be less than
$250,000.
   Rich said Barrow's lack of political experience has hindered him
from getting support from other politicians. ``He hasn't paid his
dues, and he's indicating that he isn't going to pay them,'' Rich
said.
   Barrow's campaign strategy generally has been one of attacking
Young's leadership.
   He has said this may be his last run for mayor, even though
Young has indicated he will step aside in 1993 after two decades in
office.
   ``I don't think I have another shot,'' Barrow said. ``I think
this is it.''
</TEXT>
