<FIRST>r w AM-Abortion     10-26 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sponsors of Failed Abortion Amendment Say They'll Try Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sponsor of a failed proposal to allow
Medicaid abortions for rape and incest victims said Thursday that
pressure will build on President Bush to change his mind while she
and allies look for a new opportunity to press the issue in
Congress.
   Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., sent a letter to Bush on Thursday
_ signed by 74 members of Congress _ asserting that a congressional
majority favors the expansion of federally financed abortion.
   They urged him not to again veto bills to which Congress may add
similar language, a move that could put the abortion issue at the
center of an impasse between the White Hosue and Congress.
   ``We urge you to accept the will of the majority and not hold
any more bills hostage in order to exert a minority view,'' the
letter said.
   The House sustained Bush's veto Wednesday on a 231-191 vote, 51
fewer than the two-thirds majority needed to overturn a veto. Two
weeks earlier the House for the first time in this decade voted to
relax the restrictions on Medicaid abortions.
   The vote followed Bush's veto on Saturday of the provision,
which is but a paragraph in a $156.7 billion appropriations bill
for health, education and labor programs for the 1990 fiscal year
that began Oct. 1.
   Boxer, in an interview, said she and her allies have not decided
whether to try to attach the same, vetoed provision to the same
bill, which has now been sent back to the House Appropriations
Committee.
   House Speaker Tom Foley said the Democratic leadership in the
House has not decided on how to handle the spending bill but said
he expected further efforts to push the more liberal abortion
provisions in an effort to force Bush to relent.
   ``I wasn't surprised by the outcome, but it's not going to be
the last, I think, we'll hear on this issue this year,'' Foley said.
   House Republican Leader Robert Michel of Illinois told reporters
that ``maybe some adjustments will have to be made'' in the current
Medicaid prohibitions because of the changing House sentiment.
Michel voted with Bush on the issue but said he has always favored
permitting abortion in cases of rape or incest.
   Claiming that the vote was a victory because it showed there is
now a majority in the House and Senate in support of broader
abortion rights, Boxer said her side was content to ``let the issue
percolate'' while it decided where next to push it.
   ``We're going to win it eventually,'' she said. ``Just keep
building pressure on the president. ... We're going to let people
contemplate what's happened and how times are changing on this
issue.''
   In their letter, the members of Congress said that in past years
they had gone along with the more restrictive abortion provisions
in passing the full spending bill even though they objected to the
abortion restrictions, known as the ``Hyde amendment.''
   ``The majority of the House has a new opinion on this, and it
should be respected, just as those of us who disagreed with the
restrictive Hyde amendment accepted it as the will of the House and
voted for the ... bill,'' the letter said.
</TEXT>
