<FIRST>u w AM-SFQuake-FederalAid     10-26 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Federal Aid,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Signs Disaster Relief Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday signed a record
$3.45 billion disaster relief package, the bulk of the money bound
for California, and said ``our hearts go out to the victims'' of
the San Francisco Bay area earthquake.
   The president signed the legislation _ part of a short-term
spending bill _ at daybreak, after it won final congressional
approval the night before.
   Later, at a picture-taking session in the Oval Office with
members of the California delegation, Bush praised Congress for its
``great speed and compassion'' in enacting the measure so quickly.
   The package would provide $2.85 billion in new disaster relief
while freeing up another $600 million from other programs.
   The bulk of the money will go to California, but some of the
disaster funds also will be used to continue the process of
assisting East Coast victims of Hurricane Hugo.
   ``Our hearts go out to the victims and we are hopeful that this
action ... will send a signal that all of us, crossing party lines,
care very much about this,'' Bush said.
   The package is the largest federal relief effort ever for a
natural disaster. The quake, which measured 7.1 on the Richter
scale, struck the San Francisco Bay area on Oct. 17.
   The $2.85 billion in new funds includes $1.1 billon for the
Federal Emergency Management Agency for general disaster relief, $1
billion for the Federal Highway Administration for road and bridge
repair and $500 million for Small Business Administration disaster
loans.
   The rest is to be held in a disaster relief contingency fund to
be used by Bush as he sees fit.
</TEXT>
