<FIRST>u w AM-US-CentralAmerica     10-26 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Central America,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says He'll Protest Soviet-Bloc Arms to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Costa Rica Meeting Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he won't confer with
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega at a hemispheric meeting Friday,
but will use ``every chance I get'' to complain about Soviet-bloc
arms shipments to Nicaragua's Marxist government.
   ``We're not going down there to have some battle with Mr.
Ortega,'' Bush said before flying to Costa Rica for a two-day
celebration of that Central-American country's 100 years of
democracy. Ortega will be among the 18 heads of state engaging in
informal discussions at the meeting.
   Bush said he hoped the summit's focus on democratic government
``doesn't get cluttered up'' by members of the news media ``wanting
to see a picture of me and Ortega together.''
   Bush spoke in a White House interview with Latin-American
journalists on Wednesday. The transcript of his remarks was
released Thursday.
   The president said it was ``somewhat ironic that Mr. Ortega is
there to salute democracy, but nevertheless, so be it. That's
good.''
   If he does encounter Ortega at the summit, he said, ``it would
be very firm because I don't see why that one Sandinista regime is
swimming against the tide'' of democracy.
   Bush criticized Nicaragua's preparations for scheduled
presidential elections on Feb. 25 as unfair to opposition
candidates, and he denounced Soviet-bloc shipments of weapons and
ammunition to Ortega's Sandinista government.
   The Soviet Union has denied shipping arms to Nicaragua, but the
Bush administration nevertheless contends that Nicaragua is still
shipping Soviet-bloc weapons to Marxist rebels fighting the
U.S.-backed government of El Salvador.
   Asked if he would bring up that problem at the Costa Rica
meeting, Bush replied, ``I'll bring it up every chance I get.''
   The president said he also will ``continue to work with the
Soviet Union,'' which had promised to use its influence with
Nicaragua to halt arms exports.
   ``We will make clear every chance we get to the Soviets that
that is not in their interests, and certainly we view it against
the security interests of the United States and we view it against
the tide in terms of democracy,'' Bush said.
   The United States complained to Moscow on Wednesday about a arms
cache that was intercepted last week along the Nicaragua-Honduras
border and found to contain several Soviet-produced weapons. U.S.
officials said the shipment was headed for Salvadoran rebels.
   Referring to the Ortega government, the president asked, ``Why
should that military clique, who at one point were espousing their
own Marxist beliefs, deny, through having a military force far
bigger than is required and bigger than any of its neighbors, the
will of the people?''
   As he heads for Costa Rica, Bush said, ``I have no agenda with
Mr. Ortega. And as he takes a step that might lead to democracy,
great, I'm for that. But we're not going to solve any problems
there in Costa Rica. I'm there as a guest of the country.''
   Bush extended a 1985 trade embargo against Nicaragua on
Wednesday for another six months, and let the Costa Ricans know he
would refuse to sign any joint communique produced by the summit if
it bore Ortega's signature. The plan for such a statement was
scrapped after objections from other summit nations.
</TEXT>
