<FIRST>u a AM-Bakker     10-26 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bakker,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jailed PTL Founder's Latest Church-Studio Losing Its Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The foundering new television ministry founded by Jim and Tammy
Bakker will have to move out of its shopping mall storefront after
Sunday's service, less than a week after Bakker began a 45-year
federal prison term for fraud.
   Bakker began serving his sentence at a federal prison in
Talladega, Ala., on Tuesday, the same day he was sentenced for
defrauding members of the defunct PTL Club and ministry of $3.7
million.
   ``They treated Jim like he was a dog. We've been through a lot,
but this is the worst,'' Bakker's mother, Furnia Bakker, said
Thursday from the home she and her husband have on the grounds of
Heritage USA, the now-padlocked retreat Bakker built at Fort Mill,
S.C., through his bankrupt PTL television ministry.
   The Bakkers have been operating the New Covenant Church and TV
ministry out of Orlando for the past five months.
   Bakker's oldest brother, Norm, who has been operations chief for
the combination church and television studio, said Wednesday that
the ministry's rental contract at Shoppers World mall extended to
the end of October.
   That is up Tuesday and the owner of the mall, Stewart Gilman,
said the ministry will have to move out. He already has signed a
lease with a new tenant who plans to use a major portion of the
plaza, in a tourist area between downtown Orlando and Walt Disney
World.
   A volunteer answering the ministry's telephone Thursday
identified himself only as ``Ed'' and said he had ``no comment and
no statements'' and said there was no activity at the studio.
   Norm Bakker said Wednesday that Sunday's service for local
supporters is planned to feature the Rev. Gene Kennett of Erie,
Pa.. who has substituted for Bakker in the past.
   Neither Tammy Bakker nor Norm Bakker could be reached Thursday
for further comment on their plans.
   Gilman said he did not ask the ministry to leave because of
Bakker's conviction and sentence, but because of the ministry's
actions.
   In the past few weeks, ministry volunteers have moved much of
their property into a smaller section of the plaza in hopes of
paying less rent. But Gilman said there had not been any change in
the rental contract.
   He said he would not interfere with Sunday's service.
   ``From my point of view, they should be out of there as soon as
it is possible or convenient for them to do so,'' he said.
   At last report, the new TV ministry had only five stations as
subscribers.
   Bakker's mother said Thursday she couldn't believe her son is in
prison.
   ``My husband just went to the doctor,'' Mrs. Bakker said. ``This
is awfully hard on both of us. We're both 83 and this is hard to
take. I was just trying to relax.''
   Mrs. Bakker and her husband, Raleigh, are among about 800 people
who have homes at Heritage USA, where a large sign at the front
entrance reads: ``Closed Until Further Notice.''
   ``We're not letting any cars in _ only residents and staff,''
said guard Mickey Rhymer.
   Bakker, 49, was taken immediately after sentencing taken to the
medium security Federal Correctional Institution at Talladega.
   Depending on the outcome of an appeal, he will serve at least 10
years before being eligible for parole.
   Prison officials said Thursday that Bakker appeared to be doing
well, but they declined to say much more about him. ``As far as I
know, he's adjusting well,'' said spokeswoman Dana Newell.
   She said the prison had received numerous requests from
reporters for interviews with Bakker and was referring those to his
lawyer.
   Baker is expected to stay at Talladega no more than two weeks
before he is transferred to another federal prison, which officials
declined to reveal.
</TEXT>
