<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2204EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearWaste     10-26 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Waste,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins Told Opening of Waste Dump Will Take Longer Than Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blue-ribbon panel of advisers to Energy
Secretary James D. Watkins has recommended a further delay of at
least two years in starting operation of a defense nuclear waste
dump in New Mexico, a panel member said Thursday.
   The suggestion, if accepted, would mean the department would
have to arrange temporary storage of nuclear wastes for much longer
than currently planned, said Leonard Slosky, a member of the
advisory panel.
   The site, known as the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant and situated
just north of the Texas border near Carlsbad, N.M. is designed to
store drums of plutonium waste from nuclear weapons manufacture for
thousands of years in caves of bedded rock salt.
   Watkins had told Congress earlier this month that he expected to
have to persuade seven states to accept some excess waste starting
next April until about September 1992, when operational testing of
the permanent repository would start. Governors of the seven states
have told Watkins they won't take the waste.
   The seven states are Washington, Idaho, Colorado, New Mexico,
Nevada, Tennessee and South Carolina.
   The $800 million Carlsbad installation was supposed to have
opened a year ago, and as recently as June Watkins was saying it
would open in September of this year. In early October Watkins said
he hoped to accept experimental shipments next July but could not
say when full-scale operation should start.
   Four of the five advisory panel members told Watkins in a
private meeting Tuesday that the operational testing should be put
off at least an additional two years to 1994, Slosky said, in part
because the results of some scientific experiments won't be known
before then.
   The four also said they believed that the first phase of
experiments would take longer than the department has planned, and
that the tests should be broadened.
   Slosky said only Robert Bishop, representing an industry group,
disagreed with the recommendation to put off the operational
testing _ essentially an effort to show that the waste can be
safely loaded, shipped, unloaded, deposited in the dump and, if
necessary, retrieved.
   The panel wrote no joint report but instead the members
presented individual recommendations in separate papers for Watkins
on Tuesday, Slosky said.
   Department officials familiar with the reports declined to
return a telephone call Thursday. The department has not published
the papers.
   An environmental group said in response to the advisory panel's
recommendations that Watkins faced further delays and political
fights over the dump.
   ``For political and technical reasons, it's not going to open
anytime soon,'' said Elizabeth Kassen, a senior attorney for the
Environmental Defense Fund.
   The panel members also told Watkins they saw serious management
problems that should be corrected before the dump is opened.
   Slosky, an environmental consultant based in Denver, said in a
telephone interview that the panel members agreed that the site is
a good one and ``We have not uncovered anything that we think is a
fatal flaw.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
