<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2216EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-LiquorTax     10-26 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liquor Tax,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Willing To Compromise On Obscure Liquor Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration said Thursday it would
not object if Congress forgives interest and penalties on an
obscure, 123-year-old liquor tax that has stirred up tavern owners,
grocers and fraternal groups.
   The administration stopped short of endorsing a waiver of
overdue taxes themselves.
   Protests over the tax have grown since a Pennsylvania Elks lodge
got a $9,776 bill last year for 50 years of non-payment, and a
California pizza shop owner got a $2,911 bill four weeks ago. Both
establishments said they never had heard of the so-called ``special
occupational tax'' on liquor retailers.
   About 600,000 beer, wine and distilled spirits dealers that sell
directly to the public must pay the annual tax, which was increased
in January 1988 from $54 to $250 per retailer. Accompanying the
increase has been a vigorous enforcement effort by the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
   The administration recognizes that the tax has created special
problems, Kenneth W. Gideon, assistant treasury secretary for tax
policy, said at a House Ways and Means subcommittee hearing.
   ``Although we continue to believe that taxpayer amnesty programs
are generally inappropriate, this case involves a tax that for
years before 1987 was insignificant and not well publicized,''
Gideon told the Subcommittee on Select Revenue Measures in a
prepared statement.
   ``It appears that noncompliance in years before 1987 was due to
the fact that many taxpayers were simply not aware of the tax,''
Gideon said. ``There is no evidence that dealers were attempting to
avoid the tax.''
   Before 1987, only about 40 percent of retailers were paying up,
Gideon said. He said the compliance rate is 80 percent now.
   A recent proposal by Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., to the Ways and
Means panel would forgive interest and penalties on the tax
accruing before last July.
   Rep. Paul Kanjorski, D-Pa., told the subcommittee Thursday that
it should also move to forgive tax debts on the books before 1985,
not just interest and penalties.
   That approach was backed by the National Restaurant Association.
   ``The great protest over this tax that you have heard recently
from constituents in the restaurant business grows from a feeling
that the federal government is unfair in penalizing honest
entrepreneurs for failure to pay a so-called `user fee' that the
IRS has never publicized or made any serious effort to collect in
the past 30 years,'' the lobbying group said.
   Gideon said the administration would balk at any proposal that
``resulted in the forgiveness of significant amounts of tax.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
