<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Refugees     10-26 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Refugees,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Refugees Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,200 Salvadorans who
fled their war-ravaged nation for camps in Honduras in the early
1980s returned home Thursday, U.N. officials said.
   The refugees crossed the border at El Poy, 45 miles north of San
Salvador, in a caravan of 34 buses and 148 trucks that carried
their belongings, said Werner Blatter, regional director for the
U.N. High Commission for Refugees.
   He said the refugees, who numbered 1,200 to 1,300, will resettle
in three northern towns that have been virtually abandoned since
the early 1980s because of civil war.
   The 10-year-old war is still being fought between a rightist
government and leftist guerrillas.
   However, the refugees, who had been living at Mesa Grande camp,
decided to try to rebuild their lives at home despite the conflict.
   About 12,000 Salvadorans remain in four camps in Honduras. Most
say they want to go home.
   Several more repatriation caravans of 1,000 to 1,500 people each
are planned for the coming months.
   With Thursday's group, more than 8,000 refugees have returned
since the program began in October 1987.
</TEXT>
