<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Soviet     10-26 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Soviet,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Delivers Letter From Gorbachev To Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Soviet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Soviet parliament member delivered a
letter Thursday to President Bush from Soviet President Mikail S.
Gorbachev offering an upbeat assessment of relations between
Washington and Moscow.
   Yevgeniy Primakov presented the three-page document, typewritten
in Russian, to Bush during a brief meeting in the Oval Office.
   Primakov, the top ranking official in the Supreme Soviet, is
leading a parliamentary delegation invited to the United States by
congressional leaders.
   Talking with reporters after the meeting, Primakov said Bush
``was quite warm when speaking about the changes that take place in
my country.''
   He said that Bush said that ``realistically-thinking politicians
understand full well that it is not only the Soviet Union but the
other countries, as well, need the success of perestroika (the
process of economic restructuring).''
   He declined to discuss Gorbachev's letter in detail but said it
``very positively evaluates the road that we have covered in the
improvement of our relations'' and suggests steps for further
improvements.
   ``That letter can cause the feelings of optimism,'' he said.
