<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Shamir     10-26 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Shamir,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush May Not Meet With Israeli Prime Minister During U.S. Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House raised the possibility
Thursday that President Bush might not meet next month with Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, even though Shamir requested such a
meeting.
   Shamir planned to visit the United States in mid-November.
   The administration was in the process of weighing
Israeli-suggested changes in Secretary of State James A. Baker
III's proposal for direct Israeli-Palestinian talks.
   But presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said there was
no link between this review and the question whether a Bush-Shamir
meeting would take place.
   Asked if the administration were trying to prod Israel by
hinting such a meeting might not take place, Fitzwater said: ``I
don't think so. I don't think a meeting is the kind of thing that's
going to influence Israel's position on these matters.''
   He told reporters that a meeting between the two leaders was
``probably likely.''
   But, later in the day his office issued a terse two-sentence
statement that said Shamir would be in the United States ``for a
private visit.''
   ``No decisions have been made concerning a possible meeting with
the president,'' it continued.
   It would be unusual for a U.S. president not to meet with an
Israeli prime minister visiting this country.
   ``We have asked for a meeting with President Bush and we're
still waiting for an answer,'' said Israel Embassy spokeswoman.
Ruth Yaron.
   Both U.S. and Israeli officials privately suggested that
scheduling problems were uppermost _ plus some confusion on the
exact dates of Shamir's visit.
   He was to speak to the General Assembly of the Zionist
Federation in Cincinnati on Nov. 16, but Israeli Embassy officials
said it was still not clear exactly when Shamir would arrive in the
country or how long he would stay.
   Shamir's government notified Baker on Monday night that it
accepted his proposal talks with Palestinians but only if two
conditions were met _ exclusion of the Palestine Liberation
Organization and limiting the meeting to making arrangments for an
election on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Baker, in a White House news conference on Wednesday, said he
would review Israel's request that he revise his five-point
proposal. But he said he could not overhaul it because that would
touch off a long process of bargaining with both sides, delaying
the onset of the talks.
</TEXT>
