<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strikes     10-26 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Miners Decide to Return to Work; Strikes May Hit Ukraine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal miners in the Soviet Far North defied the law
and struck Thursday but then returned to work. Miners, however,
threatened new walkouts in the Ukraine.
   A total of 18,000 workers in nine mines in the northern Vorkuta
region struck to demand the Kremlin make good on promised benefits,
a spokesman said.
   They decided to return to work at all but one mine after
hearings on the illegal strike began in regional court, said strike
committee member Sergei Masolovich.
   He said the walkout would continue at the Vorkuta region's
biggest coalfield, but that workers would return to the job Friday
at other mines.
   ``Due to pressure from the local media and management's taking
the case to court, the regional strike committee made a decision to
end the strike at midnight,'' Masolovich said by telephone.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, in Finland on an official
visit, said Thursday that ``strong administrative measures through
the prosecutor and the court'' might be taken against the strikers
to promote stability.
   In the Ukraine's Donetsk coal basin, the country's largest
coal-producing area, miner representatives voted against
immediately resuming the strike that paralyzed the region this
summer, Soviet television reported.
   But they decided to hold a referendum to gauge miners' support
for a renewed walkout, the nightly news program ``Vremya'' said.
   In the western Ukrainian city of Lvov, about 5,000 people massed
Thursday evening and supported calls for a one-day general walkout
Friday in solidarity with miners and to push political demands, a
Ukrainian activist said.
   Top Soviet officials have voiced concern that strikes, by
cutting the nation's coal supplies, could force a rationing of heat
and light as the traditionally brutal Russian winter begins.
   The walkouts violated a law passed earlier this month by the
Soviet legislature that sets arbitration procedures for would-be
strikers and bans walkouts in such vital areas as energy, defense
and transportation.
   Strikes this summer in virtually all the Soviet Union's major
coalfields, from the Central Asia in the South to Vorkuta,
paralyzed much of the country's coal industry.
   The miners went back to work after the government promised to
meet their demands for better working conditions, improved supplies
of consumer goods and more financial independence.
   But Ukrainian miners' representatives claimed Thursday the
promises have not been kept.
   Alexei Bokharev, chairman of the Donetsk strike committee, said
in a telephone interview that the miners will decide Friday on a
course of action. ``Either the strike will be resumed or a
conciliation commission will be appointed,'' he said.
   Coal industry minister Mikhail Shchadov said in an interview
with Soviet television that the ministry is fulfilling all promises
to the miners.
   But Vremya also said conditions at many mines remain worse than
ever, and that they are producing far below capacity because of the
lack of needed spare parts and new technology.
</TEXT>
