<DOCNO> AP891026-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1825EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Insurance     10-26 0936</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Insurance,550</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Insurers Don't See An Eruption in Quake Rates ^By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since sunrise the day after the big
earthquake, Fireman's Fund Insurance Co. has had claims adjusters
on the streets handing out checks for collapsed or burned homes.
   It was just like old times for the Novato, Calif.-based company.
   ``We made our reputation in the quake of 1906 when every other
San Francisco-based insurer went under,'' says spokesman John
Kozero. ``Our headquarters was destroyed and we had no records. But
we paid everyone, half cash and half stock, which in a few years
was worth more.''
   There's no problem for insurers in coming up with cash to pay
for the destruction of the Oct. 17 quake, and this time none are
expected to succumb to claims that could cost the industry $2
billion to $3 billion.
   Most insurers are scrambling to keep clients and win new ones by
responding quickly to claims, taking out ads in newspapers and
broadcasting commercials on radio.
   State Farm Insurance Co. flew in 250 claim handlers from around
the country to join 600 others working out of eight offices and
eight trailers.
   Despite more expensive costs and a year of calamities from coast
to coast, the insurers said Thursday they're not expecting soaring
rates as anticipated by Wall Street investors who bid up their
stocks after the big earthquake and Hurricane Hugo.
   Instead, the insurance companies said home owner rates and
earthquake riders in some damage-prone areas might go up a little
next year, others might go down and overall there won't be any
major changes.
   ``There should be no impact on personal home owners and
earthquake insurance,'' Kozero said. ``The rates were based on a
pattern of what happened in the past, and the quake was part of
what was expected.''
   If there is a rate hike, the companies said, it will more likely
affect commercial policies, which have benefited from a price war.
   Much of the estimated $4 billion for Hurrican Hugo and the
billions for the quake will be collected back from dozens of
reinsurers in Europe, Asia and the United States who assume part of
the liability of primary insurers.
   The quake is not going to bankrupt any insurance company, said
Gloria Vogel, industry analyst for Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. in New York.
``The industry does have the capital to pay out these enormous
losses and the risk is spread around the world.''
   The insurance companies also were buffered by 10 to 15 percent
deductibles on the expensive earthquake riders that make up for the
exclusion of quakes from home owners' policies. Because of that,
only about 20 percent of home owners carry earthquake insurance,
which by law must be offered in California.
   Insurers say there has been a small increase demand for
earthquake insurance since last week, just as there was after a
quake in Southern California a few years ago. But interest
typically dies down as memories of quakes fade.
   State Farm, the largest home and auto insurer in California and
the country, has $14 billion of home owners and earthquake policies
in force in the San Francisco Bay area and expects to pay out about
$300 million in quake claims.
   Unlike most insurers, State Farm will not collect much from
reinsurers.
   ``Because of our size, there's not enough reinsurance available
to make a significant impact on the amount of exposure we have,''
said Jim Stahly, spokesman for the Bloomington, Ill.-based company.
   State Farm, suffering its worst year in catastrophe claim
payments that include $500 million for Hurricane Hugo, will likely
have an underwriting loss for the year, Stahly said.
   So far, State Farm's adjusters and agents have processed about
7,500 quake claims _ about one-third of what it expects to handle.
   Fireman's Fund says its payout will be about $200 million, but
after reinsurance collection and taxes, the impact on its fourth
quarter will be no more than $50 million.
   The burden of at least half of Fireman's Fund's payouts will be
shared by 13 other insurance companies around the world, mostly in
London, West Germany, Switzerland, Italy and Japan.
   ``Often the reinsurers will reinsure again,'' said Kozero.
   Hurricane Hugo and the quake triggered a scramble among
insurance companies in London to make sure their reinsurance
protection was in place for the rest of the year.
   That increase in demand boosted reinsurance rates and eventually
could lead to higher primary rates, unless the primary companies
absorb the extra costs for competitive reasons.
   ``In the past two years many policies have been written under
cost because insurers are trying to win market share,'' said Kozero.
   ``Psychologically, this quake has a big effect on pricing,''
said Vogel. ``But it will be at least late 1990 before we see the
full effects of any price increases _ if they come.''
   Insurance stocks were attractive to investors before the quake
because of the perception interest rates may be coming down, she
said, but the rise in the past week ``may have been a little
overdone ... and we may see them backing off a little bit.''
   Insurance companies, especially those who handled reinsurance,
were the most popular plays on Wall Street after the quake. General
Re Corp. rose $2.75 to $86.50 the day after the quake and has
continue to climb this week week. Nac Re Corp., American
International Group and Cigna Corp. also were higher.
   ``The companies are not sounding as optimistic as investors are
that things are going to turn,'' Vogel said. ``But then again the
companies were the last ones to see price-cutting, too.''
</TEXT>
