<FIRST>u i AM-Chile-Pardon     10-26 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Pardon,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pardoned Labor Leaders Return Home to Santiago</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two leading labor activists Thursday
returned home to Santiago after 403 days of internal exile and
pledged to support the opposition candidate for president and to
fight for democracy.
   The union leaders, Manuel Bustos and Arturo Martinez, came back
to the capital after they were pardoned Monday by right-wing
military President Augusto Pinochet.
   ``We were punished for demanding justice, fair salaries for the
workers, and for defending the right to strike,'' Bustos said,
speaking to about 2,000 people who gathered at a Santiago suburb to
welcome them.
   ``It's the worker's right to strike which we have fought for,''
Martinez said.
   Bustos is president of the United Workers Central, and Martinez
is vice president of the group. They were sentenced to 541 days'
internal exile in provincial cities for calling a strike against
the government in 1987.
   The union officials said they will now actively support the
campaign of opposition presidential candidate Patricio Aylwin
because he has vowed to restore democracy to Chile after 16 years
of authoritarian military rule.
   Pinochet's pardon came the same week that Lech Walesa, leader of
Poland's Solidarity labor movement, was due to arrive in Chile to
visit both dissident leaders.
   Walesa canceled visits planned to Parral, 210 miles south of
Santiago, to see Bustos and to Chanaral, 595 miles north of the
capital, to see Martinez after hearing of the pardons.
   Pinochet was forced to call the presidential election, scheduled
for Dec. 14, after losing a public referendum last year on a
proposal to extend his rule to 1997.
</TEXT>
