<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1859EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MinimumWage     10-26 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Seeks Compromise on Minimum Wage Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republicans and conservative Democrats
who sustained President Bush's veto in June of a minimum wage
increase struggled Thursday to find a compromise that would avoid
another showdown next week.
   But the White House, in a meeting with leaders of the two
parties, refused to budge on Bush's demand for a six-month
subminimum training wage and labor leaders balked at accepting
anything less than a $4.25 minimum wage by January 1991.
   Whether a compromise is reached or not, Democratic leaders plan
to bring to the House floor next Wednesday a scaled-back $4.25
version of the bill that Bush vetoed, which would have set a
$4.55-an-hour minimum wage with a 60-day subminimum training wage.
   Key players in both parties and lobbyists for business and labor
groups said the White House has been sending signals since late
last week that Bush wanted to avoid a showdown and was open to
negotiating a deal.
   ``There is a lot of nervousness on the part of the White House
that they could look like a mean old ogre here fighting day and
night to get a capital gains tax break while also fighting equally
hard against raising the minimum wage,'' said Rep. Timothy J.
Penny, D-Minn.
   ``They want to come in at the last minute and make a deal but
there's no firm decision on what they want,'' said Penny, one of 28
Democrats who voted last summer to sustain Bush's veto.
   Despite pleas from Democrats like Penny and several Republicans,
White House Chief of Staff John Sununu told House Speaker Thomas S.
Foley, D-Wash., and GOP leader Robert H. Michel of Illinois that
Bush would not yield.
   ``We didn't reach agreement on anything,'' Foley told reporters
after the White House meeting.
   Bush, in what he called a ``best and only offer,'' promised
shortly after taking office to veto any bill that would raise the
minimum wage above $4.25 an hour or that reached that level before
Jan. 1, 1992.
   Coupled with any increase, he said, must be a six-month
subminimum training wage that would maintain the current wage floor
of $3.35 an hour for newly hired workers, regardless of their
experience.
   Sununu, according to congressional sources and lobbyists,
``floated'' as a possible compromise gradually increasing the wage
floor to $4.25 an hour by July 1991 _ six months earlier than Bush
wanted _ with a three-month subminimum for new hires.
   But that offer was not put forth Thursday, Foley and Michel said.
   ``The president will have to bend a little bit'' to avoid a veto
fight, Michel said, ``and there may be room for some bending. I
don't think the president would enjoy vetoing a second minimum wage
bill.''
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., said supporters still lack a
two-thirds, veto-proof majority for a new bill that would raise the
wage floor to $3.80 this January and to $4.25 by January 1991 with
a 60-day training wage only for first-time workers.
   ``But we're gaining ground,'' he said. ``Our whip count from
Republicans and conservative Democrats is much better than it was
the last vote.''
   Democrats want to have a bill approved by both the House and
Senate and on Bush's desk before the Nov. 13 arrival in Washington
of Polish Solidarity union leader Lech Walesa, believing the
occasion will make a veto more difficult politically.
   ``We want to get it to him and give him an opportunity to think
about it,'' said Bonior. ``The priorities of this administration in
terms of economic justice for people are nowhere near reality.''
   Robert McGlotten, the AFL-CIO's chief lobbyist, expressed a
willingness to negotiate the training wage issue as long as there
are assurances that employers cannot use it to rotate workers in
and out of entry-level jobs so that they never rise above the
subminimum level.
   ``They keep talking like they want to make some movement,'' he
said of the administration, ``but when we sit down with them, we
get nowhere. They're floundering all over the place.''
   McGlotten said ``there's no give'' by unions on the issue of
achieving a 90-cent increase to $4.25 an hour by January 1991.
</TEXT>
