<FIRST>r a AM-FarmSearch     10-26 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Search,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourth Body Found in Search for Transients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSH LEMIEUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities found a man's body buried in
a shallow grave in a barn under tons of hay, the fourth such
discovery in a 2{-week-old search for missing drifters who worked
with a farmer.
   The body, wrapped in plastic and clad in boots and a heavy coat,
was found Wednesday evening, officials and another farmer said.
Authorities continued to move large bales of hay and dig in the
barn Thursday.
   ``We're about half done,'' said Greg Coon of the nine-county
North Central Missouri Major Case Squad.
   The search began Oct. 9, when Ray Copeland, 75, and his
68-year-old wife, Faye, were arrested in an alleged cattle swindle.
They are being held in the Livingston County Jail here on $25,000
bond each on charges of conspiracy to steal.
   Law enforcement officials, using backhoes, shovels and
bloodhounds, first searched Copeland's farm near Mooresville about
10 miles southwest of here, then moved to other farms where
Copeland had worked in the Chillicothe area, about 90 miles
northeast of Kansas City.
   The fourth body, which has not been identified, was found on Joe
Roy Adams' farm 12 miles south of Copeland's farm and three miles
northeast of Neil Bryan's farm, where the other three bodies were
found Oct. 16.
   The three found at Bran's farm had been shot in the head and
buried in shallow graves in a barn. They have not been identified,
but appeared to be 20 to 32 years old. The cause of the fourth
man's death has not been determined.
   No one has been charged in the four men's deaths and the
Copelands have not been named as suspects. But authorities have
said they are looking for less than a dozen transients who may have
stayed with the Copelands.
   Adams, owner for 3{ years of the farm where the body was found
Wednesday, said Copeland had managed the farm for previous owner
Ted Lock. Adams said Copeland kept some of his hay in the barn for
about a year after the sale, and occasionally traveled there.
   ``He worked here for about 10 years,'' said Adams, 62. ``He was
in and out all the time. ... Copeland never worked for me at all.
He wanted to, but I didn't hire him.''
   ``We just thought he was a good, hard-working man trying to make
ends meet,'' recalled Lock's wife, Charlotte.
   Adams said the body was under small, square bales of hay that
had been stacked in the barn while Copeland still worked at the
farm and some large, round bales that Adams had added.
   There were about 800 of the large bales and more than 1,000 of
the smaller ones in the barn before officers began moving them.
</TEXT>
