<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     10-26 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Leaders Condemn Tax Raids; Troops Kill Two Palestinians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of four major Christian
denominations in Jerusalem Thursday condemned Israeli tax raids on
a nearby Christian-Arab town and pledged food donations and prayers.
   Israeli security forces shot and killed two Palestinian youths
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and masked Arabs stabbed
to death a Palestinian nurse suspected of collaborating with
Israeli authorities.
   The latest deaths raised to 605 the number of Palestinians
killed by Israelis in the 22-month-old uprising against Israeli
rule of the occupied lands. Another 136 Palestinians have been
killed by fellow Arabs, most on suspicion of collaborating with
Israel. Forty Israelis also have died.
   The army announced Thursday that security forces uncovered two
``terrorist cells'' in the West Bank connected to Yasser Arafat's
Fatah faction of the PLO, including one that injured two Israeli
soldiers in firebomb attacks in Nablus.
   An army spokesman said those captured confessed to belonging to
Fatah during interrogation, but he refused to give further
information.
   The church leaders said in a statement that five weeks of tax
raids on the West Bank town of Beit Sahour were ``causing undue
suffering to the population.''
   The town of about 10,000 has been a hotbed of anti-Israeli
resistance during the Palestinian uprising and many there have
participated in the tax boycott called by uprising leaders.
   The statement on Beit Sahour was issued by the Greek Orthodox,
Roman Catholic and Armenian patriarchs and by the Franciscan
``custodian of the Holy Land.''
   They called for special prayer services Sunday and said they
would send food supplies and ``follow up the situation with all
appropriate means.'' They did not elaborate.
   A Palestinian-run human rights group charged that the tax raids
were aimed at intimidating Beit Sahour residents and often resulted
in the illegal seizure of property.
   Al Haq-Law in the Service of Man provided five case studies,
including alleged army confiscation of furniture from a family that
owed no taxes and the ransacking of a grocery store. Al Haq is
affiliated with the International Commission of Jurists in Geneva.
   Israeli newspapers have estimated more than $1 million worth of
furniture, machinery and merchandise has been confiscated in raids
in Beit Sahour since Sept. 20. Israeli officials say the property
will be sold to recover revenue.
   Olivier Rafowicz, spokesman for the military government in the
West Bank, said he could not comment on specific cases raised by Al
Haq because he had not seen the report.
   But he said that ``from the beginning it was a totally legally
based operation.'' He said residents who felt they were wronged
could appeal to the Israeli Supreme Court, but that no one in Beit
Sahour has done so.
   In violence related to the uprising, Israeli security forces
shot and killed two Palestinian youths, including 18-year-old Naeem
Karim Daamseh of the West Bank town of Bethlehem.
   The army said troops fired on Daamseh's car after he ran a
military roadblock and intentionally ran into a policeman. It said
the officer was hospitalized with minor injuries.
   In the Gaza Strip's Jabaliya refugee camp, 19-year-old Adel Abu
Salem was fatally shot by soldiers who fired on masked youths who
ignored calls to halt, the army said.
   Arab reporters said the soldiers suprised youths painting
anti-Israeli slogans by arriving in a civilian Mercedes car and out
of uniform. The army statement did not mention soldiers being in
civilian dress.
   In the Gaza Strip, five masked Palestinians entered Nasser
Hospital in the town of Khan Yunis and fatally stabbed a nurse,
Arab reports said. She was identified as Sawsan Al-Hussein, 25.
   The attackers scrawled on a hospital wall that she was
collaborating with Israel. The army confirmed the death and said
police were investigating.
</TEXT>
