<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Flag     10-26 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Flag,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Questions Constitutionality of New Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Thursday he has ``serious
doubts'' about the constitutionality of a law that takes effect
Saturday to outlaw the desecration of the American flag.
   In a written statement, Bush reiterated his belief that a
constitutional amendment is the only way to ensure that the flag is
protected.
   The law, which will take effect at one minute after midnight
Friday, provides a prison term of up to a year for anyone who
``knowingly mutilates, defaces, physically defiles, burns,
maintains on the floor or ground or tramples upon'' any U.S. flag.
   ``While I commend the intentions of those who voted for this
bill, I have serious doubts that it can withstand Supreme Court
review,'' Bush said.
   He said the Supreme Court has held ``that the government's
interest in preserving the flag as a symbol can never be compelling
enough to justify prohibiting flag desecration that is intended to
express a message. Since that is precisely the target of this
bill's prohibition, I suspect that any subsequent court challenge
will reach a similar conclusion.''
</TEXT>
