<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain in the West, Clear in the East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and snow fell Thursday in the Pacific Northwest, while much
of the East Coast basked in the sun.
   Showers produced three-quarters of an inch of rain at Astoria,
Ore., and snow fell over some of the higher elevations of
Washington and Oregon.
   A snow advisory was posted for Thursday night in the mountains
of southeastern Idaho.
   Sunny skies prevailed across most of the rest of the eastern
half of the nation.
   Snow and blowing snow advisories continued in effect for the
northern and central mountains of Colorado and Wyoming. High wind
watches also were posted, and up to 8 inches of snow were expected
overnight.
   A cold front crossing the central United States was beginning to
produce showers and thunderstorms in the northern and central
Plains. Strong thunderstorms were developing across parts of
Minnesota, Iowa, Nebraska and the Dakotas.
   Showers and thunderstorms were again over south-central Texas
and along the southern Atlantic coast.
   Sunny skies prevailed across most of the rest of the eastern
half of the nation after an early-morning fog descended on parts of
New York, Pennsylvania, Ohio and Michigan.
   Afternoon temperatures climbed into the 70s east of the Rockies,
in northern Minnesota and the upper Great Lakes, while highs in the
80s were reported in southern Texas and southern Florida.
   Readings were only in the 30s and 40s in Montana, Wyoming and
Colorado.
   The nation's low Thursday morning was 17 degrees at Truckee,
Calif.
