<FIRST>r w AM-Markets-Brady 1stLd-Writethru a0712 10-26 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Brady, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady Calls for SEC Market-Halting Power; SEC Chairman Resists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 16th graf pvs, Breeden was, with Breeden no comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas S. Brady said
Thursday that the Securities and Exchange Commission should have
the power to halt stock trading in market emergencies.
   Brady noted that SEC Chairman Richard C. Breeden said just a day
earlier that he doesn't want such authority.
   But the treasury secretary said the Bush administration backs
bills in Congress to strengthen the SEC in the belief that
government's initial response to market emergencies should come
``from a regulator with expertise and proximity to the markets.''
   Testifying before the Senate Banking Committee in support of the
legislation, Brady, who headed a government commission that
investigated Wall Street's 1987 crash, said the 190-point slide in
the Dow Jones industrial average on Oct. 13 had not altered his
belief in the soundness of the U.S. economy.
   But he said the ``tailspin'' did point up the need for changes
in market regulation.
   He supported legislation introduced by Sens. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., and John Heinz, R-Pa., to give the SEC emergency powers to
restrict or halt trading, a power vested now only in the president.
   Brady, in a letter accompanying his testimony, noted that the
legislation would give the president power to terminate SEC
emergency actions and would require presidential approval for any
trading halt lasting longer than 24 hours.
   He said the administration supports other provisions of the
legislation to:
   _Give the SEC authority to request reports on large securities
and options trades.
   _Set rules for regulators to use in assessing the financial
soundness of the parent holding companies of brokerage houses.
   _Provide for improved coordination in the clearing and settling
of market transactions.
   Legislation making the same changes, but with minor variations,
is also before the House.
   On Wednesday, Breeden told a House panel he supports the
legislation except for the provision giving the SEC the power to
halt trading in emergencies.
   Breeden said that safety mechanisms called circuit-breakers _
temporary automatic trading halts in times of market volatility _
have eliminated much of the need for officials to order trading
stopped.
   The SEC chairman said he also believes the possibility of
arbitrary halts could cause uncertainty and volatility in the
markets.
   Late in the day, Breeden said through a spokeswoman that he
would have no comment on Brady's testimony.
   The Brady commission, in a January 1988 report on the stock
market crash of the previous October, recommended that ``one agency
should coordinate'' all the financial markets. The recommendation
was not acted upon by the Reagan administration.
   But the treasury secretary said Thursday that, given the nature
of the various market regulators _ the SEC, the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission and the Federal Reserve Board _ ``I don't
believe that's a practical possibility.''
   ``Maybe that was something written naively by somebody outside
the government,'' Brady conceded. Noting that the report was issued
``some 60 days'' after the crash, he said, ``Perhaps we overreacted
to some extent.''
   Brady was non-committal about program trading, in which millions
of shares of stocks are traded almost instantaneously by
computerized systems used mainly by huge indstitutional investors
such as banks, mutual funds and pension funds.
   ``I don't have a view as to whether we ought to do anything
about program trading,'' Brady told Sen. Timothy E. Wirth, D-Colo..
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1923EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Senate-EasternStrike     10-26 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Eastern Strike,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Eastern Strike Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted Thursday 65-35 to approve
legislation that would create a commission to investigate the
Eastern Airlines strike, after debate in which Democrats challenged
President Bush's lack of efforts to settle the 8-month-old dispute.
   Thursday's vote followed a narrow Democratic vote earlier this
month to close debate on the bill.
   Fifty-five Democrats voted for the measure and none against. Ten
Republicans also supported it.
   The House already has passed a similar legislation and the House
and Senate will have to work out differences in the bills.
   Republicans had been delaying since shortly after the strike
began March 4. President Bush has refused to appoint an emergency
board, under provisions of the Railway Labor Act, to investigate
the strike.
   That refusal led to Democratic criticism Thursday of Bush's
handling of the strike. Some 30,000 machinists, flight attendants
and pilots have been out of work as a result.
   ``Mr. President, nobody is asking you to come down on the side
of the workers, the strikers,'' said Sen. Howard Metzenbaum,
D-Ohio. ``Nobody is asking you to come down on the side of
management.''
   Metzenbaum cited 34 previous occasions under which Democratic
and Republican presidents have appointed emergency boards, causing
settlement of 26 strikes without a work stoppage.
   ``But for some reason that I don't understand, this president is
reluctant to provide some leadership in bringing about a settlement
of the case,'' Metzenbaum said.
   Bush has said management and employees should resolve the
problem.
   Under the bill, a Democrat and a Republican from the House and
one each from the Senate would be appointed by their respective
leaders in Congress to the commission.
   The panel would make recommendations on how to settle the strike
and make further recommendations on maintaining competiveness in
the airline industry. The panel also would make recommendations on
how to protect employee collective bargaining rights in bankruptcy
proceedings involving air carriers.
   The report will be due in 45 days after enactment.
   Five days after the Eastern strike began, the company filed for
protection under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act. Eastern has been
continuing efforts to reorganize in bankruptcy court and the
airline has said it plans to emerge as a carrier two-thirds its
former size.
   Eastern was purchased by Frank Lorenzo in 1986, and he has been
accused by strikers and Senate Democrats of siphoning away
Eastern's cash and assets. He has been criticized for allegedly
draining the assets of other airlines as well.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said: ``We are delighted that
the Senate has approved this labor-supported proposal, which
provides a process that should lead to a fair and equitable
settlement of the Eastern Air Line strike. We urge the House accept
the Senate bill and the president to quickly sign it into law.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
