<DOCNO> AP891026-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1938EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Spain-Nuclear     10-26 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Nuclear,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plant Fire Most Serious Spanish Nuclear Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power plant fire a week ago was Spain's
worst nuclear accident since it introduced nuclear power in 1968,
but no radiation was leaked, the national Nuclear Safety Commission
said Thursday.
   A preliminary report by the commission said the fire at the
Vandellos I plant on the Mediterranean coast probably began when
excessive shaft vibration caused failure of a mount holding one of
the two turbine generators.
   No radiation was leaked during or after the accident and there
was no radiation risk to firemen, plant personnel or the public,
the report said.
   The plant, one of seven in Spain, went into service in 1972 at
Vandellos, a coastal town in Tarragona Province 90 miles south of
Barcelona, Spain's second-largest city.
   Although the accident caused no injuries, it prompted local and
national concern about plant safety and evacuation plans. The
commission said preliminary results of its investigation indicated
plant personnel acted correctly.
   Its report said vibration of the turbine shaft created a leak of
lubrication oil and damaged an attached electric generator, which
leaked hydrogen used to cool the generator.
   Contact between the hydrogen and oxygen in the air started the
fire, which fed on the leaking oil and spread through the
electrical production area below the turbines and next to the
concrete structure housing the nuclear reactor, the report said.
The reactor is a gas-cooled unit of French design.
   According to the commission, the fire began at 9:39 p.m Oct. 19
and was brought under control by plant and area firemen at 1:30
a.m. Oct. 20, but was not extinguished entirely until 3 a.m.
   The vibration also ruptured a pipeline carrying sea water to the
condenser in the turbine area, the commission reported. It said
water washed across the floor below the turbines and eventually
leaked into the basement area of the steel-and-concrete containment
structure around the reactor, affecting ``numerous plant systems.''
   It said the fire and flooding shut down two of the four
water-cooled pumps that propel cooling gas to the reactor, but said
the two remaining were enough to cool the reactor.
   ``The actions taken permitted the overcoming of the critical
situation provoked by the precariousness of the plant following the
fire and flooding,'' the report said.
   ``At this time any statement on the future of the plant would be
premature,'' the report said. The commission said it was preparing
a technical report on the circumstances and consequences of the
accident for the government.
   A consortium of the French utility Electricite de France and
several Spanish companies owns the plant, which has a cold-gas
reactor using natural uranium.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
