<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Attack 1stLd-Writethru a0744 10-26 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0744,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill British Soldier and 6-Month-Old Daughter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with name of soldier, age of infant,
that woman was soldier's wife and not seriously wounded as previously reported.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Tom King ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILDENRATH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen killed a British
soldier and his 6-month-old daughter near a Royal Air Force base
Thursday, officials said.
   British military authorities said the soldier's wife was driving
the family car at the time of the attack and was taken to a local
hospital in shock.
   ``As far as we know she was not otherwise hurt,'' a British Army
of the Rhine spokeswoman said in a telephone interview from
Moenchengladbach.
   Local police had said earlier the woman had been injured in the
attack near the Royal Air Force base at Wildenrath, close to the
border with The Netherlands.
   Hans-Juergen Foerster, spokesman for the federal prosecutor's
office in Karlsruhe, said authorities were ``pretty certain that
the attackers belong to the Irish Republican Army.''
   No one claimed responsibility, but the IRA has made similar
attacks on British soldiers in recent months.
   The British spokeswoman, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
identified the slain soldier as Royal Air Force Cpl. Maheshkumar
Islania, 34, whose parents live in London.
   The British army spokeswoman said the assailants opened fire
with automatic weapons as the family drove away from a gasoline
station that also has a fast-food bar.
   Foerster said the gunmen drove off in a van toward the Dutch
border.
   Tom King, the British defense secretary, expressed shock at
``this vicious murder.'' He said British military officials were
working closely with West German authorities on the investigation.
   Wildenrath is one of Britain's main air bases in West Germany.
   The Irish Republic Army, outlawed in Britain and Ireland,
claimed responsibility for the killing a British soldier's wife
Sept. 7 outside Dortmund. It said the woman, a West German, was
shot in the mistaken belief she was a British soldier.
   Since June, two car bombs have exploded in British military
housing areas in West Germany and one soldier was killed in an
attack in Hanover. A third bomb planted in a soldier's car was
found Aug. 28 and defused.
   The IRA, which seeks to drive the British from Northern Ireland
and unite the province with the Irish Republic, claimed
responsibility for the fatal attack and police suspect it in the
others.
   More than 66,000 British soldiers and their dependents are in
West Germany.
</TEXT>
