<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1945EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Marijuana-Raids 2ndLd-Writethru a0739 10-26 0878</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marijuana-Raids, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0739,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Agents Raid Stores Selling Marijuana Cultivation Supplies</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: TOPS with 5 grafs to update with new figures for Thursday's
action; notes that while 22 stores raided thus far, only 7 or 8 have been
seized; picks up 6th graf pvs: `The stores;'' INSERTS 10th graf: ``The
only,'' to update with 4 states where no raids were planned. FYI DEA says
it expects no more information to be available in Washington tonight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug agents staged dozens of raids nationwide
Thursday, arresting 119 people on charges of growing marijuana
indoors or selling equipment for it and seizing 65 indoor groves,
the Drug Enforcement Administration said.
   In addition, the agents raided 22 stores that sell the equipment
for the indoor marijuana growing, seizing and boarding up seven or
eight of them, said DEA spokesman Frank Shults, who provided the
figures as of early evening for the raids in Operation Green
Merchant.
   The DEA planned to raid a total of 65 commercial businesses in
22 states as well as more than 100 indoor cultivation locations in
46 states on Thursday. The raids continued into the night.
   A marijuana legalization advocate said the raids were just ``a
publicity stunt.''
   A law enforcement source, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said earlier in the day that federal agents had expected to make
only 100 arrests Thursday. In the previous month, 112 people had
been arrested in connection with the same investigation.
   The stores raided ``range from mom-and-pop to something
equivalent to a K-mart,'' said the source.
   ``We have established through the advertising and other means
that these stores do sell the indoor cultivation apparatus and give
advice about its use for the cultivation of marijuana,'' Shults
said. ``They openly do it.''
   The DEA used undercover agents in every store to determine
whether the owners knew the equipment _ such as lighting,
irrigation and ventilation apparatus _ was being used for indoor
marijuana cultivation, the source said.
   The stores were located in Alaska, Arizona, California,
Colorado, Georgia, Illinois, Kentucky, Massachusetts, Michigan,
Minnesota, Missouri, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma,
Oregon, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Texas, Virginia, Washington
and Wisconsin.
   The only four states where no raids were planned on indoor
cultivation sites were Hawaii, Nebraska, North Dakota and West
Virginia.
   Doug McVay of the National Organization for the Reform of
Marijuana Laws, said the raids on stores were ``a publicity stunt,
a largely ineffective one,'' and ``silly, really silly.''
   ``I can understand the DEA's frustration,'' McVay said. ``It's
true, some of this equipment is being used for (indoor marijuana)
cultivation. On the other hand, dirt is used for indoor
cultivation. I don't think we're going to stop people from selling
dirt.''
   An increasing number of U.S. marijuana growers have been moving
their plants indoors because of extensive aerial surveillance that
enables officials to spot drugs grown outside.
   In the past month, 112 people have been arrested on charges of
cultivating marijuana at 94 indoor growing locations containing
17,000 sinsemilla marijuana plants, according to Shults.
   ``We are trying to send the message to all those people in the
United States who have been cultivating marijuana that they are
violating the law, they will be caught, they will be prosecuted
and, if found guilty, they will serve time,'' said Shults.
   The raided stores ``specialize in the sale of these otherwise
legitimate products with the knowledge that they will be used to
cultivate marijuana,'' he said.
   A DEA statement said the agency has obtained ``the names and
addresses of thousands of individuals who are suspected of being
involved in the indoor cultivation of marijuana.''
   Steve Hager, editor of High Times magazine, said he believed
federal drug agents had subpoenaed the United Parcel Service
shipping records of the publication's advertisers ``and have been
using that information to build a conspiracy case of some kind.''
   ``I've been told that by people who have been visited by the
DEA,'' Hager said. ``They were told they (the agents) got their
names from UPS.''
   However, UPS spokesman Al Winnik said, ``There's no word here of
any subpoenas by DEA ... or any agency of that type.''
   The DEA would not comment except to say there was still an
``ongoing investigation.''
   McVay noted that legitimate manufacturers sell such items as
lights used for growing plants indoors and kits of indoor gardening
equipment, and that they can be bought at hardware stores.
   Shults said such companies were not targeted by the DEA, which
carried out the raids in coordination with state and local
officials.
   Domestic suppliers produce about 25 percent of the marijuana
consumed in the United States, while Colombia produces about 40
percent, Mexico 25 percent and other countries 10 percent,
according to government estimates.
   The DEA estimated that domestic production increased from 2,100
tons in 1986 to 4,350 to 4,850 tons in 1988. The National Drug
Control Strategy announced by President Bush in September called
for increasing federal funds for domestic marijuana eradication
from $8 million in fiscal 1989 to $16 million in the 1990 fiscal
year.
   A pound of sinsemilla _ the highly potent form of marijuana that
accounted for about 53 percent of the domestically eradicated
cannibis in 1988 _ costs $2,000 to $4,000, McVay said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
