<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1954EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-UPI     10-26 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-UPI,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Closes UPI Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Thursday ordered the
local office of United Press International closed and gave its
foreign correspondents 72 hours to leave the country.
   An order from the government and Justice Ministry delivered to
the UPI office said the U.S. news agency ``has systematically
violated journalistic ethics by the publication of false news with
the evident intention of discrediting the authorities of the
Republic of Panama and damaging the image of its leaders.''
   ``Despite (having this) called to its attention frequently,
United Press International (UPI) has not varied its conduct, and on
the contrary has accentuated its hostility to the national cause of
the people and government of Panama,'' the order said.
   Milt Capps, senior UPI vice president for corporate affairs,
said in Washington: ``The Panamanian government has in a written
communique to us today indicated they expect one of our staffers to
leave the country in the near future. We right now are pursuing
every avenue to contact government officials to attempt to resolve
this matter.
   ``We're confident that we will be able to continue to report
from Panama objectively and fully.''
   The government order canceled the registration of UPI
correspondents in Panama and gave its foreign personnel 72 hours to
leave the country.
   Chief correspondent Tomas Cupas, a Panamanian who has been with
the agency 27 years, was in Puerto Rico on Thursday. The other
correspondent, Elizabeth F. Lordan, an American citizen, has been
based in Panama for a year.
   UPI, formerly United Press, has had an office in Panama since
the 1930s.
   According to the Justice Ministry, the order was placed on the
door of the UPI office, which is in Cupas' home, as formal
notification, and the agency has two days from the time of the
posting to appeal.
   Luis Romero Villalobos, government director of communications
media, who signed the order, told The Associated Press the decision
was based on ``several cases'' of false information.
   ``It may be that the correspondent is not to blame as they say,
but that the editing desk changed the story,'' he said.
   The Government Ministry fined Lordan $1,500 in August for a
dispatch it said contained false information, and UPI executives
met with Panamanian authorities at the time. Villalobos said UPI
had not paid the fine because the ministry had not yet decided to
collect it.
   Lordan said that she was cited again for another story they said
was false. In both cases, the UPI central editing desk had included
statements made in the United States, not in Panama, she said.
   Government and Justice Minister Renato Pereira told reporters
UPI ``systematically has taken it upon itself to denigrate the
government of Panama and its national leadership. We require of
news agencies objectivity and respect for Panamanian legislation.''
   Asked whether the action was a warning to other news media,
Pereira said: ``It is not a warning, it is a reiteration of a
civilized policy of the Panamanian state, which, as any other
country, requires that its personality be respected, that it not be
denigrated, that what happens in its territory not be crudely
falsified.''
   The government has expelled three foreign correspondents since
1987, but this is the first time it has closed a news agency office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
