<FIRST>u w AM-MalariaIndictment     10-26 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaria Indictment,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Malaria Researcher Indicted For Lying On Grant Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chief of the Agency for
International Development's worldwide malaria research program was
indicted Thursday for allegedly lying about a grant proposal.
   Dr. James M. Erickson was accused of falsely stating in a
written report that a proposal by KT&amp;R Laboratories Inc. of St.
Paul, Minn., to devise a simple test for the disease had been
approved by a panel of outside experts.
   The indictment, returned by a federal grand jury in Alexandria,
Va., charged that Erickson, who was also chief of AID's
communicable disease division, knew that the proposal had not been
approved by the review panel.
   If convicted, Erickson could be sentenced to five years in
prison and fined up to $10,000
   The indictment sought by Justice Department prosecutors was
returned a week after the General Accounting Office found financial
irregularities and serious management problems in the malaria
program, which has an annual budget of $9 million.
   The GAO study of the project's operation between 1982 and 1987
found ``waste, fraud and abuse'' as well as ``questionable contract
and grant awards'' and ``inadequate financial management.''
   Without identifying him by name, the GAO report said that as
project manager Erickson ``had more influence than any other
individual over the direction and day-to-day management of the
malaria vaccine research project, and he initiated many of the
questionable actions.''
   The indictment did not specifically describe the KT&amp;R grant at
issue in the criminal case. But it appeared to refer to grant
referred to in the GAO report.
   The GAO report said that AID terminated a $736,801 grant KT&amp;R
after the agency ``found major deficiencies and unreasonably high
expenditures given the subproject's limited accomplishements.''
   In that case, Erickson falsely reported to superiors that the
grant proposal had received favorable reviews from an evaluation
panel. The GAO report also noted that Erickson had made similarly
false statements about an evaluation of a proposal by the
University of Illinois.
   The university received a $2.38 million contract for the
proposed research.
   Both cases were investigated by the inspector general's office
of AID, which referred the information to the Justice Department,
the GAO report said.
   In September, a prominent malaria researcher at the University
of Hawaii, Wasim Siddiqui, and his administrative assistant, Susan
Lofton, were charged by Hawaii authorities with stealing more than
$130,000 in AID research grants to the university.
   They were accused of diverting the money from the university to
help finance an international malaria conference held in Honolulu
in 1985.
</TEXT>
