<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-SAfrica     10-26 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-SAfrica,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Denies Swapping Missile Technology for SAfrican Uranium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Thursday
dismissed as ``pure lies'' a news report that Israel traded
ballistic missile technology to South Africa for uranium.
   However, a U.S. official in Washington said South Africa has
test-fired an intermediate-range ballistic missile built with
Israeli technology. The official said the missile could carry
nuclear missiles.
   In South Africa, Foreign Minister Pik Botha said he had no
knowledge of nuclear cooperation between the two countries.
   The Israeli Defense Ministry issued a statement saying, ``There
is no truth whatsoever ... on alleged links between Israel and
South Africa in the nuclear field.''
   The denials came in response to a Wednesday report on NBC-TV
News, which cited unidentified intelligence sources and a CIA
document. NBC's report said Israel provided missile technology to
South Africa in return for a continuous supply of uranium and use
of the Overberg long-range test site in South Africa.
   ``It's pure lies,'' Shamir told reporters at a political rally
in a Tel Aviv suburb. ``All this is baseless.''
   The official in Washington also said, however, that Israel and
South Africa are cooperating in the development of a long-range
missile that could be used to launch satellites.
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, the official said
intelligence reports showed South Africa had tested a modified
version of the Israeli-made Jericho II medium-range missile at
Armaston on the Indian Ocean coast last summer.
   The State Department and Pentagon refused to make formal
statements, but State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
said: ``Our ambassador in Israel has discussed similar reports in
the overall question of proliferation on a number of occasions with
Israel's Ministry of Defense.''
   Shimon Schiffer, a reporter for the Israeli daily Yediot
Ahronot, told Israel television there were reports from Washington
that the report was based on a leak intended to pressure the
government into accepting a U.S.-backed Middle East peace plan.
   Yair Tsaban, a left-wing legislator, demanded that the issue of
Israel's defense ties with South Africa be brought before
Parliament.
</TEXT>
