<FIRST>r i AM-Guatemala-Coup     10-26 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala-Coup,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Army Officers Sentenced in Failed Coup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civilian court on Thursday sentenced two
former army officers to seven years in prison for involvement in a
May 9 coup attempt against President Vinicio Cerezo.
   Both defendants had served prison sentences for their roles in
an earlier failed coup.
   The attempted overthrow this year of Cerezo's 3-year-old
civilian administration was headed by 21 army officers with support
from 300 troops.
   Former Col. Gustavo Adolfo Padilla Morales and former Maj.
Gustavo Adolfo Diaz Lopez were tried in civilian court because they
had been discharged from the armed forces after a May 11, 1988,
coup attempt.
   They were released from prison under a 1988 amnesty, which also
freed civilians accused of taking part in the failed coup earlier
that year.
   The defense lawyer, Edgar Arnoldo Lopez Straub, said his clients
will appeal the sentence of Judge Napoleon Gutierrez Vargas. They
were convicted Wednesday.
</TEXT>
