<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2009EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lawson 1stLd-Writethru a0675 10-26 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lawson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0886</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain's Treasury Chief, Thatcher Aide Both Quit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Walters resigning, details.
Pick up graf 4 pvs, `The financial...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's treasury chief,
Nigel Lawson, and her personal economic adviser both resigned
Thursday in a dramatic government upheaval during difficult
economic times.
   Lawson quit his Cabinet post as chancellor of the exchequer
saying he could not work for Mrs. Thatcher unless she dropped her
adviser, Sir Alan Walters.
   Walters, who was visiting the United States, resigned shortly
afterward.
   Mrs. Thatcher expressed ``the most profound regret'' after
Lawson's resignation but moved quickly to demonstrate stability by
replacing him with her foreign secretary, John Major. Home
Secretary Douglas Hurd became foreign secretary.
   No replacement was announced for Walters, and no other details
on the shakeup were immediately available.
   The financial markets were shaken by the news and the pound fell
3 cents against the dollar.
   Lawson, 57, had held the job since 1983, engineering tax cuts
and an economic recovery that won him Mrs. Thatcher's praise as one
of Britain's greatest chancellors.
   It was the first time since the 1986 resignation of Defense
Secretary Michael Heseltine that Mrs. Thatcher has had a senior
Cabinet official quit on her.
   Lawson and Thatcher appeared to be in close harmony as long as
the economic boom lasted, but when it began to falter 18 months
ago, reports of discord surfaced.
   They were said to disagree over the pound, with Lawson
advocating a managed exchange rate and Mrs. Thatcher insisting it
be controlled by market forces.
   Lawson also was thought to favor Britain joining the European
Monetary System, a mechanism for stabilizing exchange rates. Mrs.
Thatcher favors joining only after Britain's inflation rate moves
down and capital flows freely in Europe.
   Walters bluntly opposed joining the EMS, and has criticized
Lawson's policies.
   In his letter of resignation, Lawson wrote: ``The successful
conduct of economic policy is possible only if there is _ and is
seen to be _ full agreement between the prime minister and the
chancellor of the exchequer.
   ``Recent events have confirmed that this essential requirement
cannot be satisfied so long as Alan Walters remains your personal
economic adviser.''
   Mrs. Thatcher replied: ``You have been responsible for possibly
the most far-reaching reform of our tax structure this century, as
well as for a period of unprecedented growth and prosperity. It is
a matter of particular regret that you should decide to leave
before your task is complete.''
   She said: ``There is no difference in our basic economic
beliefs, and Britain's economy is vastly stronger.''
   Lawson, a former financial journalist, is a member of Parliament
whose career highlight was his 1988 budget, which slashed taxes for
the top income bracket from 60 percent to 40 percent.
   Plump and darkly handsome, he has a boyish, fun-loving manner
and is known to have complained that his government salary is too
low and that he would like to go into business. In July, he lost
his official country residence in what was seen as an unseemly
byproduct of a Cabinet reshuffle.
   Walters, a Johns Hopkins economist, is Mrs. Thatcher's appointee
and is sometimes referred to as her economic guru, one of the group
of free-market apostles who shaped Mrs. Thatcher's thinking in the
1970s.
   He was her adviser from 1981 to 1983, went back to Johns
Hopkins, and returned to a Downing Street post earlier this year in
what was seen as a slight to Lawson.
   On Tuesday night, Lawson publicly rebuked him, telling a TV
interviewer: ``I think it is right that advisers do not talk or
write in public.''
   Opposition Labor Party members, elated at the apparent disarray
in Conservative Party ranks, said Lawson must have made his
decision when Mrs. Thatcher failed to use a regular appearance in
Parliament to express absolute confidence in her chancellor.
   Labor leader Neil Kinnock said: ``When the prime minister failed
to give real support to Nigel Lawson this afternoon, he really
could not stay and it is entirely the prime minister's fault.''
   Mrs. Thatcher gave the job to Major just three months after she
lifted him out of political obscurity and made him foreign
secretary at the age of 46.
   Major is a former senior Treasury official. Born into a
blue-collar family with a father who was for a time a circus
trapeze artist, he represents the new breed of ``working-class
Tories'' who have flourished in the Thatcher decade.
   Major inherits an economy suffering from inflation of 7.6
percent, interest rates at an eight-year high of 15 percent, and a
trade deficit running at record levels this year.
   Labor is up to 10 points ahead of the Tories in opinion polls.
But elections need not be held until mid-1992, giving the new
Thatcher-Major team more than two years to head off a recession and
the threat of electoral defeat.
   Hurd, 59, has served as a junior minister in the Foreign Office,
and was Northern Ireland secretary before moving to the Home Office
in 1985. In Who's Who, he lists his recreation as writing
thrillers. He has written nine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
