<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Lebanon     10-26 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Lebanon,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Members to Visit Lebanon Despite Warnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of Congress planned to spend the
weekend in Beirut to meet with Lebanese Christian Gen. Michel Aoun,
despite warnings from the State Department that their lives could
be in danger.
   Reps. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, and Nick Rahall, D-W.Va., were
scheduled to leave Thursday night and return to Washington Sunday
afternoon, said Ambassador Clovis Maksoud, the Arab League envoy in
Washington.
   ``They are going to try and lend their moral support to the Arab
League efforts to bring peace to Lebanon,'' he said.
   The offices of both lawmakers declined any comment on the trip,
and it could not be confirmed that they had left.
   The State Department also declined to discuss the trip, but
noted that travel to Lebanon was banned for most Americans. Eight
Americans are being held hostage by Iranian-backed extremists there.
   The danger for Americans is compounded by the fact that the U.S.
Embassy evacuated all its personnel last month in response to
veiled threats of kidnapping by Aoun.
   ``There is no support we can provide for Americans there now,''
said one official. ``It's a very unsafe place, life-threatening.''
   But Maksoud insisted the two American lawmakers would be safe.
   ``It's not a problem,'' he said. Security is guaranteed in the
city by a committee of officers from several Arab League members,
including Algeria and Saudi Arabia, he said. ``Necessary measures
will be taken.''
   Aoun has rejected the plan for ending Lebanon's 14-year civil
war, saying it fails to set a deadline for the pullout of 40,000
Syrian troops sent into the country in 1976. The plan, worked out
by Christian and Moslem lawmakers after three weeks of
deliberations in Saudi Arabia, would shift control of the country's
political institutions from the Christian minority into the hands
of the Moslem majority.
   Oakar and Rahall, both of Lebanese descent, visited Lebanon in
1982 at the height of the fighting between Israeli, Syrian and
Lebanese troops to condemn the Israeli invasion of Lebanon.
   Ms. Oakar sought to travel to Beirut again in August but was
asked by the State Department to refrain from traveling to the
capital which was under intense artillery pressure from Syrian and
Lebanese Christian gunners.
</TEXT>
