<FIRST>u a AM-CocaineTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0813 10-26 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0813,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Convicted, Two Acquitted in `Son of Lehder' Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf with 2 grafs to UPDATE with prosecutor comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury convicted three men and
acquitted two others Thursday on charges they conspired with
Colombian drug kingpin Carlos Lehder Rivas to smuggle cocaine into
the United States.
   The jury reached its verdict after 18 hours of deliberation over
three days in the so-called ``Son of Lehder'' trial, which grew out
of testimony in last year's trial of Lehder. Lehder, 40, reputedly
one of the founders of the Medellin cocaine cartel, was convicted
and is serving a life prison term.
   The five defendants in the seven-week-long trial were accused of
conspiring with Lehder to either smuggle cocaine into the United
States or distribute it once it got there.
   Jack Carlton Reed, 59, was found guilty of conspiracy to
distribute cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise.
Reed was convicted last year on drug conspiracy charges and
sentenced to 15 years in prison.
   Prosecutors called Reed one of Lehder's chief lieutenants who
worked as Lehder's contact with Americans in the organization.
   Hyannis, Mass., attorney Barry Kane, 52, and Donald Lady, 41, of
Pomona, Calif., were both convicted of conspiracy to import
cocaine, but were found innocent of conspiracy to distribute
cocaine.
   Kane collapsed after U.S. District Judge John H. Moore II
formally pronounced him guilty, but was quickly revived.
   Reed, Kane and Lady face prison sentences of 10 years to life.
Moore ordered them held pending sentencing Jan. 12.
   According to the charges, Kane picked up 250 kilograms of
cocaine from cartel leader Pablo Escobar's ranch and flew it back
to the U.S. on two occasions in the summer of 1977.
   Lady was accused of acquiring a ranch in the Baja peninsula to
be used as a waystation for cocaine flights from Colombia in early
1987.
   Acquitted were Thomas H. Herington, 35, of Mill Valley, Calif.,
and Samuel T. Stewart, 53, of Anaheim,
   ``Justice prevailed,'' said Stewart, who was accused of flying
cocaine from Colombia to Norman's Cay in the summer of 1978, as he
left the courthouse following the 7-week-long trial. ``If it is any
consolation, I was innocent.''
   Stewart's attorney, Kevin Sanders, said the trial had damaged
his client's air-charter business as well as his health and
reputation.
   Herington, a student in engineering physics, refused to comment,
but his attorney, Patrick Hallinan of San Francisco said, ``It's a
great pleasure. He's very, very happy.''
   Herington, who was accused of transporting cocaine from Orlando
to California in a rented Lear jet in the late 1970s, had testified
he didn't know Lehder and had withdrawn from the conspiracy more
than five years ago. The statute of limitations for the crime is
five years.
   Raymond David, who represented Lady, said he couldn't understand
how his client could have been found guilty when others were
acquitted.
   ``It's inconsistent,'' David said. ``He was not very happy.''
   The prosecutor, Assistant U.S. Attorney Ernst Mueller, said
jurors had a difficult job sorting out the evidence. He also said
he wanted to prosecute all the cartel leaders in the indictment.
   ``It is our hope we can get Pablo Escobar, Gonzalo Rodriguez
Gacha, Jorge Ochoa, Fabio Ochoa and Gonzalo Mejia,'' he said,
naming several leaders. ``We feel we have the best case against
them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
