<DOCNO> AP891026-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Doughnuts     10-26 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Doughnuts,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>An Escape from Quake: Mock Court Settles Question on Doughnut Hole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After nine stressful days since the
earthquake, the audience was ready Thursday to look away from
nature's fury and consider what isn't there.
   The issue: Who invented the doughnut hole?
   ``Mankind, in its own wisdom, invented the hole in the
doughnut,'' Municipal Court Judge George T. Choppelas ruled after
an hour of hilarious legal outrage in the 59th session of the mock
San Francisco Court of Historical Review.
   So ruling, if meaninglessly, the judge shot down conflicting
opinions that the hole in the doughnut may have been the work of a
Dutch sea captain, a nearsighted Chinese baker 4,600 years ago, or
an Italian cook who took his eye off the pasta.
   The judge, a real jurist in a real courtroom, started the
whimsical proceedings on a serious note, telling a standing room
audience of 100 people that he had second thoughts about convening
the mock court because of the deadly terror of last week's
earthquake.
   ``We almost did cancel,'' Choppelas said. ``But this is a part
of a tradition of San Francisco. We do this for those who expect it
and enjoy it.''
   After all, he said, was this not the forum where has been
decided such weighty matters as: ``Where was the martini
invented?'' ``Is chicken soup Jewish penicillin?'' Who invented
spaghetti?'' and ``Did Albert Einstein have a fling with Marilyn
Monroe.''
   With that, the ``trial'' commenced, and attorney Frank Winston
said his opposing counsel had laryngitis and the case could be
settled without further ado. He was for the Dutch sea captain.
   ``I object,'' said San Francisco Supervisor Angela Alioto,
arguing that an Italian, inspired either by the Roman Coliseum or a
ciambella, a tire, invented the hole.
   Wearing kitchen duds, chef Jo Jung of the restaurant of the same
name took the stand to testify that an anonymous chef 46 centuries
ago was frying some dough and stuck a chopstick through it.
   ``That's where we get hole,'' Jung testified, whipping out a
package of Chinese dumplings he deftly impaled with a handy
chopstick. ``That how,'' he said trumphantly, offering a morsel to
the judge.
   ``Bribery!'' hollered Winston.
   After Choppelas threw Jung off the stand, Italian chef and
restaurateur Angelo Quaranta of the Allegro was called.
   ``Hah,'' he sneered. ``Jung is a cook. I am a chef.'' And he
hauled out his toque and planted it on his head.
   Jung leaped to his feet, Winston called for a bailiff and the
judge held his head.
   ``It was an Italian, I tell you,'' Quaranta testified
passionately as he was ejected from the witness chair.
   ``I object!'' yelled Jung.
   In the end, the Italian chef ordered a tray of his own doughnuts
handed around the courtroom, with napkins.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Fusion     10-26 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Say More Money Needed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Research scientists on Thursday criticized the
Energy Department's plans for greater competition for funds between
two different approaches toward harnessing fusion, the energy
source of the sun and stars.
   The researchers told a House panel they would like to see a
substantial increase, perhaps as much as a doubling, of government
support for both approaches, magnetic fusion and inertial
confinement fusion.
   ``A billion dollars a year to me does not seem like too much to
have an energy future,'' said Robert L. McCrory, director of the
Laboratory for Laser Energetics at the University of Rochester.
   For the current fiscal year that began Oct. 1, the department
has about $510 million for fusion research _ $340 million for
magnetic fusion and $170 for inertial confinement fusion.
   Fusion is the release of energy by the combination of certain
forms of hydrogen atoms to make helium. Enormous amounts of energy
are required to trigger the reaction.
   The magnetic approach uses powerful magnetic fields to compress
a superheated gas plasma whirling at high speed within a
doughnut-shaped apparatus known as a tokamak.
   The inertial confinement approach would fire laser or particle
beams at a pea-sized target to try to attain the extremely high
temperatures and pressures needed.
   In opening the hearing, Rep. Robert A. Roe, D-N.J., chairman of
the House Science investigations and oversight subcommittee, said
that ``fusion energy needs to be a central part of our energy
policy for the next century.''
   ``We should take the lead in developing for the world a
technology that will allow China to stop burning dirty coal, that
will remove the need for using the Amazon forest as a fuel source,
and that will save our atmosphere from pollution and warming,'' he
said.
   Earlier this month, Robert O. Hunter, director of the Energy
Department's Office of Energy Research, testified the department
favors a competition between magnetic and inertial confinement
fusion, with a winner to be selected early in the next century.
   However, McCrory said he was worried that such a competition
could be used as a pretext for shortchanging the effort to achieve
useful fusion energy.
   Erik Storm, deputy associate director for inertial confinement
fusion at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore,
Calif., said the two approaches to fusion ``should be complementary
and collaborative, rather than being in competition.''
   He predicted that ``very ambitious'' research and development
probably could produce prototype fusion plants by 2020, but without
substantial increases in spending it might take 30 to 50 years
longer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
