<FIRST>u w AM-GenericDrug     10-26 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Generic Drug,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Firm Pulls Antiobiotic From Pharmacy Shelves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bolar Pharmaceutical Co. has agreed to extend
a recall of an antibiotic used to treat urinary tract infections to
include drugstore shelves, the Food and Drug Administration said
Thursday.
   Bolar had agreed Oct. 6 to recall its generic nitrofurantoin
macrocrystalline antibiotic capsules from distributors and
wholesalers, but the FDA had said it wanted the drug removed from
pharmacies as well. The agency had said it would recommend legal
action if the company did not comply.
   The agency requested the recall because it said it had evidence
that Bolar substituted the brand name product _ Norwich Eaton's
Macrodantin _ for its own in tests required for FDA approval.
   The FDA said that while no safety problems were found with the
drug, the agency could not assure that it was therapeutically
equivalent to Macrodantin.
   In a letter to its customers Wednesday, Bolar requested they
extend the recall to the retail level.
   In addition to the recall request, the FDA is trying to revoke
the company's approval to sell the drug.
</TEXT>
