<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Elections     10-26 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Elections,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Observers Claim U.S. Interference in Nicaragua Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian observers of Nicaragua's election
preparations said Thursday that United States is doing everything
it can to disrupt the elections set for next year.
   ``American intervention continues as the main obstacle to the
attainment of free and fair elections in Nicaragua,'' the
Registration Observer Mission said in a report prepared after four
weeks in the Central American country.
   The group also said U.S.-backed Contra rebels were trying to
sabotage the elections set for Feb. 25. Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government has made the same charge.
   The four-man Canadian observer mission was sponsored by the
Committee for Peace and Democracy in Nicaragua, a group of
representatives of church, human rights and academic groups as well
as unions and development agencies.
   Its report said the U.S. government is disrupting the election
process by its continued support of Contra guerrillas and by
large-scale massive illegal financing of opposition groups and
parties.
   Robert Fox, who coordinated the observer mission, said the U.S.
actions are all part of a strategy to destabilize the election
process.
   The report said the U.S. government is spending millions of
dollars supporting the United National Opposition, an opposition
party, and other anti-government groups. It called the aid an
``intrusion on Nicaraguan sovereignty.''
   Earlier this month, President Bush signed a $9 million aid
package designed to support Nicaraguan opposition groups.
   The Bush administration wants to see President Daniel Ortega's
government voted out of office and contends that election
preparations unfairly benefit the Sandinistas.
   The elections come under a regional peace plan under which five
Central American presidents agreed to disband the Contras _ based
in neighboring Honduras _ by Dec. 8. In exchange, Ortega moved up
the election date from 1991 and promised free balloting.
   The Canadian observers said the Contras are ``waging a campaign
of intimidation with the clear message, `If you support the
(Sandinista government), we will be back to kill you.'''
   Contras killed 42 people last month in election violence, Fox
said.
   Last year, Washington cut off military aid to the Contras, but
it still supplies them with non-lethal aid.
</TEXT>
