<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SF-Quake-HighwayProbe     10-26 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF-Quake-Highway Probe,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov Appoints Caltech Prof to Head I-880 Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired engineering professor George
Housner will head Gov. George Deukmejian's investigation of the
Oakland freeway collapse, the governor's office announced Thursday.
   His short-lived predecessor, meanwhile, applauded the
appointment while offering his own theories on what might have
caused the collapse during the Oct. 17 earthquake that killed more
than three dozen motorists.
   Housner, professor emeritus at the California Institute of
Technology in Pasadena, ``is the elder statesman of earthquake
engineering in this country,'' said Ian Buckle, who occupied
Housner's post until Monday when Deukmejian decided he had
compromised his objectivity. The governor issued no comment on his
latest appointment other than to say his work ``must be fair,
objective, and complete.''
   ``George Housner certainly has the stature and therefore I would
expect him to do a good job,'' said Buckle, reached at his desk at
the National Center for Earthquake Engineering Research in Buffalo,
N.Y..
   Housner will head an unnamed panel of experts in the search for
reasons and circumstances behind the collapse of the 1.4-mile
elevated freeway. The performance of the state Department of
Transportation will fall under the panel's scrutiny, Deukmejian has
indicated.
   On Monday, Deukmejian said Buckle, also a noted earthquake
engineer, would be replaced after the governor learned that Buckle
had published an article the previous Thursday that, among other
things, defended the transportation department.
   Buckle, who served about four days, said Thursday that he
actually offered to resign after learning from transportation
Director Robert Best late Sunday that the governor had doubts
``about my objectivity.''
   Buckle, largely unreachable since last week, on Wednesday threw
his theories into the bubbling brew of what might have caused the
I-880 double-decker to collapse.
   ``First of all, I want to say that I believe there will be
surprises. There will be lessons to learn from this collapse. The
obvious thing is that the columns failed,'' said Buckle, who was
among the first experts to spend extensive time at the site. ``The
question is: did they fail first, or was it something else?'' he
said.
   Other factors, he said, could range from a theory advanced
Wednesday by Berkeley scientists that the base of the upper-deck
columns failed first, to a theory of unstable ground beneath, and a
lack of uniform rigidity along the length of the structure. ``We
have learned from the past that variations in rigidity can cause
problems in earthquakes,'' he said.
   As for the Berkeley scientists' theory, Buckle said, ``It makes
sense that where the thighbone connects to the shinbone, so to
speak, you're going to have problems. I would say that (theory)
probably is a good one.''
   In another development, Clayton Giroux, the designer of the
collapsed I-880, said he watched in horror as televised newscasts
showed the wreckage of what he had viewed as one of his greatest
engineering achievements.
   Giroux, 63, added: But he added, ``I don't have guilt over it,
just a strong sense of disappointment and tragedy.''
   ``Out of this will come learning similar to Sylmar (the 1971
earthquake in Southern California) and future lives will be
saved,'' Giroux said. ``Unfortunately, we only learn about
earthquakes from earthquakes.''
</TEXT>
