<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake--FreewayCollapse     10-26 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake--Freeway Collapse,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memo Noted Concern About Other Bay Area Freeways, But Not I-880</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials in August had enough
concern about the seismic weaknesses of three San Francisco Bay
area elevated freeways to seek expedited repairs.
   But the almost identical I-880 freeway, which collapsed in last
week's quake, wasn't mentioned, an internal memorandum shows. State
engineers have said several times since the collapse that they
firmly believed I-880 would not fall down in a quake.
   The memo, from James Gates, a structural engineer with the state
Transportation Department's special projects office, to engineer
Bill Jones, described extensive ``seismic retrofit'' work needed
for San Francisco's Embarcadero Freeway.
   The memo adds that San Francisco's I-280 Viaduct and its Central
Viaduct also ``are known to contain this vulnerable
configuration,'' and at the request of chief structural engineer
Jim Roberts, should also be added to the ``phase 2 retrofit
program'' along with the Embarcadero.
   All three structures were closed with extensive damage after
last week's 7.1-magnitude quake, but none collapsed like I-880,
also called the Nimitz Freeway.
   Roberts, asked to comment during Caltrans' daily press briefing
Thursday, said Gates ``may have written a memo ... I haven't seen
that memo,'' and added that much of it was ``not accurate.''
   He said that among the four Bay Area, double-decker freeways,
only the Embarcadero had been singled out for expedited seismic
strengthening.
   But according to Gates, the department performed a seismic study
on I-280 and the Central Viaduct. Roberts said again Thursday that
his department had not analyzed the Nimitz for earthquake strength
since 1977, when was fitted with cables to strengthen horizontal
decking against quakes. That 1977 analysis cannot be found, Roberts
said earlier this week.
   The Gates memo notes that the design of some vertical columns on
the upper deck of the Embarcadero create ``a potentially unstable
situation'' and need strengthening. The same condition exists on
I-280 and the Central Viaduct.
</TEXT>
