<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Refugees     10-26 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Refugees,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Group of Salvadoran Refugees Heads Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,200 of the 12,000
Salvadoran refugees in Honduras began returning home Wednesday as
part of a U.N.-sponsored program that refugees and their supporters
said had stalled.
   ``Everything is ready for them to go back home,'' said Ulrich
von Blumenthal, the U.N. High Commission for Refugees
representative in Tegucigalpa.
   His agency contracted for 41 buses and 150 trucks to carry the
refugees and their few belongings back to El Salvador.
   Blumenthal said the convoy probably would reach El Salvador
before dawn Thursday, traveling slowly over dangerous, dirt roads.
   The Salvadorans have been living in refugee camps operated by
the United Nations during the nearly 10-year-old civil war in their
homeland. Those returning first have been staying in a camp at Mesa
Grande, 35 miles from the Salvadoran border, 225 miles west of
Tegucigalpa.
   They included 189 refugees who abandoned the camp to make a
seven-mile protest march Oct. 16 to a small Roman Catholic church
in San Marcos de Ocotepeque.
   Spokesmen for the refugees said they protested to pressure the
United Nations into providing transportation for the return to El
Salvador.
   Blumenthal maintained the refugees moved because they did not
want to be caught by authorities who showed up later at Mesa Grande
to check documents. He said his commission does not aid the return
of undocumented refugees.
   About 20 members of the U.S. church group Going Home formed a
human chain around the San Marcos church to protect the refugees
from ``the repression and the aggressive attitude of the Honduran
army,'' they said in a communique.
   Blumenthal said the Honduran soldiers ``are there to facilitate
the repatriation.''
   Members of the church group say the U.N. commission opposed the
refugees' return because Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani
doesn't want them back.
   The Salvadoran armed forces say the leftist guerrillas of the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation front have converted Honduran
refugee camps into retreats for rebels and their families,
providing sanctuaries for rest from combat fatigue and recuperation
from injuries.
   The U.S. government, which has backed the Salvadoran government
against the Marxist insurgents, considers refugees to be rebel
sympathizers.
   Eugenio Castro, a spokesmen for the Salvadoran Foreign Ministry,
denied the church group's charge. ``The Salvadoran government has
demonstrated its willingness to receive refugees and will do it,''
he said.
   Blumenthal said the church group just wanted to politicize the
repatriation. The organization ``has made a series of stupid moves
and blocked the relocation of the Salvadorans,'' he said.
   Salvadoran Interior Secretary Enrique Ortiz Colindres said the
10,800 refugees remaining in Honduran camps will be repatriated
within two weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
