<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Peru-Rebels     10-26 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Peru-Rebels,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill Education Official, Nephew in Peru's Mountains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas shot to death an
Education Ministry official and his nephew in an Andean village,
police said Wednesday.
   The two were shot in Acobamba, 185 miles east of Lima, on
Monday. It took two days because of the remoteness of the village
for word of the killings to reach Huancayo, authorities said.
   Police said five rebels gunned down Jose Melgar, a local
education supervisor, and his nephew. The victims, who had been
visiting schools in the area, were members of the governing Aprista
party of President Alan Garcia.
   The guerrillas of the Shining Path movement have been battling
nine years to overthrow Peru's elected government. The group has
stepped up attacks recently to sabotage nationwide municipal
elections scheduled for Nov. 12.
   The government says about 15,000 people have died in rebel
violence since 1980.
</TEXT>
