<DOCNO> AP891026-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Aid     10-26 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Aid,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>France, Japan Offer Millions to Poland, Bonn Also Reported Ready</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France on Wednesday offered an emergency plan
supplying Poland's Solidarity-led government with nearly $645
million in aid, and Japan agreed to let Warsaw extend repayments on
nearly $400 million in loans.
   In addition, West Germany intends to offer more than $1 billion
in aid to Poland when Chancellor Helmut Kohl visits that country in
November, The New York Times reported.
   The aid plans were announced on a day of partisan debate in the
U.S. Congress over how much aid to provide Poland and Hungary,
which is also undergoing democratic reform.
   The French aid came at the urging of President Francois
Mitterrand. In a speech Wednesday to the European Parliament, he
also called on the West to take steps to help Eastern European
nations struggling to rebuild their economies after decades of
communist rule.
   His plan to help Poland would provide money over three years.
   It would create an investment fund, partly provided by financial
institutions, of $145 million to help modernize the Polish economy,
said a statement issued by the presidential palace.
   Another $322 million in commercial credits would be added to the
$161 million France had already decided to provide Poland this
year, the statement said.
   The plan also envisions a $14.5 million fund for technical
assistance.
   His proposals for Eastern Europe, outlined in the Parliament's
headquarters in Strasbourg, included a European Bank to finance
development projects and a European Foundation to train managers.
   The Japanese offer came in an agreement that lets Poland extend
its debt repayment schedule for about $396.5 million in loans, the
Foreign Ministry in Tokyo said Wednesday.
   A ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Poland's debts to Japan, which had been due Dec. 31, 1988, included
$336.6 million of export insurance paid by Japan to cover Poland's
failure to pay for its imports and $59.9 million in loans extended
by the Japan Export-Import Bank.
   Under the agreement, Poland will repay the debts and interest
over five years after a five-year grace period, the official said.
   The Times report in Thursday's editions quoted unidentified West
German officials as saying Kohl would arrive in Poland on Nov. 9
with an offer of more than $1 billion in aid to help Poland rebuild
its economy. It gave no details.
   In Washington, Republican and Democratic senators clashed
Wednesday on the magnitude of U.S. aid to Poland and Hungary.
   Democrats said President Bush should commit more money, but
Republicans counterattacked.
   ``When asked for dramatic new steps, the administration takes a
wait and see attitude,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
   ``We have to be very careful and pragmatic about what we propose
to do,'' said Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas. ``There
should not be a contest about how much money we can drag out of the
U.S. Treasury.''
   Under pressure to do more, Bush has expanded his aid proposal to
its current level of $451 million over three years.
   However, the House last week voted for an $840 million package
of grants and loans for the two countries.
   Senate Democrats are seeking passage of a proposal to authorize
a total $989 million in grants and loans over three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
