<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     10-26 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill 26 People; Six Officers Die in Landmine Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unidentified gunmen killed 26 people
and six policemen died in a landmine blast in separate incidents in
Sri Lanka, police said Wednesday.
   All the deaths were reported in the previous 24 hours and
occurred in central and southern Sri Lanka, where Sinhalese
radicals from the People's Liberation Front are fighting the
government.
   Police officials in Kandy, 55 miles northeast of Colombo, said
the bodies of 24 Sinhalese men, women and children were discovered
Wednesday in nearby Katugastota. The officials, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said they were killed in a raid Tuesday.
   Opposition politicians and human rights activists have blamed
government forces or pro-government vigilante groups for similar
killings. The government has repeatedly denied the charges of
retribution against suspected members of the People's Liberation
Front.
   Police blamed Sinhalese radicals for the slayings Tuesday of a
Buddhist monk and a Sinhalese school principal in Kandy.
   They also blamed the radicals for an attack Wednesday in which
six police officers were killed when the vehicle they were riding
in was hit by a mine in the central city of Baddula.
   The radicals accuse the government of making too many
concessions to the Tamil minority in the northeast. Police say
about 5,000 people have died in violence sponsored by the Sinhalese
radicals since the government and Tamils agreed to a peace plan in
1987.
   The Tamil insurrection began in 1983 and has left at least
11,000 dead, including 1,100 Indian soldiers who were deployed here
as a peacekeeping force as part of the 1987 pact with the Tamils.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. They
accuse Sinhalese of discriminating against them in jobs and
education.
</TEXT>
