<FIRST>r a AM-ZsaZsa-Jail 1stLd-Writethru a0798 10-26 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zsa Zsa-Jail, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0798,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zsa Zsa Won't Get Any Special Privileges In Jail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to include writethru designation. SUBS 7th graf,
`She did...,' to final graf to UPDATE with Miss Gabor's comments in television
show interview. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zsa Zsa Gabor, accustomed to a life of
entertainment and elegant gowns, can expect a lonely cell and a
cotton shift or pantsuit if she chooses to serve her 72-hour jail
term at the county women's jail.
   But she would get color television.
   Under the sentence handed down Tuesday by Beverly Hills
Municipal Court Judge Charles G. Rubin, the convicted cop-slapper
may choose any jail in Los Angeles County to complete her 72-hour
stay behind bars before Dec. 29.
   Miss Gabor said she was still upset about the sentence Wednesday.
   In a brief telephone interview with The Associated Press, Miss
Gabor said she was afraid of most reporters because one demanded to
see the age listed on her driver's license.
   ``I don't know why you all do this to me,'' she declared. ``I
was just trying to save the women of America,'' she said before
hanging up abruptly. The actress was in the middle of taping an
interview for the television program ``A Current Affair.''
   In that interview, Miss Gabor said the judge and prosecutor Ira
Reiner enjoyed the trial's circus-like publicity more than she did.
   ``They loved it. They milked it. I don't need it,'' she said.
``I'm a rich woman. I don't need these people, they needed me.''
   A jury convicted Miss Gabor on Sept. 29 of misdemeanor charges
of battery on a police officer, driving without a valid driver's
license and having an open container of alcohol in her car. The
former Hungarian beauty queen, believed to be in her mid-60s, was
acquitted of failing to obey an officer.
   The judge ordered also Miss Gabor to pay $12,937.50 in fines and
restitution and to perform 120 hours of community service in a
women's homeless shelter, where she may not talk about her case or
give interviews.
   ``It's nothing for me,'' she said of the community service
during the television interview. ``I do much more a year. I love
it.''
   The judge said her unrepentant attitude contributed to the
sentence. She faced a maximum of 18 months in jail.
   Miss Gabor also was ordered to be interviewed by a psychiatrist
and refrain from driving until she gets her real age on her
driver's license. During the trial, Miss Gabor claimed the license
was stolen and altered by someone else.
   ``Maybe I should have my head examined. He's right,'' Miss Gabor
told ``A Current Affair.'' ``If I tried to fight City Hall and the
Beverly Hills police, a woman should have her head examined.''
   Sybil Brand Institute, the county's jail for women, is probably
the institution best equipped to deal with a celebrity inmate such
as Miss Gabor, Sheriff Sherman Block said Wednesday.
   ``She will receive absolutely no special privileges here,'' said
Lt. Joe Surgent, in charge of operations for Sybil Brand, which has
an estimated 2,000 inmates.
   Such personalities as Patty Hearst have been held at Sybil Brand
and Cynthia Garvey, ex-wife of former baseball player Steve Garvey,
recently spent a night there for contempt in a child-custody
dispute.
   ``Anytime we have an inmate who is recognizable, we separate
them from the general population for their own safety,'' Surgent
said. ``People with that kind of notoriety can be preyed upon.''
   Miss Gabor would be alone when she eats, showers and even
watches television, except for when a deputy escorts her from her
cell to the shower area, he said.
   Block called Miss Gabor's ability to choose where she will serve
her sentence ``a perversion of the system.''
   If she chooses Sybil Brand, Miss Gabor will be booked, searched
and ordered to trade her clothes for a jail uniform, like any other
inmate, Surgent said Wednesday. She would be given an 8-by-10 foot
concrete jail cell furnished with a bed, sink and toilet, he said.
</TEXT>
