<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv26   10-26 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 26,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, Oct. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Staying Ahead of Tax Penalties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final date of reckoning may be more than
five months away, but many people are checking up now on the
income-tax bill they expect to owe Uncle Sam for 1989.
   Their purpose is simple: To avoid facing a penalty for
underpayment of estimated and withholding taxes when they file
their returns for the year.
   Ordinarily this isn't a big worry for people who get most or all
of their income from wages or salaries. The withholding tax
collected from each paycheck covers what they will owe.
   In fact, most individual tax returns that are filed each year
carry claims for refunds.
   But the penalty still lurks as a potential pitfall for anyone,
wealthy or not, who for one reason or another gets down to the
bottom line of the tax form with a significant unpaid balance.
   ``Withholding may not cover your tax,'' warns the J.K. Lasser
Institute in its annual guide ``Your Income Tax.''
   ``The withholding tax rate may be below your actual tax rate
when considering other income such as interest, dividends, business
income and capital gains.''
   There are specific rules to determine who must pay a penalty,
and who doesn't have to, when there is a balance owed to the
Internal Revenue Service at the end of a year.
   You are generally in the clear if your withholding, and any
estimated payments made on schedule, add up to at least 90 percent
of the tax owed, or if the shortfall is less than $500.
   Alternatively, no penalty is assessed if your payments made in
1989 at least equal the final amount of tax you owed for 1988,
provided you filed a 1988 return that covered a 12-month period.
   Similarly, you are exempt if you had no tax liability for 1988
and were living in the United States throughout that year.
   That gives you several yardsticks to use on your likely 1989 tax
bill, which should be relatively easy to estimate this late in the
year.
   The ``research'' may require nothing more than checking the
amount of year-to-date withholding from your latest paycheck stub
against the total tax on your return for last year.
   But suppose your payments still don't look as though they will
measure up. If you should have been making estimated payments, it
is probably too late to eliminate a penalty with an increased
quarterly payment for the last installment of the year, due in
January.
   There is another way to approach this problem, however. You can
narrow or close the gap by asking an employer to take increased
withholding taxes out of your last few paychecks of the year.
   Unlike quarterly estimated taxes, withholding tax is treated as
though it were paid in a steady stream through the year, unless you
choose to establish otherwise.
   ``Thus,'' notes the Research Institute of America, an
organization that collects and publishes tax information, ``if an
employee asks his employer to withhold extra large amounts for the
rest of the year, the penalty can be retroactively eliminated.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Oct. 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
