<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv27   10-26 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 27,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Oct. 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Religious television is most popular in a
city better known for politics than religion, and unpopular in the
city that is home to the headquarters of the Mormon Church,
according to a new study.
   Stephen Winzenburg, a communications professor at Grand View
College, said his analysis of A.C. Nielsen ratings revealed that 23
percent of household viewers in Washington watch religious
programming, while just 1.4 percent of Salt Lake City residents
tune in devotional shows.
   In his analysis of the top 100 television markets, the 10 cities
with the highest viewing levels of religious television were
Washington, Dallas, Atlanta, Houston, Sioux Falls, S.D.,
Birmingham, Ala., Nashville and Chattanooga, Tenn., Jackson, Miss.,
and Detroit.
   About 10 percent of the population in the average city watches
religious television, Winzenburg said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pittsburgh Presbytery of the Presbyterian
Church (U.S.A.) is considering a plan to consolidate congregations
because of membership losses.
   A presbytery report accompanying proposals for consolidation
said, ``It is projected that by the early part of the next century,
one-third of our congregations will no longer exist.''
   The presbytery, with 178 churches and 66,000 members in
Allegheny County, has lost 23,000 members during the past 10 years,
the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Catholic Telegraph, the Archdiocese of
Cincinnati's weekly newspaper, has sent 18,000 Roman Catholic
parishes nationwide a 32-page sample of a large-print tabloid
newspaper it plans for people who have trouble reading regular type.
   Editor James Stackpoole said the Telegraph will begin
circulating the large-type edition in January. The newspaper will
feature stories and editorials from national Catholic press
services, he said.
   The large-type paper is to be issued 24 times a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christmas has been declared a state holiday in
Lithuania for the first time since the small republic on the Baltic
Sea was absorbed by the Soviet Union in 1940.
   The Lithuanian Parliament recently decreed that Dec. 25 will be
a state holiday, the Soviet government's news agency Tass said.
   An estimated 3 million of Lithuania's 3.6 million people are
Roman Catholic.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DELAFIELD, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Margaret Towner, the first woman
in the United States to enter the Presbyterian clergy, is stepping
down from the pulpit some 33 years after her ordination made
history.
   Ms. Towner, 64, preached her last sermon on Oct. 22 to the
congregations of the Kettle Moraine Parish she has served since
1973. She plans to retire in Florida.
   Ms. Towner, who was ordained in 1956, said she will continue to
work on two national committees of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)
and will be in the pulpit occasionally after her retirement.
   Ms. Towner moved a short time after her ordination to Kalamazoo,
Mich., where she was an associate pastor for 12 years before moving
to the Kettle Moraine Parish. She was one of three pastors serving
six small congregations with a total of about 630 members.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some American Jewish organizations have
expressed concern about a proposed statement by three Roman
Catholic archbishops calling upon Israel to negotiate with
Palestinians over ``territory and sovereignty.''
   The Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith said the statement
drafted by Cardinal John O'Connor of New York, Archbishop Roger
Mahony of Los Angeles and Archbishop William Keeler of Baltimore in
effect calls for a Palestinian state.
   ``Hope for progress rests on getting the parties together
without predetermined results,'' the league said. ``To call for a
state forecloses options of which there are many, and injects a
proposal into the equation that Israel and the U.S. oppose.''
   A statement from the Synagogue Council of America said the
bishops' proposal ``prejudges what can only be achieved through the
process of negotiations, which is the domain of the political
entities rather than religious bodies.''
   Rabbi Alexander M. Schindler, president of the Union of American
Hebrew Congregations, the central body of Reform Judaism in North
America, also said the issue of Palestinian territorial and
political sovereignty ``should be left to the negotiating parties
themselves.''
   The bishops' statement, ``Toward Peace in the Middle East:
Problems and Principles,'' will be presented to the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops' fall meeting Nov. 6-9 in Baltimore.
</TEXT>
