<FIRST>r f PM-US-JapanBanks     10-26 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Japan Banks,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Leader Urges Caution on Takeovers by Japanese Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Banking Committee
has urged federal officials to use caution in permitting foreign
takeovers of banks.
   Rep. Henry Gonzalez, D-Texas, said Wednesday that foreign
interests control an estimated 21 percent of the U.S. banking
market. Financial experts say Japanese and other foreign banks are
poised to purchase additional U.S. banks.
   ``Before this happens, before it is too late, I would ask the
(Federal Reserve) to be cautious in permitting such takeovers
before we fully understand how our economy is affected by increased
foreign ownsership of U.S. banks and financial services firms,''
the banking chairman said.
   Gonzalez' statement was prepared for a hearing by his
Subcommittee on Domestic Monetary Policy. Alan Greenspan, chairman
of the Fed's board of governors, was the chief witnesss for the
hearing, called to discuss the Fed's traditional independence.
   Gonzalez said he was concerned the Fed has not been as sensitive
as some foreign competitors in enforcing the requirement that
foreign banks have the same opportunities as U.S. banks, with some
special regulations and requirements for the foreign banks.
   ``It is important that we have a better understanding of how
foreign banks affect the profitability of domestic banks as well as
how such presence affects the availability of credit to domestic
corporations and individuals,'' he said.
   In recent years, cash-rich Japanese banks have made significant
inroads in the U.S. market by adding and expanding their own branch
offices here, or buying into established financial units, from
banking to securities operations. In the largest such transaction
yet, Japan's Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank _ the world's biggest bank _
agreed last month to acquire a 60 percent interest in CIT Group,
the financial services unit of Manufacturers Hanover Corp., for
about $1.4 billion.
   Other recent major transactions have included the $750 million
acquisition of Union Bank by California First Bank last year and
Daiwa Bank Ltd.'s agreement to acquire the U.S. commercial banking
operations of Britain's Lloyds Bank PLC for about $200 million.
   Japanese-owned banks now reportedly account for nearly 20
percent of the banking business in California, while eight of the
10 largest foreign bank branches in New York are part of Japanese
banks.
   Japanese institutions make about 5 percent of all U.S. loans and
hold about 9 percent of U.S. banking assets, according to industry
estimates, and the figures are expected to grow in the next 18
months as Japanese banks try to remain competitive with each other.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
