<FIRST>r f PM-SEC-StockBaskets     10-26 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Stock Baskets,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Approves Trading in Stock Baskets for NY, Chicago Exchanges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Markets-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators have approved plans by the
New York Stock Exchange and Chicago Board Options Exchange to begin
trading a financial instrument known as a ``stock basket.''
   The Securities and Exchange Commission voted unanimously, 4-0,
Wednesday to approve trading in those two products as well as
allowing the Chicago-based Midwest Stock Exchange to establish an
after-hours, computerized trading session for transactions in
portfolios of securities.
   The New York product, to be known as the Exchange Stock
Portfolio, will allow large institutional investors, but not
individuals, to trade in ``baskets'' _ $5 million blocks of about
126,000 shares apiece _ of stocks reflecting the Standard &amp; Poor's
500 stock index.
   The Chicago product, also limited to institutional investors,
will permit trading in $1.6 million baskets based on the S&amp;P 100
Index and $1.73 million baskets based on the S&amp;P 500 Stock Price
Index.
   Both products were recommended in the wake of the October 1987
stock market crash as a means of reducing volatility in the markets
without cutting efficiency.
   The Chicago and New York stock baskets are different from two
hybrid financial instruments, developed earlier this year by the
Philadelphia Stock Exchange and the American Stock Exchange, also
known as stock baskets.
   Those ``baskets'' represented the S&amp;P Index itself rather than
the actual stocks that make up the index.
   For that reason, a federal appeals court in Chicago has ruled
the products are more like futures than securities and must be
regulated by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission.
   The court ordered the Philadelphia and American exchanges, which
received permission to trade their products from the SEC, to cease
trading until they receive approval from the CFTC.
   On Monday, the court turned down an appeal of its ruling.
   In the third item approved at the SEC's first open meeting since
Richard C. Breeden took over as chairman two weeks ago, the Midwest
Stock Exchange will be able to start a secondary trading session
from 4:30 p.m. to 6 p.m. EST for the execution of stock portfolio
trades using a new automated Portfolio Trading System.
   There is still one vacancy on the five-member SEC. Breeden was
the numerical replacement for Commissioner Charles Cox. No one has
been nominated by President Bush to fill the numerical vacancy left
by formr Chairman David Ruder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
