<FIRST>r f BC-ControlData     10-26 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Control Data,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Control Data to Sell Computer Maintenance Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. said Thursday it
has agreed to sell its 1,000-employee computer maintenance business
in the United States to Bell Atlantic Corp. of Philadelphia for an
undisclosed price.
   The sale, to be completed by the end of the year, involves
operations that service computers made by International Business
Machines Corp., Digital Equipment Corp. and others. Control Data is
retaining service operations for its own computers.
   Bell Atlantic will merge the Control Data operations with its
Pennsylvania-based Sorbus subsidiary, which has 2,200 employees.
Bell Atlantic is a regional Bell phone company with headquarters in
Philadelphia.
   ``We anticipate that a significant number of the Control Data
people will be integrated into Sorbus as a result of the sale. We
don't have an exact number,'' said Stacey Mironov, a Bell Atlantic
spokeswoman.
   Control Data said the computer maintenance business has been
profitable, but is being sold because it doesn't fit the new focus
of the company's computer business.
   Nancy Foltz, a Control Data spokeswoman, said, ``This was not
done to raise cash. It was done for strategic reasons.''
</TEXT>
