<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   10-26 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Markets Mixed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade as gains linked
to new export business were offset by harvest-related selling.
   The markets opened mostly higher on news that the Agriculture
Department had given the Soviet Union approval to buy up to 16
million metric tons of U.S. grain in the fiscal year that began
October 1. That's 4 million tons more than had previously been
approved.
   But traders said the increase had been widely anticipated, so
Wednesday's announcement prompted only a brief flurry of buying
that was quickly neutralized by harvest-related selling.
   The good fieldwork conditions that have prevailed in the Midwest
this week are expected to continue into the weekend, speeding new
supplies of corn and soybeans to market.
   ``The weather remains the most bearish influence here,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat futures were unchanged to 2\ cents lower
with the contract for December delivery at $4.03\ a bushel; corn
was \ cent to } cent higher with December at $2.43 a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 1 cent lower with December at $1.45 a bushel;
soybeans were 2{ cents lower to \ cent higher with November at
$5.66\ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle futures were .07 cent to .27 cent lower with
December at 75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .42
cent lower with October at 83 cents a pound; live hogs were .23
cent to .47 cent lower with December at 47.35 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .15 cent to .25 cent lower with February at 53.07
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
