<DOCNO> AP891026-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1327EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Avon     10-26 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Avon,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Posts Quarterly Earnings After Loss Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cosmetics company Avon Products Inc. on Thursday
reported a third-quarter profit of $34.6 million after losing money
a year earlier due to the cost of discontinuing some operations.
   Avon earned 46 cents a share in the three months ended Sept. 30
compared to a loss of $405.9 million, or $7.78 a share, in the
third 1988 quarter, when the company took a $425 million after-tax
charge for discontinued operations.
   Worldwide sales grew 8 percent in the third quarter to $785.1
million from $725.6 million a year earlier.
   James E. Preston, Avon's chairman and chief executive officer,
attributed the company's earnings growth to aggressive expense
reduction programs.
   The New York-based direct sales company implemented new cost
controls and speeded up the sales of certain holdings earlier this
year when it was facing unwanted takeover interest.
   Looked at geographically, Avon said its third-quarter direct
sales slipped a little in the United States, falling 2 percent,
while international sales grew 14 percent. Strong sales in Latin
America are compensating for a below-plan performance in the United
Kingdom and continental Europe, Avon said.
   Avon's retail fragrance division, comprising Giorgio Beverly
Hills and Parfums Stern, had a 41 percent increase in pre-tax
profit on a 35 percent sales gain. Avon has said that it is
exploring the sale of its retail business.
   For the first nine months of the year, Avon earned $80.3 milion,
or 97 cents a share, compared with a loss of $461.1 million, or
$7.20 a share, through the first three quarters of last year.
   Nine-month sales came to $2.27 billion, up 11 percent from the
prior year's $2.05 billion.
</TEXT>
