<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891026-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 0613EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv26 1stLd-Writethru 10-26 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 26, 1st Ld-Writethru,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, Oct. 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Putting Money Behind The Advice</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Janke's name in 8th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For several decades the National Association of
Investors Corp. has preached a conservative investment philosophy
through its member clubs and in manuals and a monthly magazine.
   Smart amateur investors, it advised, should be able on average
to double their money in five or six years in sound common stocks,
and do so without taking unusual risks or relying on costly
professional services.
   Stories are inspiring, but money talks. Asked what new service
the NAIC might offer members, it responded: A common stock mutual
fund. And so the NAIC Growth Fund has been formed. It will put the
philosophers on record.
   Closed end _ meaning individual holdings will be traded like a
stock rather than redeemed through the company _ shares will sell
for $10 each, minimum of 100, through The Allied Group, P.O. Box
10499, Des Moines, Iowa 50306.
   It isn't the first time an advisory service was talked into
direct action, because in some ways stocks are an ego game. You can
star; you can be a hero; you can show up the other fools; you can
be called a guru, a genius.
   In the not distant past, for instance, a popular economic
adviser thought a fund would be nice to publicize his services. He
formed one. He soon found, however, that an adviser can reverse his
position with a telephone call, but that it isn't so in the stock
market. He pulled out, a loser.
   Given time, the new NAIC fund isn't likely to be a loser so long
as it sticks to its philosophy, one that's been demonstrated again
and again but not always listened to in a market geared to
frenzied, sometimes mindless, trading.
   Thomas O'Hara and Kenneth Janke, the fund managers, believe in
patience. At any one time they might not look good, they say, but
over time they think they'll be able to outperform the market with
a low level of risk.
   Their criteria:
   Choose from companies whose sales-earnings have doubled every
five years, especially in the latest five; whose earnings on
invested capital are about the best in the industry; and whose
per-share prices are low by most standards.
   That too is the philosophy of the the association's 6,900
investment clubs and its 132,000 members. And, of course, it is
part of the philsophy of Janke's and O'Hara's own club, the
50-year-old Mutual Investment Club of Detroit.
   In those 50 years, investments of the Detroit club have doubled
on average in less than six years, based on compound annual growth
of 12.5 percent. That, O'Hara says, is 25 percent better than the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index.
   It was the Detroit club that supplied much of the founding
energy for the NAIC back in the 1940s. Since then the NAIC has
published a magazine, ``Better Investing,'' in which it recommends
a monthly stock for study.
   Going back over the records, it finds that these 12 stocks a
year have, on average, performed about the same, that is, close to
doubling every five years. The returns were poor in several years,
many of them in a row. But in good years they made up for the
losses. They even tripled values in one year.
   Not bad for non-professionals, further evidence that people
willing to work at the job can do well in a marketplace dominated
by professional traders.
   Although the new fund will have a professional adviser _
Seger-Elbekorg Inc., Birmingham, Mich. _ it won't deprive itself of
amateur opinion. At least two are on the board _ and both O'Hara
and Janke tend to identify as amateurs, although O`Hara once was a
governor of the New York Stock Exchange.
   Then there are volunteers. O'Hara, who is NAIC chairman _ Janke
is president _ relates how you're not likely to sit anywhere next
to an NAIC member who won't nudge you and tell you the story of a
good prospect.
   No, he said, they don't tell you about it because they want
others to invest and push up the price. That would be nice, of
course, but ``it's pride,'' says O'Hara.
   These people are intelligent, creative and wise, he says, and
they are proud of their discoveries. Like any hobbyist with a
consuming interest, they like to share. It's their bond with other
members.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, Oct. 26.</NOTE>
