<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-AutoWorkers     10-26 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Auto Workers,0304</SECOND>
<UNK>Ford Offers British Workers 8 Percent Raise For Coming Year</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Company Ltd. said Thursday it opened
contract talks by offering its hourly workers a 15 percent wage
increase over the course of two years, but the hike was rejected by
union leaders.
   A spokesman for the British operations of Ford Motor Co. said
33,000 manual workers at the company's 21 plants in Britain have
been offered an 8 percent increase in the first year and 7 percent
in the second.
   Charlie Whelan, an official of the Amalgamated Engineering Union
said, however, that Ford's offer has been rejected by union leaders
as ``totally unacceptable'' and therefore wouldn't be submitted to
the union membership for a vote.
   Negotiations are to resume negotiations on Nov. 6, said the Ford
spokesman, who wasn't identified.
   The settlement is being watched closely as a barometer of wage
inflation in the Britain.
   Annual wage increases are currently running at about 8.75
percent; overall inflation is about 7.6 percent. Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher has urged companies not to give in to wage
demands that would aggravate inflation.
   Unions earlier this month rejected Vauxhall Motors Ltd.'s offer
of a 9.1 percent raise, made as part of a two-year package that
also includes an increase in holidays. Vauxhall is a unit of
General Motors Corp.
   On Thursday, workers at Vauxhall's Ellesmere Port plant voted in
favor of a series of one-day strikes in support of their claim for
a 25 percent increase. The workers also voted for an overtime ban
at the factory in northwest England.
   The 4,300 hourly workers must vote to legally confirm the
planned action, part of a national campaign also affecting
Vauxhall's car factory and parts operation in Luton, north of
London.
</TEXT>
