<HEAD>Galoob's Profit, Sales Post Records</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Lewis Galoob Toys Inc. Thursday announced a 56 percent jump in
third-quarter earnings on a 52 percent sales gain.
   The company credited strong sales of its Micro Machines
miniature vehicles, Bouncin' Baby dolls and a few toys introduced
this year for its record results.
   Galoob earned $7.29 million, or 75 cents a share, in the three
months ended Sept. 30 _ the largest quarterly amount ever for the
company _ compared to $4.69 million, or 51 cents a share, a year
earlier. Sales reached a record $76.04 million, up from $50.05
million in 1988's third quarter.
   ``This record-setting quarter, coming on the heels of six
previous consecutive record quarters, demonstrates the success of
the company's strategic marketing position, as well as the
tremendous receptions given our products in the marketplace,'' said
David Galoob, president, chief executive and chairman.
   Micro Machines have been on Toy &amp; Hobby World magazine's monthly
hit parade of hot-selling toys consistently since April 1988. Toy
industry analysts say Galoob's sad-faced Lost and Found stuffed
animals, which cry tears when fed a bottle, could be a big seller
this Christmas.
   For the first nine months of the year, Galoob had more than a
three-fold income gain. It earned $14.39 million, or $1.49 a share,
compared to $3.31 million, or 36 cents a share, through three
quarters of last year.
   Nine-month sales were $169.65 million, up 80 percent from $94.46
million in the comparable 1988 period.
</TEXT>
