<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0312</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined broadly today, giving a
wary reception to the latest data on the pace of the economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 32.38 points to
2,620.90 by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by almost 3 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 395 up,
1,119 down and 415 unchanged.
   Before the opening the Commerce Department reported that the
gross national product grew at a 2.5 percent annual rate, after
adjustment for inflation, in the third quarter.
   That matched the increase posted for the second quarter and was
in line with, or slightly stronger than, advance estimates in the
financial world.
   But observers also said the report showed a buildup of
inventories that betokened continued problems for the manufacturing
sector of the economy, which has been struggling of late.
   They also noted worries about the outlook for corporate profits,
intensified by a series of disappointing reports from individual
companies in recent weeks.
   Compaq Computer fell 7] to 101\. Late Wednesday the company
reported a third-quarter earnings gain that came up short of
expectations, and anlysts also cited uncertainty over the company's
fourth-quarter prospects.
   Anheuser Busch lost } to 37} on top of a 4]-point drop
Wednesday, when the company posted a smaller-than-expected profit
increase for the third quarter and said it was planning a
price-cutting strategy for its beers.
   Philip Morris, whose Miller Brewing operation competes with
Busch, dropped 1{ to 42.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slumped 1.96 to 187.56. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 2.27 at 373.65.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 148.14 million shares with an
hour to go.
