<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-26 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Fall On Demand Slump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices dropped below $4 a bushel
for the first time in nearly a month Thursday on the Chicago Board
of Trade as traders weary of waiting for new export business took
profits.
   Other grain and soybean futures were narrowly mixed in listless
trading.
   A lack of new U.S. wheat sales to the Soviet Union was the
biggest bearish factor in Thursday's market, said Katharina Zimmer,
a grain analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc. in New York.
   ``They apparently have picked up Canadian wheat and wheat from
England, and the market is just tired of waiting,'' she said.
   The Agriculture Department announced late Wednesday it had given
the Soviets approval to buy an additional 4 million metric tons of
grain in the fiscal year that began Oct. 1, raising the ceiling to
16 million tons.
   But traders said the announcement had been expected, which
limited its market impact, and Ms. Zimmer said recent purchases of
feed grains have packed the Soviet grain pipeline.
   ``Nobody expects the Russians to be back tomorrow to buy more
corn _ or wheat for that matter,'' she said.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1} cents to 6} cents lower with
the contract for delivery in December at $3.98} a bushel; corn
futures were } cent to 1} cents higher with December at $2.44 a
bushel; oats were \ cent lower to { cent higher with December at
$1.45} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to } cent higher with
November at $5.66{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
