<DOCNO> AP891026-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1609EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-Electronics     10-26 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Electronics,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Huge Gains At Four Large Japanese Electronics Makers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of Japan's largest electronics makers reported
sharply higher earnings Thursday for the first half of the fiscal
year, reflecting rapid growth in their automation and information
processing businesses and a boom in capital investment in the
country.
   Mitsubishi Electric Corp. said earnings rose 84.6 percent in the
six months ended Sept. 30 to 25.127 billion yen or $176.95 million,
vs. 13.615 billion yen in the year-earlier period. Earnings per
share rose to 11.79 yen from 6.47 yen. Sales totaled 1,151.110
billion yen, a 12.3 percent rise.
   Japanese companies report their earnings every six months.
   Mitsubishi said sales were particularly strong in its
communication equipment and semiconductor businesses.
   Toshiba Corp. reported similarly large gains, with earnings
rising 47 percent to 48.844 billion yen or $343.79 million from
33.236 billion yen a year earlier. Earnings per share rose to 15.53
yen from 10.90 yen.
   Sales rose 8.1 percent to 1,463.439 billion yen from 1,354.314
billion yen a year earlier. The sales and earnings figures were
records for the first half of the year.
   Sales of laptop computers and other office automation equipement
were primarily responsible for the large earnings gain, the company
said.
   Victor Co. of Japan Ltd., also known as JVC, reported earnings
rose 16 percent to 6.866 billion yen or $48.35 million from 5.937
billion yen a year earlier. Earnings per share weren't reported
because the company is a unit of Matsushita Electric Industrial Co.
   JVC reported a 3 percent decline in sales to 300.666 billion yen
from 308.922 billion yen, partly because of price declines due to
intense competition among consumer electronics makers.
   Hitachi Ltd. said first-half earnings rose 22.2 percent to
55.508 billion yen or $390 million from 45.438 billion yen, largely
because of strong gains in heavy equipment and information
processing sales. Earnings per share rose to 18.20 yen from 15.18
yen. Sales rose 11.9 percent to 1,770.780 billion yen.
   Dollar equivalents are based on an exchange rate of 142 yen to
the dollar.
</TEXT>
