<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2136EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BellCuts     10-26 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bell Cuts,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan Bell Trims Jobs to Meet Competition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan Bell said Thursday it will cut roughly a
fifth of its management staff as it reorganizes to fight
competition in the telephone business it once monopolized.
   The company, serving about 3.2 million Michigan telephone
customers, wants to trim its white-collar workforce of 4,200 by
about 850, President Kenneth E. Millard said.
   Total employment at Michigan Bell is about 17,700, down from
more than 19,300 two years ago. Cuts in other areas may be
considered later, spokesman Greg Gordon said.
   For now, the company is offering incentives to lure workers into
early retirement.
   Competition authorized since January 1988 for long-distance and
WATS (wide area telephone service) business will cost Michigan Bell
an estimated $120 million by the end of 1990, including loss of
about 10 percent of its long-distance market and 30 percent of its
WATS line market, Millard said.
   ``Like other deregulating industries, we're taking steps to make
the transition to a non-monopoly, competitive business
environment,'' Millard said. Michigan Bell reported net income of
$316.8 million on revenues of $2.46 billion in 1988, compared with
$307.9 million on revenues of $2.34 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
