<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FedEx-Union     10-26 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fed Ex-Union,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Express Pilots Reject Union Representation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Express Corp. pilots on Thursday
voted down union representation, delivering a blow to the Air Line
Pilots Association.
   The rejection stopped the major move to organize workers at
Federal Express, the world's largest small-package delivery company
with 80,000 employees worldwide.
   ``It underscores the fact that ... the pilots, still have a
great deal of confidence in (Federal Express president) Fred Smith
and the management team,'' said David Guthrie, a market analyst
with Morgan Keegan &amp; Co. in Memphis.
   Ballots counted by the National Mediation Board showed that of
the 2,022 Federal Express pilots eligible to vote, 709 cast their
ballots for ALPA, said Joe Anderson, a board spokesman. Ballots
were mailed in over a six-week period.
   Pilots who did not cast ballots in effect voted against the
union, Anderson said.
   ``I undertand ... they had a lot of ballot-burning parties,'' he
said.
   Anderson said the union filed a petition alleging improper
company interference with the election, and the complaint will be
investigated.
   John Mazor, an ALPA spokesman, refused to elaboarate on charges
of interference and declined to discuss the vote.
   The vote was sparked by Federal Express' $880 million purchase
earlier this year of Tiger International Inc., the parent of Flying
Tigers Inc., a cargo airline heavily involved in overseas business.
   Pilots with Flying Tigers were represented by ALPA, while pilots
with Federal Express were not. The merger raised questions about
seniority lists for pilots and other employment issues, pro-union
pilots said.
   In a statement, ALPA said it would continue meeting with Federal
Express pilots.
</TEXT>
