<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     10-26 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hit New Record, Third Straight Weekly All-Time High</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 476 money market mutual
funds rose by $1.26 billion in the latest week to a new record of
$357.49 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday broke the
record set the previous week and marked the third straight weekly
all-time high for fund assets, the Washington-based mutual trade
fund group said.
   The previous record also was revised upward by the institute to
$356.23 billion from the $356.10 billion originally reported.
   The institute said that in the latest week, assets of 236
general purpose funds rose $300.10 million to $116.91 billion,
assets of 96 broker-dealer funds increased $1.72 billion to $155.76
billion, and assets of 144 institutional funds declined $751.4
million to $84.82 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.14 percent from 8.21 percent the
previous week, said Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade journal
based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.22 percent from 8.26 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
40 days, up from 38 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual
yield available on money market accounts fell to 6.40 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.41 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, fell to 5.09 percent from 5.10 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.20
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.22 the
previous week. Yields were 8.24 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
8.26 percent; 8.17 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.18 percent;
and 8.15 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.16 percent.
</TEXT>
