<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   10-26 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market sustained a broad loss Thursday
in selling attributed to increasing concern over the outlook for
corporate earnings.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 39.55 to 2,613.73,
bringing its drop over the last four sessions to 75.41 points.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 11 to 4 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
406 up, 1,141 down and 410 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 175.24 million
shares, against 155.65 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 204.16 million shares.
   Before the opening the Commerce Department reported that the
gross national product grew at a 2.5 percent annual rate, after
adjustment for inflation, in the third quarter.
   That matched the increase posted for the second quarter and was
in line with, or slightly stronger than, advance estimates in the
financial world.
   But observers also said the report showed a buildup of
inventories that betokened continued problems for the manufacturing
sector of the economy, which has been struggling of late.
   In addition also noted worries about corporate profits,
intensified by a series of disappointing reports from individual
companies in recent weeks.
   A tally of the latest quarterly reports from some 430 companies
by Prudential-Bache Securities through the end of last week led the
firm to conclude that ``so far we're looking at a very
disappointing quarter.
   ``Almost twice as many companies have reported negative
surprises as positive surprises,'' said Melissa Brown, a
Prudential-Bache analyst.
   Compaq Computer fell 8| to 100. Late Wednesday the company
reported a third-quarter earnings gain that came up short of
expectations, and anlysts also cited uncertainty over the company's
fourth-quarter prospects.
   Anheuser Busch lost { to 38 on top of a 4]-point drop Wednesday,
when the company posted a smaller-than-expected profit increase for
the third quarter and said it was planning a price-cutting strategy
for its beers.
   Philip Morris, whose Miller Brewing operation competes with
Busch, dropped 1~ to 41|.
   In the auto group, where operating earnings for the third
quarter were lower at all of the Big Three domestic manufacturers,
General Motors slipped { to 44]; Ford Motor ] to 47{, and Chrysler
] at 22\.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $40.47 billion, or 1.21
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 2.30 to 187.22.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 5.73 to 385.19, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was down 4.57 at 337.93.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
slumped 4.74 to 458.15. On the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 373.48, down 2.44.
