<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-26 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher in U.S.; Gold Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against most major currencies
in U.S. trading Thursday, particularly the British pound, which
plunged after the country's Treasury chief announced his
resignation.
   Gold prices rose. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery settled at $372.50 a troy ounce, up
$3.40 from Wednesday. The Republic National Bank of New York quoted
an ounce of gold at $371.10 as of 4 p.m. EDT, $2.60 higher than
Wednesday's late bid.
   Currency dealers unloaded sterling and bought dollars and West
German marks following news of Nigel Lawson's decision to leave
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Cabinet.
   Lawson, who had served as chancellor of the exchequer since
1983, said he was resigning because of differences with the prime
minister's economic adviser, Sir Alan Walters.
   The pound, which had been quoted at $1.6130 when most trading
ended in London, sank to $1.5995 on the few European markets still
open after Lawson's sudden announcement. Later, in New York,
sterling fetched $1.5780, down sharply from $1.6143 on Wednesday.
   Central banks, including the Federal Reserve, reportedly bought
sterling to cushion its collapse, dealers said.
   Even though the British government quickly appointed a
replacement for Lawson, sterling was expected to remain under
pressure with financial markets questioning the stability of
Britain's economic policies.
   Lawson recently had been stressing the importance of a firm
pound as part of the government's fight against inflation.
   Mrs. Thatcher announced that her foreign secretary, John Major,
would take over at the Treasury.
   John McCarthy, chief dealer at the New York office of the
Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank, said apart from the impact of the
sterling selloff, the dollar did not do much during most of the
session.
   ``We were having a rather quiet day'' until word came of
Lawson's resignation, said McCarthy, noting that a report on U.S.
economic growth elicited little response from traders.
   The report that the economy grew at a 2.5 percent annual rate in
the third quarter was consistent with market expectations. The
Commerce Department's reading on the gross national product, the
broadest gauge of economic health, matched the second-quarter
increase.
   The dollar began its trading day in Tokyo by rising to a closing
level of 141.90 yen, up 0.35 yen from late Wednesday. Later in
London, the dollar traded at 141.58 yen. The dollar ended New York
trading at 142.125 yen, up from 141.57 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
quotes, included: 1.8410 West German marks, up from 1.8350; 1.6115
Swiss francs, up from 1.6075; 6.2545 French francs, up from 6.2270;
1.17545 Canadian dollars, unchanged; and 1,351.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,345.00.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates were: 1.8390 West German marks, down from 1.8410;
1.6085 Swiss francs, down from 1.6229; 6.2455 French francs, down
from 6.2520; 2.0810 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0740; 1,347.75
Italian lire, down from 1,350.00; and, 1.1750 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1745.
   On precious metals markets abroad, gold traded at a late bid of
$369 a troy ounce in London, up from $368.25 bid late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, the metal dropped to a closing bid of $368.25 from
$368.70 bid late Wednesday.
   Gold in Hong Kong rose 11 cents to close at a bid of $368.70 per
troy ounce.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $5.13 a
troy ounce from $5.11 bid late Wednesday. On New York's Comex
silver bullion for current delivery rose to $5.194 an ounce from
Wednesday's settlement of $5.114.
</TEXT>
