<FIRST>u f AM-Exxon-NYC     10-26 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon-NYC,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Apple Sees Some Giants Leave, Some Stay</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Exxon Move Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The announcement Monday that Exxon Corp. is
moving its headquarters to Dallas raised anew the question of
whether costly, crowded New York can continue competing with the
rest of the country's offerings.
   Exxon was only the latest corporate giant to move elsewhere in
search of cheaper space.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. moved its headquarters to the Dallas-Ft.
Worth area in 1987, saving about $60 million a year in office and
administration expenses. Mobil Corp. that same year announced plans
to move its headquarters to Virginia over three years.
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. announced earlier this year that it was
moving 2,600 back-office jobs to New Jersey from Manhattan in 1992.
Bankers Trust New York Corp., PaineWebber Inc. and Donaldson Lufkin
&amp; Jenrette Inc. have moved thousands of jobs from New York to New
Jersey in the last four years.
   But city officials say the losses have been offset to an extent
and the city economy remains vibrant.
   RJR Nabisco Inc., for example, is moving its headquarters from
Atlanta to New York. Numerous other companies have been convinced _
by tax breaks and other incentives _ to stay put.
   ``No matter how you stack it up, we're a net winner,'' said
Stanley E. Grayson, deputy mayor for finance and economic
development, who said the city had gained 4,500 new companies in
the past 10 years.
   ``Although Exxon is certainly a major company in New York, in
the country and the world, the practical matter is they employed
300 people here,'' he said.
   ``If it was 30,000 jobs, it would be a lot more troubling,''
said Ray Horton, chairman of the Citizens Budget Commission and a
professor at the Graduate School of Business at Columbia University.
   New York's economy boomed for most of the 1980s, and although
the 1987 stock market crash slowed the economy the city shows net
job growth since then.
   ``The trend is that far more stay than actually leave,'' said
Claire Tallarico, spokeswoman for the Office for Economic
Development.
   ``People stay because this is the world's decision center. It is
the capital of commerce, the capital of communications, the capital
of banking,'' she said.
   The announcements in 1987 that Mobil Oil and J.C. Penney were
moving their headquarters out of the city gave the impression that
New York was losing its grip.
   When the National Broadcasting Co. threatened to move to New
Jersey the same year, the city offered $100 million in tax breaks
and other incentives that persuaded NBC to stay.
   Among the others that decided against moving jobs out of New
York in the past two years are Chase Manhattan, Drexel Burnham
Lambert, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, Shearson Lehman Hutton and
Citicorp.
   ``I would say that certainly any city that loses a corporate
headquarters ought to be worried about it, particularly when
they're moving from high-cost locations to low-cost locations,''
said Dennis J. Donovan, head of the business relocation division of
Moran, Stahl &amp; Boyer, a consulting firm.
   ``I would say it's not a trend. It was a trend in the late '60s,
early '70s, because the cost differentials were so staggering. ...
Again, I don't see it as a stampede or trend, but there are other
corporations that will consider leaving, and New York ought to do
everything it can to hold on to them,'' Donovan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
