<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1812EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Autos Bjt   10-26 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Autos, Bjt,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third-Quarter Earnings Tumble for Big Three</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Summertime sales incentives eroded the Big Three
automakers' third-quarter profits, which skidded a combined 27.3
percent from record levels a year ago, the companies reported
Thursday.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. each
said rebates and other inducements to lure buyers during the
July-September period were much costlier this year and were largely
responsible for the weakness.
   The combined earnings for the Big Three during the three-month
period was $1.33 billion on revenues of $56.92 billion. That
compared with an industry third-quarter record profit last year of
$1.83 billion on revenues of $56.48 billion.
   ``I don't think it was a real big surprise,'' said analyst Paul
Kleinaitis of Duff &amp; Phelps, a Chicago investment research concern.
   Boosting the Big Three's total profit figure was a one-time,
$309 million increase in Chrysler's profits stemming from the sale
of some of its stock in Mitsubishi Motors Corp. in Japan during the
quarter.
   If that stock sale were removed, Big Three quarterly profits
would be $1.02 billion, 44.2 percent below last year's level.
   GM's earnings fell 40 percent and Ford's income dropped 44.3
percent during the period. Chrysler's profits nearly tripled on the
strength of the Mitsubishi stock sale, but without that boost, the
company's earnings plummeted 80.4 percent.
   Once again, Ford and GM profits benefited from overseas
operations. Chrysler has few overseas operations. Ford Vice
President and Treasurer David McCammon said his company lost $37
million during the quarter domestically, mostly because of
incentives that averaged $800 a vehicle.
   GM spokesman Terry Sullivan and Chrysler spokesman Tom Houston
declined to say how much their companies spent on incentives.
   Sullivan also declined to give North American profit figures for
the third quarter, but said that so far this year, all major
segments of GM business are profitable.
   The size of the drop at Ford caused some anxiety among industry
analysts, largely because the automaker has been so successful in
making itself one of the most profitable companies in the world in
recent years.
   ``That is a little worse than I expected,'' Kleinaitis said of
the Ford decline. ``If Ford lost money, you can imagine that GM was
cleaned out.''
   Profit-sharing amounts for auto workers are based on a formula
rooted in North American earnings. Earlier this year, Ford workers
got about $2,800 each, Chrysler workers got checks for about $720
apiece and GM employees got about $265 each in profit-sharing based
on 1988 North American earnings.
   That's likely to change next spring when profit-sharing checks
for 1989 business are calculated.
   ``Profit sharing will be down for the U.S. workers and will be
down substantially,'' McCammon said. However he said the checks
still would be ``meaningful'' and more than those for GM or
Chrysler workers.
   GM, the nation's largest automaker, said it earned $516.9
million on revenue of $28.79 billion during the period this year,
compared with $859.2 million on revenue of $28.22 billion during
the same time last year.
   GM's profits could not be translated directly to a per-share
basis because of a complex system of ownership of GM common, Class
E and Class H stocks.
   For the first nine months of the year, GM reported earnings of
$3.52 billion, up 1.7 percent from profits of $3.46 billion in the
January-September period last year.
   GM's nine-month revenue totaled $95.57 billion, up from $91.21
billion a year ago.
   No. 2 Ford said it earned $477.1 million, or $1.03 per share of
common stock, during the third quarter this year, compared with
$856.3 million, or $1.78 a share, during the same time last year.
Revenue fell to $20.24 billion during the period this year from
$20.38 billion in the third quarter of 1988.
   For the first nine months of the year, Ford's earnings were down
15 percent to $3.52 billion, or $7.51 a share, from $4.14 billion,
or $8.53 a share. Revenue rose to $72 billion from $68.53 billion.
   Chrysler, the nation's third-largest automaker, said it earned
$331 million, or $1.42 a share, during the third quarter, compared
with $112.5 million, or 50 cents a share, during the July-September
period last year.
   Without the $309 million infusion from the Mitsubishi stock
sale, Chrysler's third-quarter profits would been $22 million, or
10 cents a share.
   Chrysler's $7.88 billion in revenue for the quarter matched its
revenue for the same period a year earlier.
   For the first nine months of the year, Chrysler's profits rose
15.8 percent to $714 million, or $3.06 a share, excluding profits
from the Mitsubishi sale. With the stock sale worked in, Chrysler's
nine-month profit rose 65.9 percent to $1.02 billion, or $4.38 a
share.
   Chrysler's revenue for the first nine months of this year rose
to $27.95 billion, up from revenue of $25.78 billion during the
same time last year.
   ``It's been a tough quarter,'' Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca
said.
</TEXT>
