<DOCNO> AP891026-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 1817EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-26 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Falls Below $4 On Export Dismay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices fell below $4 a bushel for the first time
in a month Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting
disappointment that a newly expanded Soviet grain deal contains no
incentives to boost wheat sales.
   Corn prices rose in Chicago while soybeans were mixed.
   On other futures markets, cocoa hit a new 16-year low; copper
fell and precious metals climbed as the stock market dropped nearly
40 points; stock-index futures plunged; energy futures were mostly
lower, and livestock and meat futures largely fell.
   Wheat futures settled 1} cents to 7 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $3.98{ a bushel, its lowest
settlement price since Sept. 28.
   Corn futures were } cent to 2{ cents higher with December at
$2.44} a bushel; oats were \ cent lower to { cent higher with
December at $1.45} a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents lower to } cent
higher with November at $5.66{ a bushel.
   The Agriculture Department announced late Wednesday it had given
the Soviet Union approval to buy an additional 4 million metric
tons of grain in the fiscal year that began Oct. 1, raising the
ceiling to 16 million tons.
   But the expanded deal does not require the Soviets to first
fulfill a 4 million-ton wheat purchase requirement contained in the
original program.
   The original deal also requires the Soviets to buy at least 4
million tons of corn but they have already exceeded that amount.
Soviet purchases of U.S. corn totaling 4 million tons were
announced last week alone.
   Meanwhile, the Russians have bought just 1.2 million tons of
wheat since June 1, said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``Corn is the commodity of choice,'' he said. ``And even though
they will buy 4 million wheat, it looks like that business will
come later rather than sooner.''
   Analyst Katharina Zimmer of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
said there were indications the Soviets recently bought wheat from
Canada and England. And with last week's corn purchases, she said,
the grain pipeline to Russia is full.
   ``Nobody expects the Russians to be back tomorrow to buy more
corn _ or wheat for that matter,'' she said.
   Cocoa futures plunged to new 16-year-lows on New York's Coffee,
Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange following news that Brazil, the world's
second-largest producer, was suspending a 10 percent tax on cocoa
exports. The move is likely to add more cocoa to an already
overburdened market.
   Cocoa settled $24 to $38 lower with December at $961 a ton.
   Copper futures sank to new 2{-month lows on New York's Commodity
Exchange as the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 39.55 points,
contributing to fears of a recession-related drop in copper demand.
   Copper settled .25 cent to 1.6 cents lower with December at
$1.142 a pound.
   The stock market's plunge also sent investors scurrying for the
perceived safety of precious metals. Gold futures settled $3.10 to
$3.60 higher on the Comex with December at $375.40 a troy ounce;
silver was 7.7 cents to 8.4 cents higher with December at $5.237 a
troy ounce.
   The selloff in stocks was reflected in stock-index futures
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for
December delivery of stocks tracked by the Standard &amp; Poor's 500
index settled 5.1 points lower at 339.55. The contract is worth
$500 a point.
   Stock-market jitters also got some of the blame for
significantly lower livestock and meat futures prices on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle settled .17 cent to .57 cent lower with December at
74.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .80 cent lower to .02 cent
higher with October at 83.07 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent
to .83 cent lower with December at 46.97 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .70 cent to .87 cent lower with February at 52.45
cents a pound.
   Energy futures worked lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange
amid a dearth of fresh suppy-and-demand developments.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 18 cents to 25 cents
lower with December at $19.38 a barrel; heating oil was .61 cent to
1.2 cents lower with November at 57.24 a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .24 cent lower to .23 cent higher with November at 53.63 cents
a gallon.
</TEXT>
