<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices ended mixed Thursday as
crude oil prices weakened for the fourth straight day mainly
because of internal market conditions of supply and demand.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the December contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
fell 24 cents to finish at $19.38 a barrel. Other contracts also
declined.
   Among refined oil products traded on the exchange, wholesale
heating oil also fell. The contract for November delivery lost 1.20
cents to close at 57.24 cents and the December contract dropped
1.11 cents to 57.56 cents a gallon.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for November rose 0.23 cent to end
at 53.63 cents a gallon while the December contract gained 0.07
cent to 52.85 cents.
   Analysts said the market's recent weakness was driven by
technical factors after an 11-week rise in prices.
   ``The uptrend was led by product prices and now the downward
move is also product led,'' said Michael Broder, energy trader with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Peter Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc., said that seasonal weakness also appeared to have hit
the market.
   ``Prices usually decline from about the second week in November
to December,'' Beutel said. ``It seems to be occurring early this
year.''
</TEXT>
