<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CollectiveBargaining     10-26 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Collective Bargaining,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Average Private Contract Wage Gains Put at 3.1 Percent Annually</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private-sector workers who got new contracts
through collective bargaining from January through September won
average annual wage increases of 3.1 percent compared to average
gains of 2.4 percent in their prior contracts, the Labor Department
said Thursday.
   The data covers contracts for 1.3 million workers negotiated in
the first nine months of the year. If the trend continues for the
final three months, 1989 would be the first year since 1981 in
which new contracts provide workers with better pay raises, on
average, than their prior contracts, the department said.
   The rebound in wage gains was attributed to the restoration of
prior concessions in several industries that were slumping earlier
in the decade, particularly the U.S. steel industry.
   Also, the Labor Department said wage increases given to workers
in the health care sector, particularly nurses, were outpacing the
gains provided in prior contracts. Competition for skilled workers
in that sector has pushed wages higher.
   The department's Bureau of Labor Statistics tracks collective
bargaining agreements affecting 6 million workers in bargaining
units of at least 1,000 employees.
   Contracts affecting an additional 903,000 workers in the private
sector are up for collective bargaining in the fourth quarter. More
than one-third of those workers are rail workers, the government
said.
   Most of the settlements reached in the first nine months of the
year, 81 percent covering 1 million of the 1.3 million workers,
were in non-manufacturing sectors. About one-third of those were in
the construction industry, where settlements called for average
annual wage increases of 3.0 percent. The settlements in the other
non-manufacturing sectors, primarily communications, food stores
and utilities, provided average annual pay hikes of 3.3 percent,
the government said.
   In manufacturing, a sector which has slumped most of the year,
the settlements provided lower wage adjustments, averaging 2.9
percent a year over the life of the new contracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
