<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Jaguar     10-26 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Jaguar,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Seeking Clearance to Buy up to 15 Percent of Jaguar</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Earns-Autos, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. is seeking U.S. regulatory
clearance to purchase up to 15 percent of Jaguar PLC, a GM
spokesman said Thursday.
   Jaguar, which wants to remain independent and faces a possible
takeover bid from Ford Motor Co., has been talking with GM about a
cooperation agreement that would involve GM, the world's biggest
auto maker, buying a minority stake in Jaguar.
   GM's filing for regulatory clearance was within the context of
those talks, sources said.
   The GM spokesman, reached in London, confirmed the company had
made a filing with the Federal Trade Commission, which must approve
major share acquisitions involving U.S. companies under the
Hart-Scott-Rodino Act.
   The spokesman declined to say when the filing was made, but
sources close to GM and Jaguar said it was sometime last week.
   Under U.S. regulations, a company may begin the intended stock
purchase if the FTC has raised no objection within 30 days.
   Until it receives FTC clearance, GM will be limited to buying no
more than $15 million worth of Jaguar shares.
   Ford said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission Monday it was prepared to bid for all outstanding Jaguar
stock when takeover restrictions are lifted at the end of 1990.
   Jaguar bylaws prevent any outside individual or company
acquiring more than 15 percent of its stock before Dec. 31, 1990.
   Ford announced Sept. 19 that it planned to acquire 15 percent of
Jaguar's stock, and received U.S. regulatory approval for the
purchase. By Tuesday, Ford had accumulated 12.45 percent of the
stock.
   Jaguar has called Ford's move unwelcome.
   Jaguar Chairman John Egan has said he hopes to announce a deal
with GM by mid-November.
</TEXT>
