<FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-89 2250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-LIN-McCaw     10-26 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LIN-McCaw,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Backs McCaw Effort to Acquire LIN Broadcasting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission upheld
on Thursday staff decisions granting the applications of McCaw
Cellular Communications Inc. to acquire control of LIN Broadcasting
Corp.
   On Aug. 31, the FCC's mass media and common carrier bureaus
granted McCaw's transfer applications and denied counter-petitions
filed by LIN and others who objected to the requests.
   The New York-based LIN, which has interests in cellular
telephones, television stations and specialty publishing, has
resisted McCaw's nearly five-month takeover effort and appealed the
bureaus' actions.
   The commission concluded that ``it should not engage in
comparisons of the transferee and transferor in determining whether
grant of the transfer will serve the public interest.''
   Further, the commission said hostile takeover cases should not
be considered differently than other transfer cases. The commission
also said it will not generally consider an applicant's level of
debt when assessing the applicant's financial qualifications.
   The commission said McCaw has demonstrated ``reasonable
assurance of acquisition financing from three prominent banks.''
   McCaw, which already owns 5.1 million on LIN's shares, has
offered $125 a share, or $2.75 billion, for an additional 22
million LIN shares. That would give McCaw about 50.3 percent of
LIN's stock.
   LIN's board has taken no position on the offer, but previously
agreed to merge its cellular operations with those of BellSouth
Corp., the regional telephone company based in Atlanta.
   The McCaw offer is scheduled to expire at midnight Friday.
</TEXT>
