<FIRST>u f AM-CompaqProblems     10-26 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Compaq Problems,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compaq Stock Plunges on Earnings, Chip Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock of Compaq Computer Corp. tumbled 8
percent Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange in response to a
disappointing earnings report and news of a problem with a critical
computer chip.
   The Houston-based personal computer maker said it uncovered two
minor flaws in the i486 microprocessor made by Intel Corp., which
will be the brains of a major new computer it is introducing next
month.
   Intel confirmed that two flaws had been discovered by a
customer, which it did not identify, and said it would begin
shipping a fixed version of the chip by the end of November.
   One flaw involves trigonometric functions and another involves a
feature that detects irregular operations such as attempting to
divide by zero. Both occur only under special conditions and would
not affect most users, according to Bill Rash, Intel's marketing
directorfor the i486.
   Compaq's stock fell $8.62{ to $100 a share on the NYSE in heavy
trading, while Intel's held up better, losing just 87{ cents to $32
a share in over-the-counter trading.
   Compaq reported Wednesday that its earnings jumped 51 percent in
the third quarter, but part of the increase came from a gain in the
carrying value of its investment in a disk-drive maker, Conner
Peripherals Inc. The earnings were at the low end of analysts'
expectations.
