<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Rorer     10-26 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Rorer,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rorer Reports Profit Up 29 Percent in 3rd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WASHINGTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pharmaceutical company Rorer
Group Inc. reported a 29 percent increase in its third-quarter
profit Wednesday, crediting a boost in sales of its Maalox antacid.
   Net income totaled $19.6 million, or 54 cents a share, compared
with $15.2 million, or 48 cents a share, a year ago. Sales for the
quarter totaled $260 million, up from $244 million.
   Operating income for the quarter declined by more than 44
percent, from $37.2 million to $20.8 million, but the drop was more
than offset by the sale of assets to finance an ad campaign for
Maalox.
   Gains from the assets sales totaled $23.3 million _ primarily
from the sale of Asilone, an over-the-counter antacid sold in
Britain, and Thrombinar, a topical hemostatic product sold in the
United States.
   ``Our strategic initiative seems to be working,'' said Robert E.
Cawthorn, Rorer's chairman and chief executive officer. ``For the
first time, quarterly sales of Maalox in the U.S. were higher than
in 1988.
   ``We chose to fund the `Maalox Moments' campaign by selling
minor products whose proceeds will deliver a higher return invested
in Maalox.''
   For the first nine months of 1989, the company had net income of
$41.7 million, or $1.26 per share, compared with $34.9 million, or
$1.10 per share, in the 1988 period. Sales totaled $778 million, up
from $716 million in the first three quarters of 1988.
</TEXT>
