<FIRST>r f BC-TelerateAd     10-26 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Telerate Ad,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telerate Pulled Ad That Criticized Its Majority Owner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Telerate Inc., the financial data company,
planned to run an ad in The Wall Street Journal that criticized Dow
Jones &amp; Co., which owns two-thirds of Telerate's stock and
publishes the Journal. But the ad was pulled before it appeared in
print.
   The conflict between the companies stems from an offer by Dow
Jones to buy the shares of Telerate it doesn't own for what
Telerate called ``the low-ball price of $18 per share.''
   Telerate's management owns about 7 percent of the company's
stock; the remaining 26 percent is publicly held.
   Hours after people close to the Telerate board circulated copies
of the ad and said it had been submitted to the newspaper, the ad
was withdrawn, The New York Times reported in its Thursday editions.
   A person close to Telerate confirmed that the company withdrew
the ad but declined to say why, the Times reported.
   Roger B. May, a Dow Jones spokesman, said, ``It is Dow Jones'
understanding that the ad will not run, and that Telerate has
chosen not to run the ad at this time.''
   The ad, signed by Telerate's chief executive, urged shareholders
not to sell their stock to Dow Jones.
   Telerate has been resisting the bid for its remaining stock
since it was announced Sept. 20. Dow Jones has repeatedly described
the offer as fair.
   Telerate provides computer screens used in brokerage houses that
show stock transactions, oil prices, bond trading and a host of
other financial information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
